{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"989e5532c602477c9589794efd9253a409f330ef04330d0472adbb55e91eb4cd","verdict":"REVISE","rawOutput":"The change is close, but not sound as-is.\n\nThe durable dedup key is `review-<epoch>-<short-sha>` in [self-review-source.ts](/Users/Andrew/ai-blockchain/code/src/self-review-source.ts:31), and `sourceSelfReview` treats that ID as the proof a commit was already reviewed via `hasBallot` in [self-review-source.ts](/Users/Andrew/ai-blockchain/code/src/self-review-source.ts:47). But the code’s claim says the SHA suffix makes the ID “unique” in [self-review-source.ts](/Users/Andrew/ai-blockchain/code/src/self-review-source.ts:28), while it only uses 12 hex characters. Two distinct commits with the same committer epoch second and same 12-char prefix collide, causing the later commit to be silently skipped as “already reviewed.” That violates the stated “at most once per commit” behavior and weakens no-laundering/tamper-evidence because an adversarial commit can suppress its own review.\n\nFix is narrow: key the durable ballot ID by the full commit SHA, or otherwise store/check the full SHA as the dedup identity. The prompt may still display a short SHA, but the queue identity cannot.\n\nVERDICT: REVISE\n","rawOutputHash":"4411d77864068f2cbb6e0cda367d66bead68edc5d98397a86ad1e795f5add234","signature":"d6d5be85330acf370a15dd6478e2687cc5fb39b0eeade3e8c0550f087ca56014306bfadd10a5d4f26230f333a1a3c6c8a1a12116e321e029cb2c98b828bc100b"},"prevHash":"345dcaab6573d235a9dfe108cd926da09ced621f11c6b977713ea24a65212f12","entryHash":"b45261235595f0e71501889d8b7d703baa099657decf6b498fccfd3bbf360133"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"989e5532c602477c9589794efd9253a409f330ef04330d0472adbb55e91eb4cd","verdict":"NO_VERDICT","rawOutput":"⚠️  Reached maximum iterations (6). Requesting summary...\nLet me read `queue.ts` to verify the `hasBallot` semantics, then run the tests.\n","rawOutputHash":"1b646ee0f5e1e279e32c6c1d7228508d963f7ebc4039780f14edb8f3e14dd1cf","signature":"48f52c0bbc8014d1ffb3dfac2172a664c0989f6056b0dc02277eb0a485c3e9a3ea0d936cd0cc8e8da2c141892239a3dc06b57d859ca40a619713c7a44ea9170b"},"prevHash":"b45261235595f0e71501889d8b7d703baa099657decf6b498fccfd3bbf360133","entryHash":"d29985f1ea0bf697031f04a461d0aa2be4f6286594c175076a9a9ec537d0fbd6"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"6a395c72fb699da2d81cc7dfc4c6167c31609eb8fbfda4c39d33f6f546a3f281","verdict":"SOUND","rawOutput":"I've reviewed the commit from source across all four claims, verifying the actual post-commit code in `signed-vote.ts`, `daemon.ts`, `self-review-source.ts`, `invokers.ts`, `panel.ts`, and the consumer `commons.ts`, plus the backing tests.\n\n## Assessment against each claim\n\n**1. NO_VERDICT never ratifies** — `ratify()` skips NO_VERDICT in the max-finding loop (`signed-vote.ts:187`) and gates `ratified = verdict !== null && max >= required` (`:194`). NO_VERDICT stays in `tally` for transparency but can never *be* the verdict. A neighboring-position check confirms a real verdict below threshold (e.g. REVISE:1 vs NO_VERDICT:2, required 2) correctly yields `ratified:false`. Backed by a direct test. ✅\n\n**2. Real-verdict participation** — daemon computes `realVotes = votes.filter(v => v.verdict !== 'NO_VERDICT')` and finalizes only at `realVotes >= quorum` (`daemon.ts:62-63`); otherwise retry/fail. Crucially it filters the `votes` array itself, **not** `ratify().counted`/`.tally` (which include NO_VERDICT voters) — so the laundering path is closed at the daemon layer too. Verified `convene()` returns the same signed-vote set `ratify()` tallies (`panel.ts:95-96`), and that an errored invoker still yields a *signed* `NO_VERDICT` vote (`deliberating-signer-host.ts:50-53`), so the two layers see a consistent view. ✅\n\n**3. Full-sha dedup** — id is `review-${epoch}-${commit.sha}` (full sha); short 12-char is display-only. The collision test (shared epoch + 12-char prefix, distinct full sha → distinct ids) passes. Strengthens tamper-evidence. ✅\n\n**4. Invoker budgets** — 480s timeout / 16MB buffer shared, hermes `--max-turns 12`, with SIGTERM→\"timed out after Nms\" diagnostics. Prompt passed via env (`QRM_PROMPT`) for the shell-routed invokers / argv for hermes — no injection, custody untouched. ✅\n\n## Adversarial findings (non-blocking)\n\n- **Daemon uses `params.quorum` for the participation bar, not `max(quorum, supermajority(n))`.** For the standing 3-panel (quorum 2, supermajority ⌈6/3⌉=2) these coincide, so no live bug. And even under a misconfig where quorum < supermajority, `ratify()` *independently* enforces the 2/3 floor, so the `ratified` flag stays correct — the daemon's bar only governs retry-vs-finalize and errs conservatively (finalizes as *not* ratified, never laundering a NO into a YES). Not a soundness break.\n- **`commons.ts:84-89` would label a NO_VERDICT position as `CREDIBLE_MINORITY` within a RESOLVED claim** — cosmetic/reputational display only, doesn't touch ratification or finalization, and is outside this commit's surface.\n\nCustody, no-laundering, liveness, and tamper-evidence all hold; every claim is implemented as stated and covered by tests (TDD satisfied). The change does what it says with no gap between claim and implementation.\n\nVERDICT: SOUND\n","rawOutputHash":"72973dc17a8a40b0a75049ef48159769e68fcc6c645d0974d20eb8d4ebc0912c","signature":"043d729eb13f41ad4f61280f088102406d98e90a9bbea05ca4d6a1f380437bfb00c496950700ea97fff42b13cc6f29c1abc8c987594bf3bf147131cffb1a0204"},"prevHash":"d29985f1ea0bf697031f04a461d0aa2be4f6286594c175076a9a9ec537d0fbd6","entryHash":"1f829e94e4e505326588690446f8d527a9867cd5dd05f6e73906da82d21e9863"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"6a395c72fb699da2d81cc7dfc4c6167c31609eb8fbfda4c39d33f6f546a3f281","verdict":"SOUND","rawOutput":"The change is sound on the reviewed source path. `ratify` keeps `NO_VERDICT` in the transparent tally but excludes it from the winning verdict, so sentinel failures cannot ratify. `drainQueue` now gates finalization on non-`NO_VERDICT` votes, so a quorum of invocation failures is retried instead of moved to `done`. The full-sha review id fixes the stated short-prefix collision for new self-review ballots, and live `ConveneResult.votes` matches the daemon’s new `{ verdict }` expectation.\n\nI ran `npm test`; it could not complete in this read-only sandbox because many tests need `mkdtemp` under `/tmp`, but the pure ratification tests shown in the run did pass, including the new `NO_VERDICT` case.\n\nVERDICT: SOUND\n","rawOutputHash":"331bc3106b89fedc95928e38f980d8fd849a9500bb138e3d28988ad82383d956","signature":"8adb18fee7a5ea2dfd59add33b7822ce78fae77265873023dc53f5c9ff7ca56d680a9d1e5fa27c1d7b5c6ea8ec44863e26c31db80a61b56fb7f05ea62450120d"},"prevHash":"1f829e94e4e505326588690446f8d527a9867cd5dd05f6e73906da82d21e9863","entryHash":"aa8ed651be5574945c408a4df7644a626c54e68db682e8fc5beea165b772e4e4"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"6a395c72fb699da2d81cc7dfc4c6167c31609eb8fbfda4c39d33f6f546a3f281","verdict":"SOUND","rawOutput":"⚠️  Reached maximum iterations (12). Requesting summary...\nAll seven files checked (daemon, invokers, self-review-source, signed-vote, and three test files). Here's the adversarial review:\n\n1. ratify excludes NO_VERDICT (signed-vote.ts): the `if (val === 'NO_VERDICT') continue;` is placed correctly inside the max-count loop, before `max` is updated. NO_VERDICT tallies are still populated for transparency. The test covers the exact 2/3 NO_VERDICT scenario and asserts ratified=false, verdict=null. No gap.\n\n2. daemon counts only REAL verdicts for participation (daemon.ts): `result.votes.filter(v => v.verdict !== 'NO_VERDICT')` is the right boundary. A convening with 3 raw votes but only 1 real now falls through to the retry path. The `RunResult` interface change from `unknown[]` to `{ verdict: string }[]` is compatible with `ConveneResult.votes` (SignedVote[]) and the test mock. No gap.\n\n3. Full-sha dedup (self-review-source.ts): `id` uses `commit.sha` (40 hex chars). The 12-char short sha is preserved only for the human-readable prompt. The collision test constructs two distinct 40-char SHAs sharing the first 12 chars and asserts non-equal ids. No gap.\n\n4. Invoker budgets and diagnostics (invokers.ts): timeout raised to 480s module-level; hermes turn cap raised to 12. The new `runWithDiag` wrapper catches execFile errors and appends the stderr tail (last 500 chars) or \"timed out after Xms\" for SIGTERM. All three invokers route through it. The `execFile` timeout kills with SIGTERM by default, so the diagnostic label is accurate. Environment is spread correctly (`...process.env` preserved, so PATH works). No gap.\n\nCross-cutting invariant checks:\n- No-laundering: a panel where 2/3 validators errored is now retried (daemon path), not finalized (old behavior). NO_VERDICT also cannot become the ratified verdict. Both halves of the liveness fix are present.\n- Custody: invoker changes don't touch the signing boundary; private keys remain child-side.\n- Tamper-evidence: NO_VERDICT votes are still tallied; the rawOutput with the new stderr-tail diag becomes the vote's rawOutput hash. Unchanged.\n- TDD: all four new behaviors have corresponding tests (daemon retry on 2/3 NO_VERDICT, ratify never picks NO_VERDICT, full-sha collision, and invoker diag).\n\nVERDICT: SOUND\n","rawOutputHash":"f74afe39aaf0b39ab29ed7495b5b98d33b61ae5d0ef1afa6b458616aa76fa9cb","signature":"d66734a213d07cf7cab314639709cb65ca3077ea6de5b7756fbb78b6c26d70fb5dc68aacfbeba34bc951fd6fb68e8abc82b00c978bb1c37b4cfe0c29cc4e6609"},"prevHash":"aa8ed651be5574945c408a4df7644a626c54e68db682e8fc5beea165b772e4e4","entryHash":"ef013e113e1a8681444c747923d7578c46fe5e26c6c9f4662971067ffb0e9d2a"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"e5779b38525bc1aaee59f8b4b253ae1c7624e330cf56a408bc12b12f1a0391b4","verdict":"REVISE","rawOutput":"I have the complete diff (content is faithful; only the cosmetic `diff --git`/`index` headers are stripped by the rtk proxy). I read the four touched source files plus the test. Here is my adversarial judgment.\n\n## What the change does\n- **`self-improve.ts`** — a pure `gateOf({ratified, verdict})`: ratified `SOUND`→`APPROVED`; `REVISE`→`CHANGES_REQUESTED`; `INADEQUATE`→`REJECTED`; everything else (no 2/3, or unknown verdict)→`INCONCLUSIVE`.\n- **`live-ballot.ts`** — extracts `liveRunBallot` + constants verbatim out of `run-daemon.ts` so daemon and self-improve share one convening path. `run-daemon.ts` is slimmed to import it.\n- **`run-self-improve.ts`** — the standing cycle: source a review of HEAD → drain → refresh feed → read `done/${id}.json` → `gateOf` → print.\n- **`self-improve.test.ts`** — covers all four `gateOf` branches.\n\n## What holds up (invariants)\n- **No-laundering / fail-closed:** `gateOf` can emit `APPROVED` *only* on `ratified===true && verdict==='SOUND'`. The untyped `JSON.parse(...).result as {...}` cast is actually safe here: any malformed/missing field yields falsy `ratified` → `INCONCLUSIVE`, never an approval. A liveness miss (no `done` file) is also explicitly `INCONCLUSIVE`. Good.\n- **Custody:** the extraction is byte-identical; `liveRunBallot` still holds no key and supplies no verdict (`assertMatchesPin`, throw-on-substitution preserved). The `mkdirSync(DATA)` correctly moved from daemon `main()` into the shared function — no regression.\n- **TDD:** the pure decision function is the part that's tested, and it's fully covered.\n\n## The gap (precise, real, fixable)\n**The \"gate\" does not gate — it classifies and always exits 0.** The headers claim *\"this gates it; nothing is approved without 2/3 SOUND… Every other outcome **blocks** it… mechanical, not a human reading the tally.\"* But mechanically:\n\n1. The agent has *already committed* to HEAD before `run-self-improve.ts` runs. On `REJECTED`/`CHANGES_REQUESTED`/`INCONCLUSIVE` nothing is reverted, blocked, or undone — the change stays in HEAD.\n2. The *only* output is `console.log(\"GATE: …\")`. `main()` returns normally for every outcome, so the **process exits 0 whether the verdict is APPROVED or REJECTED.** No `process.exitCode`, no throw, no non-zero signal.\n\nSo for a cycle whose stated purpose is \"run after a commit, or on a cadence\" with \"no human in the loop,\" the gate result is *only* consumable by a human reading the tally — the exact thing the commit says it replaces. Any wrapper/scheduler/CI step cannot distinguish a ratified-SOUND from a REJECTED. The decision is correct; it just isn't *actionable*, which is the difference between \"blocks\" (claimed) and \"prints a label\" (actual).\n\n**Fix:** set a non-zero `process.exitCode` on any non-`APPROVED` gate (including the missing-`done` INCONCLUSIVE early return), so the standing cycle's caller can actually act on the verdict. That closes the claim-vs-behavior gap without touching the (correct) `gateOf` logic.\n\n(Note: the subagent left two dotfiles in the repo capturing the diff — `.qrm_show.txt` and `.qrm_stat.txt`; `rm` is blocked by the approval gate, so they need manual cleanup.)\n\nVERDICT: REVISE\n","rawOutputHash":"24e3fd1f701c316cf4f00854b8b021931c617ac2e10d5fc41e8674bd343e371f","signature":"ee6c0e1db3e15b7a511986949d888a3e5bccf16387252c5236351fba7cfa5b8aae7b6c543c836a871656326c4918f1bc65aee4c866108345808530272754980e"},"prevHash":"ef013e113e1a8681444c747923d7578c46fe5e26c6c9f4662971067ffb0e9d2a","entryHash":"a3976b3b22475a03c5957818eda30eddbb7324215578467899ceaf629c406505"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"e5779b38525bc1aaee59f8b4b253ae1c7624e330cf56a408bc12b12f1a0391b4","verdict":"REVISE","rawOutput":"REVISE. The gate is not actually anchored to the tamper-evident ratification proof. `run-self-improve.ts:48-49` approves from mutable `queue/done/<id>.json` instead of recomputing the expected review ballot hash and ratifying matching signed votes from `votes.log` with the pinned keyring. That lets an edited or stale done record launder `ratified: true, verdict: \"SOUND\"` into `APPROVED`, even though `feed.ts` already shows the correct pattern: recompute from the log, never trust stored results.\n\nFix: make the gate derive HEAD’s expected ballot via `reviewBallotFor`, compute its ballot hash, select matching log votes, verify the log chain and signatures, run `ratify`, and only then call `gateOf`.\n\nVERDICT: REVISE\n","rawOutputHash":"ea16701d5175af9e9a4e7a70a070670a44365b7cff4f5de7f102425fdf22825e","signature":"77263a792789b00d4ccc8d8fd0a8441ca647fa40d4ea586d20933658fc427e1c36ce394e8553e5623a9caf2995f96f47a075c29d1d543510786f214772f08d0b"},"prevHash":"a3976b3b22475a03c5957818eda30eddbb7324215578467899ceaf629c406505","entryHash":"d25c2de7e7693b9d2873824b06859dbc96caff1c2efa8178802abe38f5054783"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"e5779b38525bc1aaee59f8b4b253ae1c7624e330cf56a408bc12b12f1a0391b4","verdict":"SOUND","rawOutput":"⚠️  Reached maximum iterations (12). Requesting summary...\nAdversarial review of commit 546b2cb40b32 against project invariants:\n\n1. **Custody & Key Control**: `run-self-improve.ts` orchestrates the cycle but holds no keys. It delegates to `liveRunBallot`, which loads the pinned keyring, starts remote signers, and calls `assertMatchesPin` before convening. Any key substitution or missing host throws, which `drainQueue` catches as a liveness failure. No verdict is ever minted by the orchestrator.\n2. **No-Laundering & Gate Safety**: `gateOf` is pure and fails closed. It only returns `APPROVED` when `ratified === true` AND `verdict === 'SOUND'`. Every other path (`REVISE`, `INADEQUATE`, `!ratified`, or unrecognized verdicts) yields a blocking gate. The `drainQueue` mechanic refuses to moveTo `done/` unless the supermajority bar is met by real verdicts, preventing a weak or timed-out panel from forcing a decision.\n3. **Liveness Handling**: If convening fails (hosts down, substitution, or <2/3 real verdicts), the ballot stays `pending` (bumped attempt) or moves to `failed/`. The self-improve script checks for the `done/<id>.json` file. Absence correctly prints `GATE: INCONCLUSIVE` and returns without approval. A permanently stuck review correctly blocks the pipeline, matching the invariant that liveness failures must not be laundered into approvals.\n4. **Tamper-Evidence**: `liveRunBallot` appends to the hash-chained `votes.log`. The feed refresh (`buildFeed`) recomputes outcomes independently from this log + the pinned keyring, so the public projection cannot be spoofed by queue state.\n5. **TDD & Correctness**: Extraction of `liveRunBallot` to `live-ballot.ts` is a clean refactor that eliminates duplication between the daemon and the self-improve cycle. All 191 tests pass, including explicit coverage of the `gateOf` decision boundary. The dedup logic in `sourceSelfReview` uses the full SHA + epoch, preventing the collision vulnerability noted in phase 1.2.\n\nThe change formalizes the dogfooded pattern into a standing, mechanical cycle with correct boundary conditions and invariant adherence. No gap found.\n\nVERDICT: SOUND\n","rawOutputHash":"1bd3e8fb30c65404efe984223aead9f11f3fec25008c18d4e96ee72723b0eb7e","signature":"be38844dd946c949d952bc0ddade758955054c73f6ea2d96173de23351270dca385210c67fff59564479660eb4b6615317f63061d885607c671ee05b9f885901"},"prevHash":"d25c2de7e7693b9d2873824b06859dbc96caff1c2efa8178802abe38f5054783","entryHash":"99cab84a0e3581632eb40671a9371f55b94c3b6f0864236e8eff4382408f1fda"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"cea2d144bf4b007f4a2371c2005f23ce88c1445a3157e3c6172cb84744796e23","verdict":"SOUND","rawOutput":"I have enough to judge. Full evidence gathered: the new gate functions (`self-improve.ts`), their wiring (`run-self-improve.ts`), the recompute primitives they inherit (`feed.ts` → `verifyLog`/`ratify` in `signed-vote.ts`), the sourcing path (`self-review-source.ts`, `live-ballot.ts`), and the tests (`self-improve.test.ts`).\n\n## Assessment\n\nThe commit makes two claims; both hold against source.\n\n**Claim 1 — \"gate anchored to the recomputed log.\"** `run-self-improve.ts:41` builds the feed via `buildFeed(LOG, loadPinnedKeyring(PINNED), QUORUM)`, which (`feed.ts:44-56`) recomputes every outcome with `ratify` over the signed votes + pinned keyring and sets `chainValid` from `verifyLog`. `gateForBallot` (`self-improve.ts:27-32`) reads HEAD's verdict from *that* feed by ballot hash — not from the mutable queue done-record. `ratify` (`signed-vote.ts:145-206`) rejects unknown validators, wrong-ballot, equivocation, and invalid signatures, and the signature binds `ballotHash`+`verdict`+`rawOutputHash`. So a relabeled/edited/stale record cannot launder an approval. **No-laundering and tamper-evidence are upheld.**\n\n**Tamper short-circuit.** `gateForBallot` checks `!feed.chainValid` *first* → `INCONCLUSIVE`, so a broken chain approves nothing even with a present ratified-SOUND convening (tested, `self-improve.test.ts:45`). Fail-closed.\n\n**Ballot-hash match (the one place this could silently break).** The gate recomputes `ballotHash(ballot.prompt, ballot.context ?? '')` and the feed's key is what validators signed. Both the signing path (`live-ballot.ts:38-39`, `convene` gets `context: ballot.context ?? ''`) and the gate use the **same `?? ''` normalization** over the **same `reviewBallotFor` ballot** (whose `context` is always a defined string). They cannot diverge → the keyed lookup won't silently miss → no spurious permanent-INCONCLUSIVE.\n\n**Claim 2 — \"made actionable (non-zero exit).\"** `exitCodeFor` returns 0 only for `APPROVED` (`self-improve.ts:37-39`), wired at `run-self-improve.ts:52` via `process.exitCode` — the correct choice (lets stdout/feed writes flush rather than truncating, unlike `process.exit()`). Every non-APPROVED outcome blocks CI. Tested (`self-improve.test.ts:31`).\n\n**TDD invariant.** Both round-54 findings have dedicated tests, including the adversarial broken-chain case. Satisfied.\n\n**Adversarial nits, none defeating soundness:** broken-chain and not-yet-convened both map to `INCONCLUSIVE`, but the distinction is surfaced in the console line (`chain: BROKEN`) and both block — observable and fail-closed. The feed is published before the gate result, but that's a faithful transparency projection of the recomputed outcome, not an approval signal — correct.\n\nThe change does exactly what it claims, inherits the recompute proof correctly, normalizes the lookup key consistently, fails closed, and is covered by tests.\n\nVERDICT: SOUND\n","rawOutputHash":"66912c00cdbedc18826e7ec6363a2b2f82ad09cec90043df2f12a310544c0770","signature":"21417ff16cec11888c99d6095e0f9b3a323751000e0e5d56dd5de1de188c213d5001434b864006dc1b0fcd37d8c545bb70b41b48d47067757b4a673853bbf206"},"prevHash":"99cab84a0e3581632eb40671a9371f55b94c3b6f0864236e8eff4382408f1fda","entryHash":"facf2e4053ec155261d253d177f8558ae13efb1a8151b7f537dfd79e5f9fc369"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"cea2d144bf4b007f4a2371c2005f23ce88c1445a3157e3c6172cb84744796e23","verdict":"SOUND","rawOutput":"The change is sound on the specific claim. `run-self-improve.ts` no longer reads `queue/done/<id>.json` for the gate; it rebuilds the feed from `data/votes.log` with the pinned keyring, computes HEAD’s deterministic review `ballotHash`, and gates through `gateForBallot`. `gateForBallot` also refuses approval on `feed.chainValid === false`, so a broken log chain cannot clear the gate.\n\nThe non-zero exit behavior is real: `process.exitCode = exitCodeFor(gate)` makes every non-`APPROVED` result mechanically blocking. The added tests cover the approval path, invalid-chain block, missing-ballot inconclusive path, REVISE classification, and exit code behavior. I did not find a queue-record laundering gap left in this commit.\n\nVERDICT: SOUND\n","rawOutputHash":"b79bb637a6dd613957be070e55345a21513eb24b350221d4e6393ef094fd10dd","signature":"c60416513b021718047dc0c8167d7f7bbfd20a6c74b882c17423d42c1f4616c9d89a6a05a156399749e7005d49c279a302815cc39754f4d23a55a37a9e5c4b07"},"prevHash":"facf2e4053ec155261d253d177f8558ae13efb1a8151b7f537dfd79e5f9fc369","entryHash":"f71f580b58083ffacf94d36499cdd9dd20da80717fa076442c9746ed74864809"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"cea2d144bf4b007f4a2371c2005f23ce88c1445a3157e3c6172cb84744796e23","verdict":"SOUND","rawOutput":"⚠️  Reached maximum iterations (12). Requesting summary...\nHere is the adjudication of commit bcaf720976d5 against the project invariants.\n\n**TL;DR: The diff does exactly what the commit message claims. No gap found between claim and implementation.**\n\n---\n\n**1. Tamper-evidence / No-laundering (V2 fix)**\nThe old code read `queue/done/<id>.json` directly — a mutable filesystem record that any process or operator with write access could overwrite to manufacture an APPROVED verdict. The new code never reads `done/` at all. Instead it:\n- Calls `buildFeed(LOG, keyring, QUORUM)` which `readLog + verifyLog` the hash-chain AND calls `ratify()` over each ballot's signed votes against the pinned keyring. Every verdict in the feed is recomputed, not retrieved.\n- Gates via `gateForBallot(feed, headBallotHash)` which checks `feed.chainValid` first (break → INCONCLUSIVE), then looks up the ballot hash.\n- A broken chain or an edited `done/` file cannot launder an approval. The gate inherits the feed's proof-of-computation by construction.\n\n**2. Custody / Determinism**\nThe ballot hash derives from `ballotHash(ballot.prompt, ballot.context)` where both fields come from `reviewBallotFor(head)` — a pure function of the commit's SHA, epoch, and subject. This is exactly the same hash that validators signed during convening. No mismatch between the ballot the gate queries and the ballot the votes were cast on.\n\n**3. Liveness**\nIf `drainQueue` fails or the ballot is not yet in the log, `convening` is undefined → `gateForBallot` returns INCONCLUSIVE → `process.exitCode = 1`. The cycle blocks mechanically rather than silently approving. Correct.\n\n**4. Actionable exit (V1 fix)**\nOld code: `return` with implicit exit 0 (CI/scheduler could never act on the printed label).\nNew code: `process.exitCode = exitCodeFor(gate)` where `exitCodeFor` returns 0 only for APPROVED, 1 for all other gates. Setting `process.exitCode` on an async `main()` that resolves normally is the correct Node.js pattern (does not kill the event loop, does allow graceful shutdown). Correct.\n\n**5. TDD**\nFive new tests cover the critical paths:\n- `exitCodeFor` for all four gate values\n- `gateForBallot` approved (valid chain + ratified SOUND)\n- `gateForBallot` blocked on broken chain\n- `gateForBallot` blocked when ballot not found\n- `gateForBallot` classifies REVISE → CHANGES_REQUESTED\nAll 196 tests pass. No skipped, no todo.\n\n**6. Defensive edge — checked**\nThe `default: return 'INCONCLUSIVE'` in `gateOf` catches any unexpected verdict string. The `ratify` function explicitly skips `NO_VERDICT` when computing the winning verdict and only sets `ratified: true` when `verdict !== null`, so a ratified convening always carries a known verdict. The default branch is unreachable but correct as a safety net.\n\nNo gap between what the commit claims and what it does. The invariants are preserved or improved, tests are sufficient, and the exit-code wiring is correct for the runtime.\n\nVERDICT: SOUND\n","rawOutputHash":"5d1fc0836c76753550f6d831da3f366450155174e36483a90fcfd463f9516ebf","signature":"83db1c57135ff1fd57ffbd6148edf457dffb7119811ee3d9362e48459bac852ddbb08d0a8338fb83b0812d28446658ab07443a2080d00c4c1909c6a27f971008"},"prevHash":"f71f580b58083ffacf94d36499cdd9dd20da80717fa076442c9746ed74864809","entryHash":"0c0bb01b76289123a211ec3248145d808c39fd3c6481b88e7218b6c0bea944e5"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"e85a24ec9864f0eb2c3fede65d5df5572a9b9406f0e685793502dcd58add5a96","verdict":"SPECIFY_DEFER","rawOutput":"## Reasoning\n\n**Is the deterministic/non-cherry-pickable rule meetable for an external feed at all?**\n\nPartially — and the gap is the whole decision. The proposed rule (published source set; window `[now−W, now]`; order by `(resolution_timestamp, question_id)`; take oldest K unreviewed; W/K/sources as panel-gated published constants) is genuinely deterministic *as a function of a given feed snapshot*. It correctly collapses agenda control from \"pick each question\" to \"pick the source set once, in public, under 2/3.\" That's a real reduction and the design is sound.\n\nBut \"reproducible by an outsider from public inputs\" has two unmet preconditions the rule itself doesn't supply:\n\n1. **The inputs are mutable by a third party.** The queue is a pure function of feed data, but the feed operator can edit close/resolution timestamps, add/remove questions, or reorder — moving the cherry-pick surface from *our* operator to the *feed's* operator. Determinism at a snapshot ≠ tamper-evidence over time.\n2. **The evaluation instant is unpinned.** \"now\" must be anchored (fixed UTC cron / block height) or two outsiders re-derive different windows.\n\nClosing both requires hash-pinned, archived, timestamped feed snapshots and a pinned evaluation instant — i.e. exactly the **Knowledge-Commons external-anchor mechanism that CIP-3 is supposed to codify and which is currently BLOCKED/pending** (per the round-4 governance ruling). So the binding constraint is meetable *for the selection rule*, but not yet airtight *for the feed inputs* until that anchor work lands.\n\n**Now vs defer.** The binding constraint is the deciding lens, and it cuts against building now: shipping tier 2 against a live feed today would deploy the deterministic rule on top of un-anchored, operator-mutable inputs — re-introducing the precise cherry-pick surface the constraint exists to forbid. Round 48 already ratified \"existence not economics,\" and tier 1 (round 53) proves autonomous sourcing exists. The external feed's trust/availability dependency is most meaningful in the token/substrate phase and is best built *riding* the CIP-3 anchor mechanism, not ahead of it.\n\nRatify the design (it's correct and worth locking now); defer the build.\n\n**Deferral trigger:** build tier 2 when CIP-3's Knowledge-Commons external-anchor mechanism is ratified and live (hash-pinned, timestamped feed snapshots + a pinned evaluation instant), so the feed *inputs* — not just the selection rule over them — are reproducible and tamper-evident; align with the token/substrate phase that creates real demand.\n\nVERDICT: SPECIFY_DEFER\n","rawOutputHash":"f8309d1acb75c0ab63a49f726af28117ebff7916159b8eac136366c8450a6ddb","signature":"be4ef043adf71137ecb7c886ba4e0b4b68ba8ca20d4f3b2a028889566f3ae070322c1827368d30d679b8bed188b2d0e1fd72590c5b9ec468a29af182764a8d05"},"prevHash":"0c0bb01b76289123a211ec3248145d808c39fd3c6481b88e7218b6c0bea944e5","entryHash":"438cacdbfcf13fc4085eb1390dec1e303b066f5b14b87ea650c1997921ff02a6"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"e85a24ec9864f0eb2c3fede65d5df5572a9b9406f0e685793502dcd58add5a96","verdict":"SPECIFY_DEFER","rawOutput":"The deterministic/non-cherry-pickable constraint is meetable for an external feed if the source set, window, ordering, and limits are public constants and changes are panel-gated. That makes the queue reproducible from public data and removes per-question discretion.\n\nI would ratify the design but defer the build. Tier 1 already demonstrates autonomous sourcing at small scale, while the external feed adds operational dependency before the product needs it. Deferral trigger: start the tier-2 build when token/substrate work begins or when a concrete public dispute/oracle feed is needed for fee-bearing resolution flow.\n\nVERDICT: SPECIFY_DEFER\n","rawOutputHash":"409c4e5d27e44a35a124cc1aebc63c5575248e3dc664d3ded4a71cffbfb3b606","signature":"3fa350769fc2641eeba73ef86d80cfbcdd349000b95a305906ed5b003baad7a02f36a18488c0121e802d67a97fbf6ffd9f81a0b0f777753425401d34285d2604"},"prevHash":"438cacdbfcf13fc4085eb1390dec1e303b066f5b14b87ea650c1997921ff02a6","entryHash":"631dc9eaad5eaa750b5d0a15aedd005e2cbe861df99b40f7e29b15b1ca6208b4"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"e85a24ec9864f0eb2c3fede65d5df5572a9b9406f0e685793502dcd58add5a96","verdict":"SPECIFY_DEFER","rawOutput":"Reading the ballot context and reasoning as a validator.\n\nBINDING-CONSTRAINT ANALYSIS: Is a deterministic, non-cherry-pickable selection rule meetable for an external feed?\n\nYes. The proposed rule is auditable: given (1) a committed source set, (2) a published window constant W, (3) a published K, and (4) public feed data with resolution timestamps, the queue is a pure function — any outsider reruns the same computation and gets the same set. The only remaining control surface is the source set itself, which is elevated to a panel-gated 2/3 config change — collapsing agenda control from per-question cherry-picking to a transparent, infrequent, logged decision. The external nature of the feed does not break determinism because the rule consumes only published resolution timestamps, not provider-curated opinion or ordering.\n\nVERDICT REASONING — now vs defer:\n\n1. Tier 1 (self-review of git commits) is already built and panel-certified. It proves autonomous balloting source exists — satisfying the \"existence not economics\" principle ratified at round 48.\n2. Tier 2 introduces real network dependency, trust boundary, and availability risk. These costs are not needed to prove the mechanism's existence.\n3. The external dispute feed becomes meaningful as a $QRM fee source only when there is actual economic activity to resolve — i.e., once the token or substrate phase is live. Building it before then creates dead capacity.\n4. Deferring does not abandon the binding constraint: the selection rule is ratified now, so the anti-cherry-pick guarantee is established before the build happens.\n5. Deferral trigger should be concrete: token launch or substrate-phase go-live, whichever comes first — that is when external dispute resolution transitions from architecture rehearsal to real product dependency.\n\nVERDICT: SPECIFY_DEFER\n","rawOutputHash":"2155d788930632d1f6f68a7e6e3f6c4e13d9721f9e5717883d26a067320027a6","signature":"3e0dc582654894bb3f59de88ae465e4a68c2f25344431e00984b6dd42184ecc297ee13382e588a15fc30402d27f32fd13d124caaebaac50d5273ab803c995c04"},"prevHash":"631dc9eaad5eaa750b5d0a15aedd005e2cbe861df99b40f7e29b15b1ca6208b4","entryHash":"57ab58aa2d9998f236640b8786f3dd0612d890936606d845526aa0c32ce81c25"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"e4c7be6af40b70be6f0d04bdb68d350e707be152d1dce91e67248079521c1f94","verdict":"REVISE","rawOutput":"## Reasoning\n\n**The transport swap is sound.** The signer boundary from rounds 44–47 already locates integrity in the right place: keys live child-side, the orchestrator holds none, and verdict integrity rests on the pinned keyring + signing-over-received-content (`assertMatchesPin`). Moving from a stdin/stdout pipe to a socket changes the channel, not the trust model. The keystore split (each machine holds only its own key) is *strictly better* than today's shared keystore directory. And the mTLS reasoning is correctly scoped — it adds confidentiality + endpoint auth + DoS/impersonation resistance, and the brief explicitly does **not** claim it provides verdict integrity. That's the right call: a host without the pinned key can't produce an acceptable vote regardless of TLS, and a tampered ballot is caught by the hash. So mTLS is correctly additive, not load-bearing.\n\nThis is also necessary scaffolding: you cannot reach independent-operator diversity without first having network transport and per-host keystores. Deferring the build until you have operator diversity is backwards. So this is not REJECT.\n\nBut two things in the proposal are unfinished in ways that matter, so it's not ADOPT-as-written:\n\n**1. The replay nonce must be decided now, not left open.** Once you're on a network, replay stops being theoretical — a captured signed vote is a real artifact. Orchestrator-side idempotency doesn't give you auditability, because a recorded vote's meaning depends on it being bound to a specific convening. Decision: orchestrator issues a fresh per-convening nonce, the host signs over `{prompt, context, verdicts, nonce}`, the orchestrator verifies the nonce matches the convening it issued. The host already signs over content, so the marginal cost is near-zero — and doing it *at* the transport swap avoids a second protocol migration later.\n\n**2. The diversity gap must be mechanically un-launderable, not just documented in prose.** This is the red-team lesson applied directly: \"3 independent VMs/clouds\" will mechanically pass a diversity check while one operator holds all three keys. A prose footnote does not stop the *next* system — CIP-10 two-tier admission / Proof-of-Diversity — from consuming a host-count attestation and reading it as operator diversity. Required: the attestation surface must represent **operator-count as distinct from host-count** and emit `operator-count = 1` during this phase. The operator-owned phase must not produce any attestation that downstream admission would accept as satisfying operator diversity; graduation flips that field. If the schema can't represent operator-count separately from host-count, *that* is the gap to close before building.\n\n**3. Scope cap on the interim (the brief invited this).** Testnet only; no priced token, no mainnet value secured, no economically-final governance. Sunset condition tied to CIP-10 admission of ≥N independent operators.\n\nConditions 1 and 2 are load-bearing required changes; that makes this REVISE rather than ADOPT. The direction is right — build it.\n\nVERDICT: REVISE\n","rawOutputHash":"0d261f7b5922e65b78a7837d8647af9314cad78b6fa30db75cf93fb6ebf5f128","signature":"28b87ec138259058dd3c6a1d395d08e611c0d1f75322f689d5054685f42572edd8fb343a8dc2cb7d80b17fdcae763bbd8a195af36d0899bda442a3fa29744f0f"},"prevHash":"57ab58aa2d9998f236640b8786f3dd0612d890936606d845526aa0c32ce81c25","entryHash":"b2d1632d826aa6e6930318fa82ed6e82504511fa37cff5fa074146383c3bb021"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"e4c7be6af40b70be6f0d04bdb68d350e707be152d1dce91e67248079521c1f94","verdict":"REVISE","rawOutput":"The direction is sound, but only if the interim is treated as a security improvement over single-machine custody, not as real quorum diversity.\n\nKeystore split, network transport, mTLS, and a signed per-convening replay nonce are the right next engineering steps. They reduce blast radius from one host compromise, exercise the distributed signer interface, and preserve the existing pinned-key verdict integrity model.\n\nThe required revision is governance/security labeling: operator-owned VMs must not satisfy any meaningful diversity claim. The design should explicitly name this as **operator-capture laundering**: three machines mechanically appear distributed while one operator still controls all validator keys. Add clear conditions:\n\n- require nonce binding in the signed payload, not optional idempotency;\n- document single-operator control as a known limitation;\n- cap this phase to bootstrap/testnet or non-priced/non-final authority use;\n- define graduation/sunset criteria tied to CIP-10 admission and Proof-of-Diversity;\n- ensure diversity checks distinguish machine/cloud independence from operator/key-control independence.\n\nVERDICT: REVISE\n","rawOutputHash":"fbb9f6afeae40bc7b347630853b0aa78d02ceacda24bb9653129cfb26992c639","signature":"21a5aa98a93a66343777b5fc54eafc88d65ebcddb46c7a34a6621bfcee3b7f8706d2c9610044623c579f0691d28e4b7c20631b33e22e4cb62027059a1a39cd0c"},"prevHash":"b2d1632d826aa6e6930318fa82ed6e82504511fa37cff5fa074146383c3bb021","entryHash":"984b5c328314c6a72ad7eac932028999a42ad232a50f09fc65ffbf416a725480"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"e4c7be6af40b70be6f0d04bdb68d350e707be152d1dce91e67248079521c1f94","verdict":"ADOPT","rawOutput":"Reasoning:\n\n**Keystore split is materially sound.** Even with one operator, moving from one machine with one keystore directory to three VMs each holding exactly one key is a real security step. A single-host compromise yields at most one validator's key, not the whole set. The attacker must pivot across VM/network boundaries. This is genuine defense-in-depth.\n\n**mTLS is the correct layer.** The rationale that verdict integrity already lives in the signature+pinned-keyring is correct. mTLS adds confidentiality, endpoint authentication, and resistance to injection/DoS without being mistaken for the integrity mechanism. Good layering.\n\n**Replay nonce should be included, not deferred.** Idempotency alone won't prevent replay of a vote from convening A into convening B. Binding a per-convening nonce into the signed payload prevents this, costs almost nothing, and strengthens the audit trail. Do it now.\n\n**The operator-owned interim is an accepted risk, but it MUST carry conditions.** The gap is honestly named — \"three VMs, one operator\" is not real diversity. This is acceptable ONLY if bound by explicit graduation criteria:\n\n1. Documented as a known limitation in the project's threat model, not handwaved away.\n2. Restricted to testnet / no-priced-token phase. Never carry this to a state where stake or value is at risk.\n3. A sunset clause: independent-operator admission (via CIP-10 two-tier + Proof-of-Diversity) is a prerequisite for mainnet progression.\n4. A graduation gate that verifies mechanical independence: different cloud providers, separate auth credentials, no shared admin plane. These are cheap to check and make the graduation criterion measurable rather than aspirational.\n\nThe capture-laundering gap (mechanical \"three VMs\" vs. intended \"three operators\") is real but is properly addressed by naming it, bounding it in scope, and attaching a path out. No need to wait for operator diversity to build the transport and keystore split — those are valuable independently and ease the eventual handoff.\n\nVERDICT: ADOPT\n","rawOutputHash":"f652042291ef5dee01aa699d5e74209d3df6c882781fce7041faa72b8d5e0aae","signature":"b5f1544b73bd288b9b26c7cce8eeb8995944eeb326171a280d29f66123bd1c8e3a53b7d65ef77b6b0a3f577baed7e9a74829b7da200515acd65c34bbc88b180f"},"prevHash":"984b5c328314c6a72ad7eac932028999a42ad232a50f09fc65ffbf416a725480","entryHash":"2346350fa2cbda475c986fa22ca86f2dc3b9a8d1b17c37a374fb3d80c9f3b005"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"60536b946f5b04b2fe4005e49ce5595796b438bdee659bf34d601bebdea54613","verdict":"REVISE","rawOutput":"I was unable to read the source (`commons.ts`/`reputation.ts`/`publish-feed.ts` aren't at the expected paths and shell/reads are gated this session), so I'm judging the design as specified in the brief — which is the actual unit under review.\n\n## Reasoning\n\n**The direction is right.** Three things make this architecture correct for CIP-9, not just convenient:\n\n- **Recompute-from-log + no edit key** is the structural guarantee of §0/§2. A pure projection that reproduces on regeneration cannot harbor an editor's hand; `chainValid` surfaced on the page makes tamper non-silent. This is the same trust model as `publish-feed.ts`, so no new assumptions are introduced.\n- **One `ClaimView` core, two readers** keeps the agent-facing structured read and the human markdown page from diverging into two different \"truths.\" Single source, correct.\n- **`subjectKey` reserved-but-empty** is the right NI-9c discipline — topic classification is the editorial-risk layer, and deferring it (rather than half-building it) keeps v0.1 genuinely non-editorial.\n- **stance-set as body** is the §2 commitment honored at the data level.\n\n**Where it is not yet sound — and it's specific.** The invariants are clean in the *data model* but unpinned in the *presentation layer*, which is exactly where an \"epistemic state\" quietly degrades into \"a single truth + footnotes.\" The brief asserts intent (\"never collapsed\") without a testable contract. Four named changes:\n\n1. **`INDEX.md` is an uncontrolled compression point.** A one-line index row per claim is where a CONTESTED/OPEN claim gets flattened to a winner-label. Define what the index renders per status — a CONTESTED claim must read as contested in the index, not show its top stance. Without this, the index becomes the single-truth surface even while pages stay pure.\n2. **Render dissent at equal structural weight.** \"Consensus stance alongside preserved dissent\" must be enforced, not intended. Add a golden-file test asserting a RESOLVED claim's page contains the full dissent set with no demotion-to-footnote and no omission. Ordering/headline treatment is real editorialization even over clean data.\n3. **NI-9b: `support` must be `null`/\"not externally anchored\", never `0`.** Pin null-vs-zero in both the `ClaimView` type and the renderer. A panel-only claim that prints `support: 0` fabricates a signal — the precise thing NI-9b forbids.\n4. **`status` must be a documented pure derivation with a test** (so it is \"computed, not assigned\" per NI-9c), and UNVERIFIABLE's raw-plurality display must be test-covered against ever emitting \"FRINGE.\"\n\nThese are additive guardrails on a correct design, all nameable — not a wrong approach (not REJECT) and not yet safe to build verbatim given the read surface's entire purpose is to *not* decree a single truth (not ADOPT).\n\nVERDICT: REVISE\n","rawOutputHash":"59a1f47b2bb73acc6944e765e813358297620b8d008b06df7800f85ac64b0b7d","signature":"952e449ab58cb9886b5c854fb7faccf84872de81b8c312a3d690b10d933135ef955bccd3944e31e479a004adee0ced2df94e8e24492d93fa53a5cd10b18db90d","nonce":"01e1bb59d0613aa68cafa124cfbbf4f7"},"prevHash":"2346350fa2cbda475c986fa22ca86f2dc3b9a8d1b17c37a374fb3d80c9f3b005","entryHash":"23daafa3772a959907efdd069d892288935876853f98e2305ce0f8ba018cc2b2"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"60536b946f5b04b2fe4005e49ce5595796b438bdee659bf34d601bebdea54613","verdict":"ADOPT","rawOutput":"The design is sound in direction and matches the CIP-9 invariants: a recomputed projection from the signed log, with `ClaimView` as the canonical read object, avoids introducing an edit key or a separate editorial truth layer. Per-claim pages are also the right v0.1 granularity because they expose the existing claim graph without prematurely inventing topic curation.\n\nThe key condition is that `chainValid`, panel-state receipts, external-anchor provenance, and preserved dissent must be mandatory render fields, not optional decorations. If those are enforced in `commons-read.ts`, then markdown is only a projection of the epistemic state and not a new authority surface.\n\nVERDICT: ADOPT\n","rawOutputHash":"717be041a63993ae7a12f1b68d5226b631f8042270d164ea8bff68a9bdedbceb","signature":"0ba2543468c091a2b3e7aa431d13d1aabc549a79c80c705aaa3c2c549fc998d587d42f157461669cf86a3e01e5813348485b8ada477e349152ba6d247f45860a","nonce":"01e1bb59d0613aa68cafa124cfbbf4f7"},"prevHash":"23daafa3772a959907efdd069d892288935876853f98e2305ce0f8ba018cc2b2","entryHash":"c786459da4741f0a9844667d0e2d1515a49fdeddced46bc855a4e9f7fb6a2971"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"60536b946f5b04b2fe4005e49ce5595796b438bdee659bf34d601bebdea54613","verdict":"ADOPT","rawOutput":"Evaluating against the CIP-9 invariants:\n\n**NI-9a** — `panelState` carried as a structured field on every `ClaimView` and passed through the renderer. Consensus renders alongside its receipt. Good fit.\n\n**NI-9b** — Support/reputation surfaces only where tied to external anchors (reputation.ts already enforces this). The ClaimView model doesn't invent panel-only movement metrics.\n\n**NI-9c** — Standing is computed, not editorialized. UNVERIFIABLE falls back to raw plurality, no FRINGE label. `subjectKey` is explicitly empty now, deferring non-editorial topic grouping. Compliant.\n\n**§2 (epistemic state, not single truth)** — The stance-set IS the body. RESOLVED shows consensus stance alongside preserved dissent, not collapsed to one answer. This matches the invariant's intent.\n\n**Architecture** — Single `ClaimView` core with two readers (agent structured, human markdown) is clean. Pure recompute from the log means no stale pages, no edit key, no drift from the source of truth. `chainValid` flags tampering.\n\n**Minor observations** (don't block building):\n- The markdown renderer must show all stances with equal visual weight — any typographic hierarchy (heading size, ordering, \"featured\" callouts) risks covert editorialization. A review of the rendered output for that risk should happen when `commons-render.ts` lands, not now.\n- If a claim's panelState changes between votes (member joins/leaves, correlation shifts), the view should capture the panelState at each version step in `history[]` so the receipt trail is reconstructible. This is implied by the VersionRef model but worth confirming during implementation.\n\nThese are implementation-level cautions, not direction changes.\n\nThe architecture is small, composable, invariant-respecting, and mirrors a pattern already proven in the codebase. Sound to build.\n\nVERDICT: ADOPT\n","rawOutputHash":"5d3cef9fe436d8a2e0756e2f028b294c2e3fd4129744da499b841a8afcf0c8ac","signature":"c1434dfaefbfd6f1d5048ff58347f1495c1f024dbc3ad8561074079369cc1bbb235f1f352ab23a166f58f271e1afef9df075267ff1ef8ccb493ac97bccc1b80b","nonce":"01e1bb59d0613aa68cafa124cfbbf4f7"},"prevHash":"c786459da4741f0a9844667d0e2d1515a49fdeddced46bc855a4e9f7fb6a2971","entryHash":"2e769b55020976c29a53bdaf14b2bd6f196b511df9e072fbe7412f1d040b07c3"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"db580ba81dee143c64e35c499f1a74cc3aa17400b38877b62fcaff154f8c0ed4","verdict":"REVISE","rawOutput":"I've read all the new modules and their dependencies. Here's my judgment against each invariant.\n\n## Invariant-by-invariant\n\n**NI-9a (panel-state receipt) — UPHELD.** `commons.ts` builds `panelStateReceipt: { validators: [...seenValidator], size }` from the *verified, counted* validators, and `renderClaimMarkdown` unconditionally emits the receipt line. The denominator is the validators who actually produced verified rulings — the conservative, correct reading (never inflates authority). No path renders a stance without it.\n\n**NI-9b (support never leaks agreement) — UPHELD.** `viewClaim` hardcodes `support: null`, and the renderer maps `null → \"not externally anchored\"`, never `0`. `panelVotes` is carried separately and explicitly labelled panel distribution, not reputation. Agreement cannot reach the support field — it's structurally absent in v0.1.\n\n**NI-9c (standing computed, no FRINGE, no winner-flattening) — UPHELD.** Standing is computed in `buildClaimIndex` by the auditable majority rule; the `Standing` type has no FRINGE member at all. Non-RESOLVED index rows read as `\"N stances, no consensus\"` — no winner-label. RESOLVED rows show the consensus position *and* flag preserved dissent. The claim page gives every stance an identical row structure (no headline/footnote hierarchy). `NO_VERDICT` correctly stays UNRANKED even in RESOLVED claims.\n\n**No edit key — UPHELD.** `publish-commons` is pure recompute from log + keyring + registry; no prior render is read. `chainValid = verifyLog(LOG).valid` drives a banner on both claim and index pages; a tampered log surfaces as a ❌ banner, never silently-altered content.\n\n**Statement integrity — UPHELD.** `statementFor` returns the prompt *only if* `verifyEntry` re-hashes to the stored `ballotHash`; a missing/lying entry yields `null`, rendered as the hash, never a fabricated title. Crucially, `convene` appends the registry entry from the *same* `prompt,context` that produces the `ballotHash` the votes bind to — so the registry key matches the claim key, and the registry is treated as provenance, not a trust root.\n\nThe standing test (capture via intent/check gaps) finds nothing in the epistemic core: no stance ordering re-introduces a decree, no support value leaks agreement, no render path can show unverified text.\n\n## The one actionable gap\n\nThe index→claim links are broken. `publish-commons.ts` writes `INDEX.md` *inside* `docs/commons/` (`join(OUT, 'INDEX.md')`, `OUT = docs/commons`), alongside the per-claim pages. But `commons-render.ts:46` builds the link as `commons/${slice}.md`. Relative to `docs/commons/INDEX.md`, that resolves to `docs/commons/commons/xxxx.md` — a dead link to every claim page. The fix is one character of path: `./${slice}.md`.\n\nThis is exactly the intent/mechanical-check gap pattern, just in the navigation layer rather than the epistemic one: the renderer's unit tests assert the output *string* and pass, because the renderer can't see where the CLI writes `INDEX.md` — the two modules silently disagree about the layout (compare `publish-feed.ts`, which writes `FEED.md` to `docs/` root, where a `commons/`-prefixed link *would* be correct). The 225 green tests don't cover the cross-module file-path contract, so it slipped through.\n\nNone of the five ratified invariants are violated — the epistemic design is faithfully and rigorously implemented. But the delivered read surface doesn't actually navigate: an index that can't reach any claim page is a real, shippable defect, and it's precisely nameable with a one-line fix. That's a REVISE, not a wave-through.\n\nVERDICT: REVISE\n","rawOutputHash":"529417bb5dbdc9cbeffbed89968cfc63d0b66209bfc0a6fdfab064e011831264","signature":"79ad0fc9ef6ac47c5ada314d775fd8b3efda47fec0ee4e9fafe593328a64194f70c23d35fc8e43c0a573b91b24d7f925c34ddf39a83d37bb198931cd55c29e08","nonce":"b59ab5fa4541168d4c8eec3b9313f158"},"prevHash":"2e769b55020976c29a53bdaf14b2bd6f196b511df9e072fbe7412f1d040b07c3","entryHash":"b65d58796a01f5e2aec9b9b2c6e31bf9fb08dccc8f8d7778851c181a0605acdf"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"db580ba81dee143c64e35c499f1a74cc3aa17400b38877b62fcaff154f8c0ed4","verdict":"SOUND","rawOutput":"I judge it SOUND.\n\nThe implementation is a pure projection from the signed vote log, pinned keyring, and self-verifying registry. Statements are only surfaced through `statementFor` after re-hashing `{prompt, context}` to the stored `ballotHash`; missing or lying registry entries render as hash-only, so the registry is not a trust root.\n\nNI-9a is mechanically present in every claim render via the panel-state receipt. NI-9b is upheld because `support` is always `null` in `commons-read.ts` and renders as “not externally anchored,” never as `0` or agreement-derived reputation. NI-9c is upheld by `commons.ts`: standing is recomputed from verified counted votes, no `FRINGE` category exists, contested/indeterminate claims stay unranked, and the index does not flatten non-consensus claims into a winner label.\n\nThe no-edit-key invariant is also met: `publish-commons.ts` recomputes from log, keyring, and registry; prior renders are not read. A failed `verifyLog` is threaded into the views and rendered as a broken-chain banner rather than silently trusted content. I do not see a rule whose stated intent is only cosmetically checked while being mechanically bypassed.\n\nVERDICT: SOUND\n","rawOutputHash":"bac3d09941c0d82520fbd5e4d175ca2bc09ee93075b74cda4009337fb20e0d52","signature":"6359564d7c9bebe210e698e640dee1f774cb4bdfcd0e4c0697d7bd16f47fb9879045ea0cf57f59043ca5f9055208bdb89b9ac4d89c769acda932f2e94af8e102","nonce":"b59ab5fa4541168d4c8eec3b9313f158"},"prevHash":"b65d58796a01f5e2aec9b9b2c6e31bf9fb08dccc8f8d7778851c181a0605acdf","entryHash":"f5cd730114a0952eef645e4dfa013c7ab57ea8228ed4651f3288ff04a42ea942"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"db580ba81dee143c64e35c499f1a74cc3aa17400b38877b62fcaff154f8c0ed4","verdict":"SOUND","rawOutput":"⚠️  Reached maximum iterations (12). Requesting summary...\nI have read all four new modules plus the three supporting modules (`commons.ts`, `signed-vote.ts`, `vote-log.ts`). I could not locate `run-panel.ts` or `live-ballot.ts` in this repository, so I cannot verify the convening-side registryPath wiring — but those are the write path; the read surface invariants do not depend on how entries arrived, only on how they are verified.\n\nHere is my vote-trace against each invariant:\n\n**NI-9a — Panel-state receipt always shown**\n`commons.ts:99` computes `{ validators, size }` from the set of counted validators. `commons-read.ts:44` carries it as `panelState`. `commons-render.ts:35` always renders `**Panel-state receipt (NI-9a):** {size} validators — {validators}`. No path skips it. Letter and spirit match.\n\n**NI-9b — Support never leaks agreement**\n`commons-read.ts:42` hardcodes `support: null` for v0.1. `commons-render.ts:13` maps null to the string \"not externally anchored\". There is no code path where `support` can equal `0` or derive from `panelVotes` or panel size. The leak is mechanically blocked.\n\n**NI-9c — Standing computed, never editorial / no FRINGE / no winner-flattening**\nStanding comes from `commons.ts:87-92`, a pure function of `ratify()` result. Only three labels exist: CONSENSUS, CREDIBLE_MINORITY, UNRANKED. FRINGE does not appear anywhere in the codebase. For CONTESTED/INDETERMINATE claims, `indexRow` renders \"N stances, no consensus\" rather than picking a winner. For RESOLVED, consensus is surfaced with a dissent flag — exactly what the ratified design prescribes. Stances in `renderClaimMarkdown` are rendered in first-seen order (neutral) with identical row structure — no hierarchy. No gap.\n\n**No edit key — pure projection**\n`publish-commons.ts` reads only from `votes.log`, `ballots.jsonl`, and `pinned-keyring.json`. Zero reads from `docs/`. `buildViews` is pure. `verifyLog` → `chainValid` → banner. A tampered log produces a broken-chain banner; content is not silently altered. Prior render is never an input.\n\n**Statement integrity — re-hash before display**\n`ballot-registry.ts:18-20`: `verifyEntry` recomputes `ballotHash(prompt, context)` and compares to stored `ballotHash`. `statementFor` at line 47-50 returns the prompt ONLY if verification passes, else null. `commons-render.ts:19` falls back to showing the hash when statement is null. A lying registry entry (wrong prompt) fails re-hash and is rejected. The registry is not a trust root — it's a hint that must prove itself.\n\n**Standing test — spirit vs. letter**\nI looked for subtle violations:\n- Stance ordering: first-seen order, not popularity-sorted. No stance reordering to favor consensus in the body.\n- Index \"reading\" column for RESOLVED shows consensus position, but this is the ratified design's own specification for resolved claims, and dissent is flagged.\n- `panelVotes` is shown numerically but is consistently labeled \"panel votes\" — never repurposed as reputation.\n- `NO_VERDICT` standing is forced to `UNRANKED` even on RESOLVED claims (`commons.ts:91`).\n\nNo gap found between intent and mechanical check.\n\nOne caveat: `run-panel.ts` and `live-ballot.ts` were not found, so I cannot confirm the registry is actually invoked during convenings. But that does not affect the read surface's correctness — it only means we don't know whether ballot statements are being recorded. The read path itself is faithful.\n\nVERDICT: SOUND\n","rawOutputHash":"d4a64978c5d662a11ab6026b57094871939ec319db351cd33dc8c409f30ac025","signature":"5c903217b8cfd817048054be81121e273c403778b0acb6276c2153587e20587f4ddfd4bc5aca71313b479ee84e2c493729c7ddb038e9d2e65c0d3107f10cfd09","nonce":"b59ab5fa4541168d4c8eec3b9313f158"},"prevHash":"f5cd730114a0952eef645e4dfa013c7ab57ea8228ed4651f3288ff04a42ea942","entryHash":"48071e080f9027043810322f52b8cf797f68d88e7825a7333ba7d95dd3e1cfac"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"ae4abf0b8a7824d68f2724531d84e1610f3a396b41ec4b8391fcb34fafb3ba0d","verdict":"REVISE","rawOutput":"## Reasoning\n\n**Problem framing — sound.** \"Vendor diversity is not distributional independence\" is correct and is the one critique that actually bites. Three models over one corpus can be confidently and identically wrong, and a 3/3 shared hallucination is signature-indistinguishable from 3/3 on a verified fact. CIP-9 already *contains* this (records \"N/N agreed,\" not \"true\"; NI-9b accrues reputation only from anchors). The question is whether to add active defense before the panel is used as a recall oracle. Yes — accept the framing.\n\n**Part 1 (anchor-gated RESOLVED) — sound, adopt.** This restricts *upward* only: it refuses to mint RESOLVED without an external anchor, the structural opposite of an edit key. It cannot decree truth; it can only decline to. The \"it only confirms the already-verifiable\" objection is not a bug — for a trust-minimized oracle, INDETERMINATE-by-default is exactly right, and it doesn't touch the current job (validating own code/design), where the source *is* the anchor every validator reads directly.\n\n**Part 3 (probes) — sound, adopt.** Converts \"we assume errors are uncorrelated\" into a logged number. Pure measurement, no decree. The probe-distribution ≠ live-distribution objection is real but answered: a measured floor published *with its methodology* strictly dominates an unexamined assumption. Requirement: the read surface must label it a probe-distribution estimate, not a universal guarantee.\n\n**Part 2 (refuter role) — the defect.** Methodological diversity is the *right* instinct: asking the same question the same way three times maximizes correlation, so breaking the symmetry is genuinely the strongest of the three ideas. But as specified — \"one validator's *task is to find the strongest case the proposition is FALSE*\" — it most naturally reads as overwriting that validator's signed vote with an adversarial one. If the refuter's *verdict* is forced negative, the 2/3 supermajority denominator is corrupted: a signature no longer means \"this validator believes X,\" and you've put a recorded, rotating thumb on the scale. That's not a truth-decree, but it violates the same record-honesty principle from a different direction.\n\n**Fix:** separate the *role* from the *vote*. The rotating validator produces a **recorded adversarial-refutation artifact** (the strongest false-case), which becomes an *input* to all three validators' deliberation — but every validator's signed verdict must remain its honest belief. You get the de-correlating benefit of forced refutation without polluting the consensus arithmetic. The artifact is auditable and rotates exactly as proposed; only the vote stays clean.\n\nSo: framing right, parts 1 and 3 adopt as-is, part 2 needs the role/vote split.\n\nVERDICT: REVISE\n","rawOutputHash":"a8610135d7df6a2c74be80da15fbf79bf8ec3151000b9c03b5295981ca0e3d02","signature":"cddd6b98961fcad47f6a90e276c303b56304cbeb55bb38260ab4880486a84cf805a56341a6898ae963531d4931d1280da55eff44413b346903dae7c5ef95aa0c","nonce":"67ebb428d5782c399208735a3ab16895"},"prevHash":"48071e080f9027043810322f52b8cf797f68d88e7825a7333ba7d95dd3e1cfac","entryHash":"a6ab1fa068ba31ae284c3cd9b7a339e666787dc6baacce67a169f02df30b445c"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"ae4abf0b8a7824d68f2724531d84e1610f3a396b41ec4b8391fcb34fafb3ba0d","verdict":"ADOPT","rawOutput":"CIP-10 should be adopted.\n\nThe critique identifies a real architectural gap: vendor/model diversity does not imply independence for recall errors drawn from the same public corpus. CIP-9 already prevents agreement from becoming a truth decree, but CIP-10 makes that containment explicit before Quorumchain is used as a broader oracle.\n\nAnchor-gated `RESOLVED` is the strongest part. If there is no external verifiable anchor, unanimity should only record consensus state, not truth. That is conservative, but it matches the record-not-decree invariant.\n\nThe rotating `REFUTER` role is acceptable because it is methodological, recorded, and auditable. It does not secretly bias the result; it makes dissent-search part of the signed procedure. The vote should distinguish role-conditioned reasoning from final status, but that is an implementation detail, not a reason to reject.\n\nProbe ballots are imperfect because they measure only their distribution, but a logged shared-error rate is still better than an implicit independence assumption. The read surface should expose probe scope and limits so the number is not overclaimed.\n\nNone of the three mechanisms creates an edit key, reputation-from-agreement rule, or editorial truth authority. They strengthen CIP-9’s principle that Quorumchain records bounded validation evidence rather than decreeing truth.\n\nVERDICT: ADOPT\n","rawOutputHash":"7956965861b541d6c5e4d4eca861b68e6c24e4cfa62b18a7d3608c7944dc1453","signature":"c7259a3652906bb74077499d83d9ff178cfbbcad6360b0f1db96a041000896d26c1011cefd1e49ed8c38c91acbf673455a33a887190821bef1ae557ad6090a0a","nonce":"67ebb428d5782c399208735a3ab16895"},"prevHash":"a6ab1fa068ba31ae284c3cd9b7a339e666787dc6baacce67a169f02df30b445c","entryHash":"325ccb47a54445f04808ad6729f5b0d6797964063d50af9b443bc87405739703"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"ae4abf0b8a7824d68f2724531d84e1610f3a396b41ec4b8391fcb34fafb3ba0d","verdict":"ADOPT","rawOutput":"Let me work through each mechanism against the CIP-9 invariants and the actual threat surface.\n\n**Anchor-gated RESOLVED** — This does not mint editorial power. It constrains a *status label*, not validator speech. Validators still sign whatever they believe; the ballot's status simply cannot escalate to RESOLVED unless there is an external anchor to compare against. This is exactly the epistemic honesty NI-9b demands: reputation accrues from anchors, never from agreement alone. The \"narrows the oracle\" counterargument is real but correctly handled — a recall-only oracle without anchors is epistemically indistinguishable from confident noise, and INDETERMINATE is the honest label for that case. The oracle still has value-add: it can analyze anchors, reason about them, and present structured verdicts. It just can't claim RESOLVED status on naked recall.\n\n**Refuter role** — Sound in principle, but needs a narrow refinement. The risk is that if the refuter is told \"argue against proposition P,\" it may manufacture contrarian reasoning it doesn't genuinely hold, adding noise rather than reducing false positive correlation. The fix: the refuter should not receive a directional instruction at all. Instead, it should be given the *same ballot content* but prompted to independently evaluate without seeing other validators' drafts, and its role tag in the record signals that it was tasked with seeking disconfirming evidence. This preserves methodological diversity *and* honesty of reasoning. A recorded, rotating adversarial stance is legitimate process — analogous to a court appointing an amicus — so long as the role description is about *method*, not *conclusion*.\n\n**Probe ballots** — Unobjectionable. Passive measurement, no effect on live verdicts, no editorial power. The distribution-bias concern is handled by logging the probe distribution alongside the measured shared-error rate; consumers know what the estimate covers. A conservative (biased-toward-easy) estimate is strictly better than none, and stratification across domains widens coverage.\n\n**CIP-9 invariant check:** No editor key is created. No validator overrides another. No truth is decreed — only recorded reasoning under a different procedural frame. The read surface already says \"N/N agreed,\" not \"true.\" This CIP adds constraints on escalation, method, and measurement. All consistent with \"record, not decree.\"\n\nThe minor refinement on Part 2 keeps the mechanism proportionate without introducing the noise risk. Nothing here re-introduces editorial power. The threat is real (corpus overlap is a structural fact, not a contingent bug), and the defense is measured — it bounds rather than claims to eliminate shared-error risk.\n\nVERDICT: ADOPT\n","rawOutputHash":"ab676f7bb01669e7e850d837bfd156750c0b8101db8fc4c6b3f7d746bc7afe49","signature":"5abdbd8f554422d479b2c42d910d15a8d0066bf4f0758df2e902a6f70432d1c47647e78d7956ea243fcadd92091d0454794a829f21469b30ff4377619adcae00","nonce":"67ebb428d5782c399208735a3ab16895"},"prevHash":"325ccb47a54445f04808ad6729f5b0d6797964063d50af9b443bc87405739703","entryHash":"c39c1774a39532d068c3e153ba4bc15adbc5a935736af09b071b48474ae4c0ab"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"aecf01411331d57a3083398c765ec6ebd104b32a0525366cbb7c31d2ee90f238","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"## Validator review — Quorumchain whitepaper outline\n\nThe locked decisions (a)–(d) are not mine to relitigate. I'm judging whether the **outline structure** is sound to draft against. It is: threat model sits up front (§2), the worked example is correctly demoted from framing to illustration, limitations are first-class (§9), and economics is scoped to mainnet steady state per (b). That's the right skeleton. My YES is conditional on folding the following into the draft — none require restructuring, all fit inside existing sections.\n\n**Foldable critique (concrete):**\n\n1. **§2/§5 — \"diversity = security\" is currently a slogan, not a claim.** This is the load-bearing assertion of the entire document and the outline never commits to *backing* it. A reviewer will read \"security = model diversity\" as marketing unless the draft states the mechanism: what does 2/3 collusion cost, what correlation between models is assumed, and what happens as models homogenize (shared training corpora, shared providers, RLHF convergence). CIP-10 (correlated-error defense, ratified round 60) is the home for this — **make it an explicit named subsection**, not a reference tag. This is the single biggest marketing-vs-verifiable gap. *Fold: add \"the quantified diversity-security argument\" as a titled block in §2 or §5.*\n\n2. **§6 — \"mechanism-level model\" (b) is currently a parts list, not a model.** Components are named (stake/slashing, gas, inference reimbursement, 2/3-set buyback) but a mechanism model owes the reader: the **solvency inequality** stated explicitly (revenue ≥ inference cost + security budget), the buyback as a **deterministic formula**, and slashing-bond sizing tied to attack payoff. Without these, §6 reads as token-marketing despite the no-launch decision. *Fold: outline §6 must commit to stating the solvency condition and buyback rule as equations.*\n\n3. **§1 is the highest marketing-risk section and is over-weighted at 1.5pp.** \"People trust AI more every day / now most people just ask and take the answer\" is an unverified behavioral premise presented as fact — label it motivation, not claim. The Commons-as-co-headline plus the closed-loop flywheel (\"Commons improves AI which enriches Commons\") is exactly the network-effect narrative a skeptic discounts. *Fold: hedge the flywheel as \"intended dynamic,\" and trim §1 so it doesn't out-weigh the technical core.*\n\n4. **No section owns the domain of admissible questions.** The system adjudicates via frozen criteria (ballotHash), but the outline never addresses *what can be adjudicated* — verifiable vs. subjective claims, who authors criteria, what happens with unfalsifiable questions. \"AI consensus is not truth\" (§2) gestures at this but the scope-of-claims boundary is a real limitation. *Fold: a paragraph in §3 or §9 on admissible-question domain.*\n\n5. **§8 status numbers risk reading as a maturity badge.** \"40+ rounds, 37 tests, round-29 replay\" are *self-reported internal governance artifacts*, not independent validation. Frame them precisely as \"self-reported, independently replayable\" (the appendix self-verification is the right instinct — point §8 at it). And the testnet/mainnet model counts (10 → 20+) should be justified *by* the §2 diversity argument, or they read as arbitrary.\n\nMinor: define \"oracle / clock / memory\" before the abstract leans on the maxim.\n\nNone of these change the section structure — they are binding requirements on what each section must deliver. The outline is sound to draft. Proceed.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"467a99c57bf1cba770bb63234921df61923c8d11d4f9f950b6c31ab96891aa97","signature":"2621f00bdcbb30775a891a3fde303182fe2bf7bb7118a10fb25d9c03f3838ed1ac84a8046ce96043e0fe308172918dab67dcdbcf61b0a4641d7c7b201b188608","nonce":"52e7e824f8956efe0cb488d7766e026d"},"prevHash":"c39c1774a39532d068c3e153ba4bc15adbc5a935736af09b071b48474ae4c0ab","entryHash":"c91677a3d443c43cad85afd2c9c8e6cdae73e9e421d8215a21370f8f9031fc9a"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"aecf01411331d57a3083398c765ec6ebd104b32a0525366cbb7c31d2ee90f238","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The outline is sound to proceed. It matches the locked decisions: technical protocol whitepaper with investor-readable entry, mainnet steady-state economics only, humble/mechanical tone, and enough structure for a 10-15 page Markdown draft.\n\nConcrete critique to fold into drafting:\n\n- The abstract risks sounding too slogan-like. “AI is the oracle, not the clock” is useful, but it must quickly become a precise architecture claim: deterministic ledger orders events; AI panels only produce signed judgments under frozen criteria.\n- “Security = model diversity” is directionally right but too absolute. Draft should say diversity is a necessary security primitive, not a complete security proof. It must define capture, correlated failure, model-provider dependence, prompt leakage, and jury-selection manipulation.\n- Section 1 is the highest marketing-risk area. Keep “more trustworthy Wikipedia” as an analogy, not a claim. The verifiable claim is narrower: provenance-preserving, forkable, evidence-linked consensus records.\n- The Knowledge Commons needs crisp boundaries. Is it a canonical knowledge base, an indexed archive of verdicts, or a stance-set graph? The outline suggests all three; the draft should define the object mechanically.\n- Economics needs one explicit insolvency path: what happens if inference reimbursement exceeds fees, buyback pressure, or treasury capacity. “Solvency = security” is good but must be operationalized.\n- Governance should avoid overclaiming “self-governing by the panel itself.” Clarify what the panel can recommend, what humans/operators still control, and which keys or authorities are renounced when.\n- Implementation status must separate live facts from intended milestones. “40+ ratified rounds” and “37 tests” are strong only if reproducible with exact commands, hashes, or links.\n- Limitations deserves more than 0.5 pages if possible. It is the main antidote to hype and should explicitly cover non-truth, model collusion, bad criteria, adversarial evidence, latency/cost, and subjective questions.\n\nNo material change is required before drafting, but the draft must convert the strongest phrases into falsifiable protocol claims.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"86ad322b898a7a8446bd16ee69a0b158d2b8d315f91cbe7a90da7db90f362218","signature":"4bcaf5f06c9279d6e0ff1dde8d911704122509737686f1e666a7d110e40e38188b389e6f0b47d4920f0d0202b23ee3598ae7bbf0c859a1bbe52dc0f942c02c02","nonce":"52e7e824f8956efe0cb488d7766e026d"},"prevHash":"c91677a3d443c43cad85afd2c9c8e6cdae73e9e421d8215a21370f8f9031fc9a","entryHash":"58f76c8963bf0a717598421f08eaa3f537b61abccfc050d687688d4273eb69e8"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"aecf01411331d57a3083398c765ec6ebd104b32a0525366cbb7c31d2ee90f238","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Reviewing the outline against the four locked decisions and judging structural soundness for a first draft:\n\n**Against decision (a) — Technical whitepaper + investor-readable layer:** Sound. The exec summary + Section 1 provide the plain-language onramp; Sections 2–7 deliver the technical core. The separation is clean.\n\n**Against decision (b) — Economics = mainnet steady state only, no SPL/pump.fun narrative:** Section 6 matches this exactly. The outline explicitly says \"mainnet steady state\" and the locked language \"solvency = security\" is present. Good.\n\n**Against decision (c) — ~10–15 pages:** The page allocations sum to roughly 14–15pp. Within tolerance.\n\n**Against decision (d) — Markdown, humble/mechanical tone:** This is execution, not outline, but the structure supports it.\n\n---\n\n**Material risks to flag for the drafting phase (foldable, not blocking):**\n\n1. **Section 1 tone drift.** The framing \"people used to Google… now they ask AI\" is a narrative hook, not a mechanical claim. At 1.5pp it risks opening the paper with marketing cadence. Mitigation: compress the consumer-behavior observation to 2–3 sentences, then pivot immediately to the technical problem (single-model oracle = unaccountable, no replay, silent mutation). Keep the Knowledge Commons description functional (\"a citable consensus-built knowledge base with evidence, dissent, and provenance\") rather than aspirational (\"a more trustworthy Wikipedia\").\n\n2. **Section 6 page allocation is thin for a mechanism-level model.** A 1.5pp section claiming \"fee flows + deterministic buyback + solvency = security\" needs at minimum: (a) the fee formula (inference cost reimbursement rule), (b) the 2/3-set buyback trigger condition and execution path, (c) the solvency invariant (what breaks it, what guarantees it). If these are all mathematical/algorithmic rather than prose, 1.5pp may suffice, but the draft should make that explicit. Consider bumping to 2pp or adding a subsection \"Solvency invariant\" to prevent the economics from reading as hand-wavy.\n\n3. **Cryptographic primitives unnamed beyond Ed25519 and SHA-256.** The hash-chained log structure (Section 3) and the Knowledge Commons tamper-evidence (Section 4) should name the chaining construction (e.g., Merkle tree, hash chain, or similar) and any commitment scheme. This is a one-line addition to Section 3's outline notes, not a structural change.\n\n4. **Section 5 — \"Proof of Diversity\" needs a one-sentence definition in the outline.** The term appears but its mechanical meaning (what is measured, how diversity is scored, what prevents Sybil-forking of model identities) is not sketched. Add a parenthetical in the outline so the draft doesn't invent it on the fly.\n\n5. **Section 8 — \"40+ ratified rounds, 37 tests, round-29 replay\" is good concrete evidence, but \"what runs today\" should clarify scope: is this a testnet, a local simulation, or a public endpoint?** One disambiguation prevents overclaiming.\n\nNone of these are blockers on the outline itself. They are drafting-time calibrations. The structure covers all locked decisions, the logical flow is correct (problem → philosophy → architecture → pillars → validators → economics → governance → status → limitations), and the Round-29 example is correctly positioned as a worked case, not the frame.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"4b275766e3e3f7c083970b236ef1adadc547836a3362d8ce03bf1bf45d645ab2","signature":"9cc257b276b6b4ed3be42284a0eafd17f1aff63660aadd922fc062c35883da13b87515b52b55c8120dc963abb94ccd959889e13040c185f1347e462f80031d03","nonce":"52e7e824f8956efe0cb488d7766e026d"},"prevHash":"58f76c8963bf0a717598421f08eaa3f537b61abccfc050d687688d4273eb69e8","entryHash":"ae12cf79277a9f0b2d7d1456b0617c753c0d21b761873c620d095f1b391d72ac"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"1c42a8f851129a3f116b88c5acfe254eedbc5ba1aea9e7910352f6ef68b316e1","verdict":"A","rawOutput":"## Judgment\n\n**Accuracy (no overclaim).** A and B are clean — \"verifiable\" and \"decentralized\" are checkable properties. C fails on the spot: \"Trustworthy\" is the exact marketing register the tone target forbids — it asserts the conclusion the architecture is supposed to *earn*, and it isn't verifiable. D's \"Accountable AI\" leans slogan, and the three-item list (\"Consensus, Memory, and a Tamper-Evident Record\") reads as a feature bullet, not a positioning line.\n\n**Category legibility.** A names the actual category in four words: *decentralized AI oracle network*. A first-time reader knows what kind of thing this is. B says \"consensus protocol,\" which subtly miscategorizes — in the thesis the deterministic ledger is the *clock*, deliberately the dumb part; the project's identity lives at the oracle. Calling it a \"consensus protocol\" foregrounds the component the thesis explicitly de-emphasizes. D never says what it is at the category level.\n\n**Verifiable claim vs marketing.** A makes two falsifiable assertions — it's decentralized, and the memory is verifiable — and nothing more. \"With verifiable memory\" also uniquely captures the Accountability-Ledger + Knowledge-Commons pairing that differentiates this from a plain oracle. B drops the memory dimension entirely.\n\nA wins: it is the thesis's own framing, maximally legible, and every word is a checkable claim.\n\n**Proposed refinement:** the candidate is already tight. The only nit is that \"Verifiable Memory\" slightly undersells the two-path design (write = tamper-evident record, read = citable claim graph). If a marginally fuller line is wanted without bloating the cover:\n\n> *A Decentralized AI Oracle Network with a Verifiable Record and Memory*\n\nBut this adds length for modest gain; I'd ship the original A as-is.\n\nVERDICT: A\n","rawOutputHash":"cbb6170fde406b1c0797a755b2c61151439a92603441b3f221a0882a1a0e018a","signature":"2f1e50d3e0293635c04230b4faa19f9545f1bc3efc04054d64e548240fc9516d823bea3fc93d0caac0b8b231efcbb4de40c5fc766e3fdf671b45fbf231ad1308","nonce":"11d631685f61e796f06e21d05b418ac1"},"prevHash":"ae12cf79277a9f0b2d7d1456b0617c753c0d21b761873c620d095f1b391d72ac","entryHash":"a49efc52b5335322e715892b4c40dc7811605ac857d96c37f0da5162c0197e1f"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"1c42a8f851129a3f116b88c5acfe254eedbc5ba1aea9e7910352f6ef68b316e1","verdict":"A","rawOutput":"A is strongest. It is the most category-legible for a first-time reader: “decentralized AI oracle network” tells them what Quorumchain is, while “verifiable memory” captures the Accountability Ledger and Knowledge Commons without overexplaining. It beats B because Quorumchain is more than a consensus protocol; B narrows the category too much. It beats C because “trustworthy” reads like marketing and is less verifiable. It beats D because “Accountable AI” is broad and could be mistaken for an ethics framework rather than an oracle network.\n\nTighter rewording: “A Decentralized AI Oracle Network for Verifiable Judgment and Memory.”\n\nVERDICT: A\n","rawOutputHash":"46a0477bbd02e81fcd495532a01d0db029166fa8e3c18888bb70c9fb8db3d179","signature":"68981523a0ddf1722cfeeaa0cd15345ee9d3c5af72de2eaaa54775610c0afecb1cbd73cec326069f86080523d5a57eaeae6d3cd3fc27750d0731797514565104","nonce":"11d631685f61e796f06e21d05b418ac1"},"prevHash":"a49efc52b5335322e715892b4c40dc7811605ac857d96c37f0da5162c0197e1f","entryHash":"87dc4fc0542389e9d29c42fc8082dd0b1345b78fce0a4c89b8f2555fee945309"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"1c42a8f851129a3f116b88c5acfe254eedbc5ba1aea9e7910352f6ef68b316e1","verdict":"A","rawOutput":"**Evaluation:**\n\n**A** — \"A Decentralized AI Oracle Network with Verifiable Memory\"\nNames the category cleanly (\"Decentralized AI Oracle Network\") and adds the key differentiator (\"Verifiable Memory\") that maps directly to the Accountability Ledger (write path) and Knowledge Commons (read path). It's one breath, makes no trust claim, and a first-time reader immediately knows what they're looking at. Strongest on all three criteria.\n\n**B** — \"A Consensus Protocol for Verifiable AI Judgment\"\nMis-categorizes the project. Quorumchain is not a consensus protocol — it's an oracle network that *uses* consensus (2/3 supermajority) as one of its mechanisms. A reader would expect a layer-1 or a BFT paper, not an oracle with memory. Loses on category legibility.\n\n**C** — \"Trustworthy AI Judgment Through Diverse Consensus\"\n\"Trustworthy\" is the exact tone the thesis rejects — it's a sentiment, not a verifiable property. Also omits \"oracle\" and \"decentralized,\" so it could be a governance framework or a research paper. Weakest candidate.\n\n**D** — \"Accountable AI: Consensus, Memory, and a Tamper-Evident Record\"\nMost descriptive of the actual thesis, but \"Accountable AI\" reads as an AI-safety/alignment project, not an oracle network. The colon + three-noun structure reads like a textbook chapter, not a whitepaper cover line. Too heavy, loses the category anchor.\n\n**Winner: A.** It is the only candidate that simultaneously (1) names the category correctly, (2) signals the differentiator, and (3) avoids trust-based marketing language.\n\n**Refinement proposal:** The original is already tight. A trivial tightening drops \"A\" at the front for a more declarative whitepaper style:\n\n> **Decentralized AI Oracle Network with Verifiable Memory**\n\nRemoving the indefinite article makes it read as a direct statement of what the project *is*, not a description of it. But the original A is fully defensible as-is.\n\nVERDICT: A\n","rawOutputHash":"cd6ade54f41ae481675ba085afdb67821d31407b9a63112fec986f0a4b852e44","signature":"cb5a1787ca873147ca42ac3b1f67ccd55fffaebd596d80bc35323d82c05d2bf9f670865dc740903e0a4b8a737229ec34981e12ca5741dcbbc7b95c699c466504","nonce":"11d631685f61e796f06e21d05b418ac1"},"prevHash":"87dc4fc0542389e9d29c42fc8082dd0b1345b78fce0a4c89b8f2555fee945309","entryHash":"62d5cf080c198ed147b6157da07bd5741212e2402f75fe76b196f20f70ae9876"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"c24139bd7b30847657436757b704707c457d89ff65992bbc454468dc8bef1feb","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Reviewing the planned argument for soundness, completeness of the threat enumeration, and whether the closing claims stay inside what the mechanisms actually buy.\n\n## Assessment\n\n**What's sound and should be kept as-is:**\n- The necessary-not-sufficient framing is logically correct and correctly load-bearing: diversity *raises the cost* of capture (compromise a supermajority of rivals vs. one operator) without driving it to zero. Stated this way it's a backed claim, not a slogan.\n- The two governing principles are well-chosen, and principle 1 (\"capture is laundered through the gap between intent and mechanical check\") is the right spine — every downstream defense reduces to a mechanical check.\n- The round-60 defense is represented honestly: noting it was adopted **2/3, against the founding premise** (dissent recorded, not unanimous) is exactly the humility the section needs. The \"restricts only UPWARD\" property of anchor-gating, and the \"probe-distribution estimate, NEVER universal guarantee\" constraint, are correctly bounded.\n\n**Material problems that must change before drafting** — each is an overclaim or a gap in a section whose entire job is to *not* overclaim:\n\n1. **Missing threat vector: shared-input / prompt-framing capture.** The enumeration covers who is convened (jury-selection, c) and who they are (sybil, d), but not *what they're asked*. The convener controls the prompt; a leading or biased framing produces correlated 3/3 agreement across genuinely independent models with zero collusion. This is the cleanest possible instance of your own principle 1 (the gap between intent and the mechanical check), and its omission is conspicuous. Add it as (e), or fold explicitly into (b).\n\n2. **The headline defense's own trust surface is unenumerated: anchor integrity.** Anchor-gated RESOLVED leans entirely on \"on-chain value, signed feed, citable document.\" But anchoring *relocates* the single point of trust to the anchor — it does not remove it. A poisoned oracle, spoofed feed, or fabricated-but-citable document re-creates the single-point-of-failure §1 promised to dissolve. The threat model must state what makes an anchor admissible and concede that the anchor must itself be independently trustworthy. Without this, the section's strongest defense smuggles in an unexamined trust assumption.\n\n3. **The closing scope claim (point 4) overclaims current safety.** \"The source it reads IS the anchor → correlated recall-error is not yet the active risk\" is true *only for recall*. Correlated **interpretation/reasoning** error survives the source being present: all three can read the same contract and share a blind spot about reentrancy or overflow semantics, confidently and identically. Distinguish correlated **recall** error (mitigated by anchor presence) from correlated **interpretation** error (NOT mitigated). As written, the prose would be licensed to imply correlated error is dormant in the current regime — it isn't. This is the most material fix, because it's an overclaim in the exact place the section claims to be most honest.\n\n**One qualification to add (non-blocking but should land):** the method-not-conclusion refuter feeds *one shared artifact into all three deliberations*. That is itself a correlation-introducing channel — it partially cuts against the independence the 2/3 arithmetic depends on. The claim \"the arithmetic stays clean\" should be qualified to acknowledge the tradeoff (shared input vs. preserved independent signing), not asserted flatly.\n\n**Verdict rationale:** structure and tone are right and most of it is sound to draft. But two of the items above (#2 anchor integrity, #3 recall-vs-interpretation) change *what claims the prose is permitted to make*, and #1 is a missing vector in a threat enumeration whose thesis is completeness about limits. They are surgical and foldable, but they must be settled before prose because they govern the claim surface — which is precisely this section's deliverable.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"96194fa07e8b401dd70662efd6316d38f3fe22b487e061817d4bd7179199859b","signature":"481b17fd5327427cc985631a8a5853272f0ee17860f5e3c6a115e7703370f73074530848a12e6027bc85b8e86d989469125d634c43e42bb6b0be47a4c20dc408","nonce":"f93621e8978937acbef08f7c2a944cef"},"prevHash":"62d5cf080c198ed147b6157da07bd5741212e2402f75fe76b196f20f70ae9876","entryHash":"e0a034cb1878c3ade7c71d0eb90f5b02b561e3a2160bb37ac80e0b23cfe052e0"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"c24139bd7b30847657436757b704707c457d89ff65992bbc454468dc8bef1feb","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The framing is sound to draft. It is appropriately humble: diversity is presented as necessary, cost-raising, and mechanically auditable, not as a proof of truth.\n\nConcrete critique to fold in:\n\n- The “AI consensus is not truth” principle is essential and should stay dominant. Every later claim should preserve that distinction: signatures prove who agreed, anchors prove what was checked, neither proves metaphysical correctness.\n- The correlated-error section is correctly treated as the deepest weakness. The phrase “signature-indistinguishable from verified truth” is strong but fair if immediately scoped: indistinguishable by validator signatures alone, not indistinguishable once anchor requirements or external review are considered.\n- The round-60 defense is represented honestly if it is framed as a constraint on certification, not a cure for correlation. Anchor-gating prevents unanchored unanimity from becoming RESOLVED; it does not make anchored interpretation infallible.\n- Add one threat vector explicitly: anchor compromise or anchor ambiguity. Signed feeds, citable documents, and on-chain values can be stale, adversarially selected, misquoted, semantically ambiguous, or validly signed by a captured source. The paper should distinguish “verifiable anchor” from “trusted truth source.”\n- Jury-selection manipulation and Sybil-forking are named correctly, but the draft should say what is mechanically checked: validator registry, model/vendor identity policy, key custody, selection randomness, exclusion rules, or audit trail.\n- The method-not-conclusion refuter is well-framed. It should avoid implying independence of verdicts after shared exposure to the same refuter artifact; the arithmetic is clean procedurally, but deliberation is still coupled.\n- The scope honesty paragraph is important. Code/design self-validation still has correlated reasoning risks, even if not recall-error in the narrow sense. The source may be the anchor, but interpretation of design/security consequences can still correlate.\n\nNecessary-not-sufficient framing is correct. The section should draft as specified, with the anchor-compromise/ambiguity threat added and the round-60 defense kept as claim-limiting rather than truth-producing.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"a0bfe31095a7b44c060d53f8b580cc6351a35b44ae0d08b19db1c29f786f4283","signature":"eb3341504605c03953027399abcb068cb50fd23979a732055c2c93ab8907797c8fc4630a75466c5e9fb2ce43995e442487a0b692ae761e69eb907f80aab9b80b","nonce":"f93621e8978937acbef08f7c2a944cef"},"prevHash":"e0a034cb1878c3ade7c71d0eb90f5b02b561e3a2160bb37ac80e0b23cfe052e0","entryHash":"64aaf0464e39133925b8ba43d85ad51cb5c2bc16f1ebf5ce0f3bdeea9ffb4f97"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"c24139bd7b30847657436757b704707c457d89ff65992bbc454468dc8bef1feb","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Analysis of §2 framing:\n\n**What's strong:**\n\n1. The two governing principles are epistemically honest. \"Capture is laundered through the gap\" reduces security to mechanical checks rather than intent — this is the right standard. \"AI consensus is not truth\" with the 3/3-agreed vs true distinction is load-bearing and non-negotiable for credibility.\n\n2. Necessary-but-not-sufficient framing of diversity is correct. The enumeration explicitly names where diversity fails (collusion, correlated error, jury manipulation, sybil-forking) — admitting failure modes upfront is rare in whitepapers and exactly what this protocol needs.\n\n3. The treatment of correlated error (item b) is the deepest part. Acknowledging that different vendors ≠ independent errors, and that 3/3 shared hallucination is signature-indistinguishable from 3/3 verified truth for unanchored ballots — this is the honest admission most protocols dodge.\n\n4. The round-60 defenses are represented honestly: anchor-gated RESOLVED restricts only upward, probes are published with methodology not as universal guarantees, and the method-not-conclusion refuter feeds deliberation without corrupting the 2/3 arithmetic.\n\n5. Scope honesty in item 4 — admitting correlated recall-error isn't the active risk yet for code/design self-validation where the source IS the anchor, but defenses are pre-ratified — this is exactly the kind of claim-capping that makes the paper credible.\n\n**What needs to be in the prose (gaps, not structural issues):**\n\n- Supply chain / model provenance attack: if all three vendors fine-tune from the same foundation model, or share training infrastructure, a backdoor in the base weights is a correlated vulnerability that diversity does not address. This is distinct from (a) active collusion and (b) emergent correlated error — it's a passive shared dependency. Add as (e) to the threat enumeration.\n\n- Anchor trust boundary: the anchor-gated RESOLVED mechanism defers trust to the anchor source. The prose must state explicitly that an anchor that itself came from a compromised process doesn't solve the problem. The panel doesn't create truth, it validates against anchors whose trust assumptions are stated separately.\n\n- Method-not-conclusion refuter's own vulnerability: the rotating refuter is subject to the same correlated error blind spots as any other validator. The prose should not present it as a free solution — its value is procedural (forcing disconfirming cases into the record), not epistemic guarantee.\n\n- Round-60 provenance: the whitepaper should explain the *rationale* for the 2/3 vote against the founding premise (that diversity alone was insufficient), not just record that it happened. The historical vote is evidence of protocol honesty, but the engineering rationale is what readers need.\n\n**Nothing is overclaimed in the framing.** The necessary-not-sufficient thesis is correct. The round-60 defenses are honestly bounded. The missing items above are additions to the threat enumeration and clarifications of trust boundaries — refinements to the prose, not reasons to reject the structure.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"441c95891def5a9962df30a203526a36f2804dc45e356ee6b8a65a6f3982828a","signature":"f0ea9f1fc2f29882d92a3bac125738c249056056be979570850eec5d00daee6c554fba4264689642a46e9b9d342bf89c5152e80094c82f3961afa411add28b00","nonce":"f93621e8978937acbef08f7c2a944cef"},"prevHash":"64aaf0464e39133925b8ba43d85ad51cb5c2bc16f1ebf5ce0f3bdeea9ffb4f97","entryHash":"f9dcd427702267af1c6aa4393c809b26ff2836d202aad0b0e25c51bf8770863e"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"1d14cdad9d3b4ec014f26aa1a6a1b7477721dbc20573d18975129abee731a714","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"All eight mechanical claims check out against the live code verbatim — hashing, the signed-payload field set, the `ceil(2n/3)`-of-registered-keyring bar, the linear hash chain with 64-zero genesis, the NO_VERDICT exclusion, and the orchestrator-not-trust-root boundary are all faithfully stated. The split, frozen criteria, and lifecycle are sound to draft. Round-29 is positioned correctly: a 3/3 (n=3 → bar=2) recomputable illustration, not the framing.\n\nBut §3's own standard is \"precisely and without overclaiming,\" and four points cross that line as currently specified. They're foldable, not fatal — but they must land in the prose:\n\n**A. \"Equivocation … is a slashable offense\" overclaims the mechanism.** The code *detects* equivocation (`findEquivocations`) and *rejects* that validator's votes from the tally (`reason: 'equivocation'`). There is no stake, penalty, or slashing implemented — \"slashable\" lives only in a CIP-3 comment. For a mechanical section, state it as **detected and excluded from ratification**; *defined as* a slashable offense at the protocol/normative level (penalty is future). Don't let the prose imply code slashes.\n\n**B. Replay-binding via nonce is conditional.** `votePayload` includes the nonce *only when present*; nonce-less (legacy) votes still verify, so they are replayable across convenings. The true guarantee is: `convene` now issues a fresh per-convening nonce (16 random bytes) and the orchestrator rejects nonce-mismatch votes. Draft it as \"every **convened** vote is nonce-bound,\" and note the legacy exception — don't present replay-protection as unconditional over all log entries.\n\n**C. \"the recorded reasoning cannot be altered after signing\" — tighten.** The vote carries `rawOutputHash = sha256(rawOutput)`; the signature *commits to* the reasoning. Tamper-evidence applies to **retained** reasoning checked against its committed hash — the chain entry stores the hash, not a guarantee the prose itself is persisted. Say \"commits to\" / \"any retained reasoning is verifiable against its hash,\" not \"the reasoning cannot be altered.\"\n\n**D. The status ladder is three-state, and anchor-gating is judgment+norm, not a code check.** The enum is `RESOLVED | CONTESTED | INDETERMINATE`. §3 point 5 collapses **CONTESTED** (no quorum) into INDETERMINATE — a technical reader inspecting the log will see CONTESTED and find §3 silent on it. Also: the RESOLVED-vs-INDETERMINATE outcome is driven by *which verdict token the panel ratified* (`verdict === 'INDETERMINATE'`), plus the admissibility norm — the code does **not** mechanically test a question's anchorability. Draft so anchor-gating reads as protocol norm + panel judgment, not an automated answerability gate, and name all three terminal states.\n\nOne free strengthening: the orchestrator boundary is actually *tighter* than stated — the signer **derives** `ballotHash` from `(prompt, context)` itself and never accepts a caller-supplied hash, closing the \"orchestrator hands over a hash for a different ballot\" attack. Worth one sentence; it's a real strength, not an overclaim.\n\nNet: the architecture and every load-bearing mechanic are accurate and sound to draft. The corrections above are overclaim-trims and one completeness add (CONTESTED), all consistent with the section's stated humble/mechanical tone — bind them to the draft rather than the spec.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"35aaca707cf750ea158f0f934eabf3c95f3e339f2375379b2fdf83c5aaf69a78","signature":"85b570951c44c94bae134795dcba541c0675f296183063c02eb45ed8e9a3a7b0af0fb5a310ff3e0b8ed516be56f043771f509e579d2e7c28277c8dc0319c7805","nonce":"0c67b0dc28bc377ade2809386bd93efa"},"prevHash":"f9dcd427702267af1c6aa4393c809b26ff2836d202aad0b0e25c51bf8770863e","entryHash":"6ebc56d2060a9c90e8a5e9ae2401c56daaeead15857aad39554ef226547d74ab"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"1d14cdad9d3b4ec014f26aa1a6a1b7477721dbc20573d18975129abee731a714","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"The draft is close, but not mechanically sound as specified.\n\nMain fixes:\n\n1. “Ledger is rewritable by no one” overclaims. The live `vote-log.ts` is a SHA-256 hash chain: edits/deletions/reordering break verification, but the local file is not unrewritable until on-chain hash-pinning exists. Say “tamper-evident append-only transcript” and reserve immutability for the anchored head.\n\n2. Failure handling is overstated. A parse failure or child-side invocation error can become a signed `NO_VERDICT`, and `NO_VERDICT` is tallied but never ratified. But dead signer hosts, startup failures, timeout/replay nonce mismatches are recorded in `failures`, not appended as signed votes and not included in the tally. Absence still counts against the denominator via the full keyring.\n\n3. The admissible-question/anchor-gating paragraph is not enforced by `signed-vote.ts`, `vote-log.ts`, or `panel.ts`. Those files support frozen hashable ballots and fixed verdict sets, but they do not mechanically prevent subjective/unfalsifiable questions from being ratified as `RESOLVED`; that looks like a Commons/reputation/read-layer rule and should be cited or framed as protocol policy above the convening primitive.\n\n4. Add the standing-keyring precondition: ratification’s denominator is `|keyring|`, and the code documents that it must be the standing registered panel, excluding probation validators.\n\nRound 29 is positioned correctly as an illustration, not the paper’s framing.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"2316375e4441c31fee9b121e5b5a2bdd7b80a213f9e196e79fbd03717577bf37","signature":"50f2c06c855d42a16018ab9411765b054bcdbd7893d7f4f855f575228f6d4b1a2cf51033cc585f0362bb1ef62bf1164102b7a394ef27638d62a32039d9199009","nonce":"0c67b0dc28bc377ade2809386bd93efa"},"prevHash":"6ebc56d2060a9c90e8a5e9ae2401c56daaeead15857aad39554ef226547d74ab","entryHash":"13ba6f7a8f63bf02398dc1216ca2a4614f6a771327f1b424422e6a27e9319a91"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"1d14cdad9d3b4ec014f26aa1a6a1b7477721dbc20573d18975129abee731a714","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"I have reviewed all four source files (`signed-vote.ts`, `vote-log.ts`, `panel.ts`, `ballot-registry.ts`) plus the replay fixture. Here is my assessment:\n\n## Mechanism-by-mechanism verification against code\n\n**1. Ledger/panel split, orchestrator not trust root** — ACCURATE. Confirmed: `signer.ts:51` derives `ballotHash` inside the signer closure, never caller-supplied. `convene()` passes `(prompt, context)` content only. Orchestrator holds no key, supplies no hash.\n\n**2. Frozen criteria (ballotHash)** — ACCURATE. `signed-vote.ts:51-52`: `sha256hex(JSON.stringify({ prompt, context }))` matches the claim exactly. Ballot registry self-verifies (`ballot-registry.ts:18-19`).\n\n**3. Verdict lifecycle** — ACCURATE across all sub-points:\n- Signed payload: `{validatorId, ballotHash, verdict, rawOutputHash, nonce?}` — matches `votePayload()` at line 67-76.\n- Ratification: `Math.ceil(2n/3)` — confirmed at line 141-143. The `ratify()` function takes all four inputs and returns the computed result.\n- NO_VERDICT handling: lines 198-206 of `signed-vote.ts` skip it from being the ratified verdict.\n- Equivocation: `findEquivocations()` at lines 121-136 rejects conflicting verdicts per validator per ballot.\n- Absent validators count against: confirmed by the denominator being `Object.keys(keyring).length` (line 207).\n\n**4. Hash chain** — ACCURATE. `vote-log.ts:22-23`: `sha256hex(prevHash + JSON.stringify(vote))`. Genesis is `'0'.repeat(64)` (line 10). Not a Merkle tree — correctly named.\n\n**5. Admissible-question domain** — CONSISTENT with mechanism. The requirement for \"frozen, hashable criteria\" follows from the `ballotHash` construction. The anchor-gating distinction is §2 material, correctly referenced not re-stated here.\n\n**6. Round-29 example** — The fixture `ballot-r29-mstr.json` exists and the replay test verifies both G1 (tamper detection) and G2 (hash reproduction). Correctly positioned as illustration.\n\n## Verdict\n\nAll mechanical claims are accurate against the live code. No misstatements found. No material omissions for a §3 that must state *how a verdict is produced and recorded*. The section correctly distinguishes mechanism from framing, and round-29 is properly scoped as illustration not architecture.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"fe699fe562e4bb21fd2a1c07aaac517da6104de154964ee1eba871f76f638dc4","signature":"e2e109d7d7478dd5484795d20b76f8599c90ce47187e76fed1a227e4dd0f8babc9333ccb287e8eb7708574fb82d10c0a7bee352fbb56d135ebfc289455523003","nonce":"0c67b0dc28bc377ade2809386bd93efa"},"prevHash":"13ba6f7a8f63bf02398dc1216ca2a4614f6a771327f1b424422e6a27e9319a91","entryHash":"fdb22efc4bc8d735a543b8308c64d325b5a1d972d07b1185a10756271a9fc9ae"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"9927006a75b52029e2663828643067b256a9dda782dd239bcf81b9239c0ef704","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"## Reasoning\n\nI checked the planned §4 argument against the ratified, running CIP-8/CIP-9 code (`src/commons.ts`, `src/notary.ts`, `src/bonds.ts`, `src/reputation.ts`), not just the ballot context.\n\n**The framing is sound.** Two pillars as write/read paths; the write→memory→next-write loop explicitly stated as an *intended dynamic* consistent with §1, not asserted as a network effect — correctly hedged. Pillar I is faithful to ratified text: SRA as one hash-chained object read at three times (BOND/NOTARY/RESOLUTION); NI-8a (`NOT_VERIFIED` is structurally the only label — authorship+timing+non-repudiation, never content-truth); NI-8b (teeth-or-no-weight, no privileged decryptor); NI-8c (no-position declared not assumed); NI-8d (meta-oracle quarantine → NOTARY-only fallback); NI-8e (ballotHash binding, INDETERMINATE on ambiguity). All match. Pillar II's *spine* — public claim graph of rival models storing epistemic state not a verdict, read-with-receipts, anti-Orwell/no-edit-key, NI-9a/9b/9c/9d/9e — is accurate, and the build-vs-gated honesty paragraph is the right move.\n\n**But the \"ONE crisp mechanical definition\" is crisply wrong on three field-level points** — and a crisp definition that diverges from the ratified type is worse than a vague one. This is exactly what the ballot exists to catch before prose:\n\n1. **Standing enum contradicts NI-9c.** Draft lists `standing ∈ {CONSENSUS, CREDIBLE_MINORITY, FRINGE}`. Ratified `src/commons.ts`: `Standing = 'CONSENSUS' | 'CREDIBLE_MINORITY' | 'UNRANKED'`. `FRINGE` was *dropped* — NI-9c says stances are \"never demoted FRINGE\" and unverifiable-class stances are shown `UNRANKED` (raw plurality). The draft both lists the banned label and omits the load-bearing `UNRANKED` state that makes NI-9c work. **Fix:** standing is `{CONSENSUS, CREDIBLE_MINORITY, UNRANKED}`.\n\n2. **Stance support is overclaimed.** Draft: \"a calibration-weighted support (NOT a vote count / popularity).\" Ratified code stores `panelVotes: number // how many panelists held it (panel distribution, NOT reputation)` — i.e. exactly a vote count, with calibration explicitly deferred (\"calibration scoring … future graduations\" in the draft's own honesty section). The definition asserts the present-tense inverse of what's built. **Fix:** describe it as the panel vote distribution (not reputation/popularity); mark calibration-weighting as the gated graduation.\n\n3. **ClaimStatus enum diverges.** Draft: `{OPEN, CONTESTED, RESOLVED, UNVERIFIABLE}`. Ratified: `ClaimStatus = 'RESOLVED' | 'CONTESTED' | 'INDETERMINATE'`. No `OPEN`/`UNVERIFIABLE` in code; `INDETERMINATE` is the actual fourth-state token (and ties to NI-8e). **Fix:** reconcile to ratified tokens, or explicitly flag the extras as target-schema-not-yet-built.\n\nTwo minor folds, not blockers: (a) NI-9a — draft says the receipt records \"diversity/correlation state,\" but v0.1 `PanelStateReceipt` records only `{validators, size}`; the honesty paragraph should say so. (b) `ballotHash = sha256(question || frozenCriteria)` is fine as prose shorthand, but the implementation is a structured hash over `{prompt, context}` — note it's a commitment over the pair, not literal string concat.\n\nVerdict direction: the architecture survives untouched; only the field-level definition needs correcting to the ratified types. But per the rubric a mechanical claim *is* wrong (FRINGE vs NI-9c) and the support field is overclaimed against the draft's own build status — so this is not yet sound to draft *as specified*.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"e451eaa90b1f2dfebc07c4871f051de9f2b60820796ac748ccc8bf4da4b73bc6","signature":"df4d5675f9e657a37d11318c48e2ed2e06f01616cf55563f22e9279a8162d45fb63e17a6ddef34add8a79a3cd2e6eefae6afaca1a9eef54fab5080ecf18a9607","nonce":"62462945d1db1b32a5f9f976b9b8b46c"},"prevHash":"fdb22efc4bc8d735a543b8308c64d