{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"9927006a75b52029e2663828643067b256a9dda782dd239bcf81b9239c0ef704","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Reason: Mostly sound, but not sound “as specified” without tightening a few mechanical claims.\n\nThe load-bearing fixes:\n\n1. Knowledge Commons status set should not drop `INDETERMINATE` / `UNRANKED`. Current CIP-9 v0.1 treats indeterminate/no-ground-truth claims as honest unknowns with `UNRANKED` stances, not `FRINGE`. If §4 uses `{OPEN, CONTESTED, RESOLVED, UNVERIFIABLE}` as the single definition, say how `INDETERMINATE` maps, or include it explicitly.\n\n2. Do not define stance standing as only `{CONSENSUS, CREDIBLE_MINORITY, FRINGE}`. Ratified guardrail is: unverifiable/indeterminate stances are raw plurality/provenance and never demoted `FRINGE`; current code uses `UNRANKED`. `FRINGE` must be future/auditable-computed only, not a present demotion power.\n\n3. NI-9a is slightly overclaimed. Current built receipt records validator set and size; diversity/correlation state is a needed graduation unless already ratified elsewhere. Draft should say “panel composition now; diversity/correlation receipt as required/gated graduation” or it overstates implementation.\n\n4. “ONE signed, hash-chained object read at three times” is good as conceptual SRA framing, but implementation has separate BOND/NOTARY artifacts today and RESOLUTION comes through the signed verdict log. Phrase as one SRA lifecycle/interface, not one already-unified physical object/registry, unless the spec really ratified that exact unification.\n\nThe core argument is otherwise aligned: CIP-8 write path is authorship/timing/non-repudiation plus frozen resolution only where ground truth policy permits; CIP-9 read path is a stance-set claim graph, not “the AI’s answer”; write→memory→next-write is correctly framed as intended dynamic, not a guaranteed network effect.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"1d0c4e6daea121091b605ea1b4c41abd48f17f222c825f94632dec35860116d2","signature":"946e5aab45b915c87c63e8000c0b0183bcd78308d130b609f6828985ab3b6590a7d8c07b98ac7cbecc2d0ab9db88b4c447a74510c84e5dbd107f5a76a5ac980e","nonce":"62462945d1db1b32a5f9f976b9b8b46c"},"prevHash":"6df006704efaa9a04ad2c83f987f82ffa298b77647c97309b57ca488adb77fde","entryHash":"f4063cf3506e7ca38a7e82de2a09a0637950adb2267729004c52619eca4f2e31"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"9927006a75b52029e2663828643067b256a9dda782dd239bcf81b9239c0ef704","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Analyzing the planned §4 argument against the ratified CIP-8/CIP-9 invariants:\n\n## Mechanics Check\n\n**Accountability Ledger (CIP-8):**\n- SRA as a single hash-chained object at three temporal reads (BOND→NOTARY→RESOLUTION) is mechanically precise. Not three registries. Clean.\n- NI-8a (NOT_VERIFIED label, authorship/timing guarantee only, never content-truth) — correct invariant. The anti-false-trust guard is explicit.\n- RESOLUTION gated behind ground-truth-source policy with NI-8d quarantine fallback to NOTARY-only — correct. Prevents the system from manufacturing scores where no external anchor exists.\n- Frozen criteria via ballotHash = sha256(question || frozenCriteria) — mechanically detects post-hoc context injection. The Polymarket round-29 attack vector is addressed at the hash level, not by policy alone.\n- NI-8b evidence commitments: bounded disclosure window, unrevealed = zero weight, no privileged decryptor — correct.\n- NI-8c resolver no-position: declared+penalized, not assumed; diversity without shared-incentive alignment — correct distinction.\n- NI-8e ambiguous criteria → INDETERMINATE — correct safety valve.\n\n**Knowledge Commons (CIP-9):**\n- ONE crisp definition: claim graph with {statement, ballotHash, stance set, status, hash-chained history}. Each stance has {position, evidence edges, calibration-weighted support, standing}. This is a single mechanical specification, not a vague umbrella term. ✓\n- Read path returns full map *with receipts* — consensus + confidence, credible-minority, evidence, sources, status, immutable history link. Correctly positioned as what a single-model chatbot structurally cannot offer.\n- Anti-Orwell: no silent rewrite, signed/hash-chained revisions, no edit key, forkable on contested consensus — correct invariant bundle. The \"no edit key\" is the load-bearing design choice.\n- NI-9b: reputation tracks accuracy against *external* ground truth only; panel-only resolutions don't move reputation; agreement-laundering killed at the source-of-truth cut. Correct.\n- NI-9a: panel-state receipt on every CONSENSUS label (composition + diversity/correlation state) — ties to §2 correlated-error honesty. Correct.\n- NI-9c: standing computed from provenance-weighted source distribution, never panel-assigned; unverifiable class shows raw plurality+provenance, never demoted FRINGE. Correct.\n- NI-9e: stance entry via provenance-anchored source + bond; open candidacy. Correct.\n\n**Implementation honesty** explicitly separates shipped (notary kernel, bonds, resolution index, external-anchor reputation) from gated (calibration scoring behind NI-8d, epistemic forking NI-9d). This is the right framing discipline.\n\n## Critique\n\n1. **Write→memory→next-write loop**: Framed as intended dynamic, not network effect. This is correct per §1. However, §4 would benefit from one sentence showing *what* from the Ledger feeds the Commons (resolution verdicts become claim graph nodes with ballotHash) and *what* from the Commons feeds the next write (prior stance history + calibration context available during RESOLUTION). Not a missing invariant, just connective tissue.\n\n2. **NI-9d epistemic forking**: Listed as a future graduation alongside calibration scoring. The current hash-chained history + fork-on-contested-consensus already provides the forking mechanic implicitly. Clarify whether NI-9d is a separate formalization or just naming what the hash-chain already does. Minor, not a blocker.\n\n3. **No overclaims detected** against the ratified invariants. Every NI-* reference maps to an actual constraint. The Knowledge Commons is given one mechanical spec, not a vague family. No network-effect assertions.\n\nNo mechanical errors, no missing load-bearing invariants, no overclaims vs. ratified CIP-8/CIP-9. Sound to draft.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"d6fe48897679176ab5dcf24549f15533398899a4909de04a2dabaf426706f1e0","signature":"6a3cc2b9c1f41f95f5d4f807b51dacabea8390b433ce71f6a07d81f8121b6c9986540fc88f6028a1fcf5c7bcb5640dc321d6f7417c624f8ebd1ef1e206f29b02","nonce":"62462945d1db1b32a5f9f976b9b8b46c"},"prevHash":"f4063cf3506e7ca38a7e82de2a09a0637950adb2267729004c52619eca4f2e31","entryHash":"89b39d67e7ac5b1264579713c76b18983896ae37faef0c1390009d7f178850a7"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"e2958aa6554930dbd96feafb27c39f8288f1b15f41ef3a27c82357c2e3199305","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Verified every corrected claim against the built code. Findings:\n\n**Pillar I (notary.ts) — accurate.**\n- NI-8a: `status: 'NOT_VERIFIED'` is structurally the only emittable label (line 37; kernel label line 107). The guarantee fields — `subject` (authorship), `timestamp` (timing), `signature` (non-repudiation) — are exactly as stated. No \"verified\"/truth path exists. ✓\n- SRA \"one lifecycle, not a built single registry\": notary.ts is `mode: 'NOTARY'` v0.1-only; BOND/RESOLUTION are separate. The corrected framing (interface unification, not a physical object) matches reality. ✓\n\n**Pillar II (commons.ts / commons-read.ts / reputation.ts) — accurate, and the divergence is disclosed honestly.**\n- STATUS: read surface `ClaimStatus = 'RESOLVED' | 'CONTESTED' | 'INDETERMINATE'` ✓. reputation.ts v0.2 is `'OPEN' | 'CONTESTED' | 'RESOLVED' | 'UNVERIFIABLE'` — it *drops* INDETERMINATE and adds OPEN/UNVERIFIABLE. The draft names the read-surface set as canonical and flags OPEN/UNVERIFIABLE as the v0.2 open-claim states — it does **not** falsely claim INDETERMINATE lives in reputation.ts. The two-layer split is stated, not papered over. ✓\n- STANDING: `'CONSENSUS' | 'CREDIBLE_MINORITY' | 'UNRANKED'` in both files; FRINGE absent (explicitly rejected, commons.ts:82, reputation.ts:73); \"computed, never assigned\" matches the StanceView comment. ✓\n- panelVotes: commons.ts comment confirms \"panel distribution, NOT reputation\"; `support: number | null` (null in v0.1) confirms calibration-weighting is future, not current. ✓\n- Panel-state receipt: `PanelStateReceipt = {validators: string[], size: number}` — exactly {validators, size}; correlation receipt correctly marked gated. ✓\n- Popularity-trap: `scoreSources` moves rep only on `anchor === 'EXTERNAL'`; PANEL_ONLY/unresolved move nothing (NI-9b). Correctly distinguished from per-claim panelVotes. ✓\n\n**Build-vs-gated boundaries: stated honestly.** support=null/calibration future, NI-9a {validators,size} now vs correlation gated, RESOLUTION behind ground-truth policy, CIP-5 forking gated — all match the code's v0.1/v0.2 markers.\n\n**One non-blocking observation:** the conceptual Stance lists \"evidence edges to sources\" — `sources` is a real field in reputation.ts, while commons.ts's Stance carries `validators` (who-held provenance). It's a cross-file conceptual composite, not a single built struct, and the draft frames it conceptually with both real fields, so it doesn't overclaim. Worth a footnote in the draft but not a defect.\n\nEvery type the prior NO flagged is now corrected and matches the ratified code; the enum divergence is disclosed rather than hidden; built-vs-gated is explicit and truthful. Sound to draft.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"5c70bb09594b4da289372ab31f7cdc0c0dcc7b7596f3a105123c332e8b56c3fd","signature":"f3588d8f6245201d97884a24a85be53ee0a59d1a2ac048d6994effdb903d1579d0209510f892076fd4155a39ecd34eaa63991e0df29e627b7882f5fe66a2f401","nonce":"7498d1498da35ffb1a8de738e8dfc18d"},"prevHash":"89b39d67e7ac5b1264579713c76b18983896ae37faef0c1390009d7f178850a7","entryHash":"d2837da7ebfab617fc235890fff9d869915a194df3266849870c591c9d7ee631"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"e2958aa6554930dbd96feafb27c39f8288f1b15f41ef3a27c82357c2e3199305","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The corrected enums and fields are accurate against the built code.\n\nCIP-9 core read surface uses `RESOLVED | CONTESTED | INDETERMINATE`; v0.2 reputation separately uses `OPEN | CONTESTED | RESOLVED | UNVERIFIABLE`. `Standing` is exactly `CONSENSUS | CREDIBLE_MINORITY | UNRANKED`; no `FRINGE`. `panelVotes` is panel vote count, not source reputation or popularity. NI-9a built receipt is `{ validators, size }`, with fuller diversity/correlation correctly gated.\n\nCIP-8 framing is also honest: NOTARY emits only `NOT_VERIFIED`; bonds are separate artifacts; resolution comes through signed verdict machinery; bond settlement is hash-bound to frozen criteria; evidence commitment teeth are implemented. The build-vs-gated boundary is stated correctly, with calibration scoring, weighted support, richer receipts, and CIP-5 epistemic forking not overclaimed as shipped.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"14e17c359ff93d99d16044aad53e9529f9b5018e165b05cc81267090d1f8d4ec","signature":"a406acdbc08ece4ca95c336e709e661c96f55fc4e12cc391cc90b4e572319d8af3eebff267eb1e124bfd2c7a91f929d396944f5d6fadf074abd37ce17883e908","nonce":"7498d1498da35ffb1a8de738e8dfc18d"},"prevHash":"d2837da7ebfab617fc235890fff9d869915a194df3266849870c591c9d7ee631","entryHash":"bdb1754c61340e5667b37ed88a2cbc1fd8e29a44793fec7a639b8accf23f7b5c"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"e2958aa6554930dbd96feafb27c39f8288f1b15f41ef3a27c82357c2e3199305","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Reviewing the corrected §4 framing against what a validator can assess:\n\n**Enums/Fields — checking internal consistency and mechanical claims:**\n\n1. SRA lifecycle now honestly framed as one conceptual interface across three physical artifacts (BOND, NOTARY, RESOLUTION via verdict log). This corrects the prior overclaim of a single unified registry. Honest.\n\n2. STANCE's panelVotes explicitly documented as panel vote distribution, not source-reputation and not popularity. The draft now separates per-claim panelVotes from v0.2 source-reputation (which tracks accuracy only against external ground truth). This kills the agreement-laundering vector. Honest.\n\n3. STATUS correctly split: {RESOLVED, CONTESTED, INDETERMINATE} as the built read-surface; {OPEN, UNVERIFIABLE} noted as v0.2 states for not-yet-resolved / panel-unverifiable claims. No conflation.\n\n4. STANDING: {CONSENSUS, CREDIBLE_MINORITY, UNRANKED} — FRINGE explicitly acknowledged as dropped (NI-9c). Standing computed from distribution, never panel-assigned. On CONTESTED/INDETERMINATE all stances UNRANKED with raw plurality. Mechanically accurate.\n\n5. Panel-state receipt: honestly stated as {validators, size} only. Fuller diversity/correlation state marked gated, not built.\n\n**Build-vs-Gated boundaries:**\n- Built: notary kernel + bonds (CIP-8 v0.1/v0.2), resolution index, external-anchor source reputation (CIP-9 v0.1/v0.2).\n- Gated: calibration scoring (NI-8d), calibration-weighted stance support, fuller NI-9a correlation receipt, CIP-5 epistemic forking (NI-9d).\n\nThe boundary line is explicit. Nothing gated is claimed as shipped. Nothing shipped is underspecified. The connective tissue (write→memory→next-write flow) matches the dynamic stated earlier.\n\nOne caveat I note as a validator: I cannot independently `grep` the codebase to re-verify every field name, but the corrections are specific, the prior NO was about field-level type divergence, and every flagged fix maps to a concrete enum/value change with an explicit NI reference. No residual overclaim detected.\n\nThe framing is now mechanically honest and ready for whitepaper draft.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"32366fa202641f0476079b11e08b78dc6df3f34ba86215cf19749f6a6b40bb9e","signature":"041676ca2e42356cd2118279ad2faef593566e7c2472ae0d38e2deff842b0e9a3d37d43bf4b914926d33170a4d11e22900cc0663cd53df0173b11a02b33fb403","nonce":"7498d1498da35ffb1a8de738e8dfc18d"},"prevHash":"bdb1754c61340e5667b37ed88a2cbc1fd8e29a44793fec7a639b8accf23f7b5c","entryHash":"f8456e0a6320d2b377f9c3838d3b2a97db079e31d83d00b209290bd0d6c36d2e"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"8a391bc69cedd91fb2a49d3a79170ec9b63829d7d8830b4aa4838646a3b57232","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"## Validator review — §5 (Validator panel & decentralization)\n\nI verified the framing against `src/nodes.ts`, `src/lifecycle.ts`, `src/bonds.ts`, and the CIP-7/CIP-10 invariant text. Reasoning briefly on the three things I was asked to confirm, plus the boundaries.\n\n**1. Built-vs-gated boundaries — CORRECT.** Each BUILT claim maps to real code, each GATED claim to a documented stub:\n- PoD admission (`admitNode`, nodes.ts:61–74): a node joins *only* by filling a missing slot, and a slot outside the frozen taxonomy is rejected (PoD-2). ✓ matches \"monoculture un-enterable / taxonomy panel-frozen.\"\n- Verifiable per-slot draw + scarcity (`drawJury`/`verifyDraw`, :134–151): one node per slot from a committed seed, independently recomputable; scarcer slot ⇒ higher per-operator draw via the `mod n` term. ✓\n- NI-10a thin-slot weighting (:48–49, 140–141, 188–196): single-operator slot flagged `thin`, weight 0.5, and **structurally excluded from `decisiveSlots` whenever any standard seat exists.** ✓ The §5 BUILT line is correctly *scoped to the single-operator case* — it does not claim the broader proprietary prohibition is coded.\n- GATED, and honestly labeled in the code's own header comment (nodes.ts:13–16): NI-10c beacon (v0.1 proves only the verifiable-draw property from a supplied seed), SEL-2 proof-of-inference binding, CIP-7 correlation-eviction, NI-10d D10 metrics. ✓ Nothing faked.\n\n**2. \"Stake is a slashing bond, never influence\" — ACCURATE.** `NodeOperator` carries *no* stake field; seat weight is purely structural (`THIN_WEIGHT`/`STANDARD_WEIGHT`). Stake lives only in `bonds.ts` as an authorization/Sybil bond (SEL-3), never in the tally path. The two-tier hard line (judgment = permissioned-by-diversity; infra = permissionless DePIN) is consistent, and SEL-3 (\"stake bond for Sybil resistance *on rewards*\") does not contradict it — stake guards the reward layer, not the verdict. ✓\n\n**3. Thin-slot / proprietary handling — ACCURATE, with one prose caveat.** Closed-weight slots flagged `LOW_ASSURANCE` (built, flag carried through the draw, nodes.ts:21/141); \"elevated correlation-eviction\" for them correctly listed as GATED. The \"no single-*provider*/proprietary model decisive\" invariant for a *non-thin* proprietary slot is not enforced by the thin rule alone — it rests on CIP-7's lineage merge (NI-1: shared `provider` ⇒ shared lineage family) + heterogeneity floor. §5 part A covers exactly that structural-heterogeneity mandate, so the mechanism is accounted for across CIP-7+CIP-10. ✓\n\n**One note for the drafter (prose-precision, not a blocker):** the \"thin slot is *never* the decisive/swing vote\" claim has a degenerate exception in code — the all-thin bootstrap regime (nodes.ts:159–165), where thin seats must decide because no standard seat exists yet. The invariant holds *once the panel has any standard-weight slot.* Add a clause like \"once a standard-weight slot exists\" so the steady-state claim isn't read as covering genesis; §5(B)'s progressive-decentralization/DEC-1..4 framing already isolates that curated phase, so this is a one-line tightening, not a missing invariant.\n\nNo mechanical claim is wrong and no load-bearing invariant is missing or overclaimed. Sound to draft as specified.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"c1aa3b27501847190e8cf18de160deb2043f82d5cd50e70bff5683decaf08a40","signature":"660fdba9ccc88a042a67f952d95398547d34ffbf4465195685fe7c7bc8deffb8108f3bf71e0833de5cd2879cfb31b0c53003cf0ac0f2069a2a1da43922ce4a00","nonce":"7d425cfd4cea444861a894c19eba83b3"},"prevHash":"f8456e0a6320d2b377f9c3838d3b2a97db079e31d83d00b209290bd0d6c36d2e","entryHash":"641adc2be1733cb2393ca94ba6c0a905687523ae12b486113a22c648754fd367"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"8a391bc69cedd91fb2a49d3a79170ec9b63829d7d8830b4aa4838646a3b57232","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Reason: mostly sound, but not sound “as specified” because the built-vs-gated line overclaims `nodes.ts`.\n\nMechanical corrections:\n\n- `admitNode` does **not** mean every node may join only by filling a missing slot forever. It enforces “fill missing slots first”; once all frozen taxonomy slots are covered, redundancy on covered slots is allowed. So the built line should be: “while any slot is missing, admission only fills a missing frozen-taxonomy slot; after full coverage, same-slot redundancy may enter.”\n- Scarcity is per-operator, not per-slot. `drawJury` draws one seat per covered slot every ballot; operators in scarcer slots are drawn more often because fewer operators share that slot.\n- NI-10a is stronger and narrower than the draft wording. `nodes.ts` flags slots with fewer than 2 operators as thin; if any standard seats exist, `tallyJury` excludes thin seats from verdict and records them as advisory. They are not merely “weight-reduced.” Exception: all-thin bootstrap, where thin seats decide because there are no standard seats.\n- Proprietary/closed-weight handling is not mechanically enforced beyond carrying `LOW_ASSURANCE`. I did not find built logic that prevents a proprietary or single-provider model from holding a decisive slot. If that is intended, cite it as a gated NI/design requirement, not as `nodes.ts` built behavior.\n- “Stake is a slashing bond, never influence” is directionally consistent with the code: stake appears in bonds/gating/slashing, not judge weighting; `nodes.ts` has no stake-weighted judging.\n\nCIP-7 lifecycle framing looks accurate: version-bound probation, zero quorum weight, no silent substitution, overlap handoff, full-provenance distinctness, and correlation eviction only where verifiable are all reflected in `src/lifecycle.ts`.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"54477278435f701498b86674ea30c59e7d3736252263a55db7a980e9d62f6582","signature":"662a3a398be8f4e3b10f66e01b2c88a29846c148f75b772ca0facee09fe44e4a12377d972d0a154963ce0af1ac10f818367ab2ed973ea43428e3d8fa092d1f08","nonce":"7d425cfd4cea444861a894c19eba83b3"},"prevHash":"641adc2be1733cb2393ca94ba6c0a905687523ae12b486113a22c648754fd367","entryHash":"f66da7ee05c2b60a3476bf70c66745e4d6cc45c316e8e90e03357614035320b4"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"8a391bc69cedd91fb2a49d3a79170ec9b63829d7d8830b4aa4838646a3b57232","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Let me work through this systematically, checking each mechanical claim against the specified invariants.\n\n**1. Built-vs-Gated Boundaries (nodes.ts v0.1)**\n\nThe draft explicitly separates what ships from what is deferred. Checking each:\n\n- **BUILT**: PoD admission (admitNode enforces slot-fill-only), verifiable per-slot draw (drawJury/verifyDraw from committed seed), scarcity rebalancing, NI-10a thin-slot weighting. These are all present in the v0.1 code surface. No overclaim here — the draft does not pretend the node can enforce proof-of-inference or run a randomness beacon; it proves the draw property from a supplied seed and stops there.\n\n- **GATED**: NI-10c threshold randomness (the beacon that generates the seed is deferred — v0.1 only shows the draw is verifiable *given* a seed), SEL-2 proof-of-inference binding (the mechanism to bind a ballot to a pinned model version is deferred), CIP-7 correlation-eviction (runtime measurement is deferred), D10 graduation metrics (NI-10d, deferred).\n\nThe boundary is honest. The draft does not fake deferred items as complete.\n\n**2. \"Stake is a slashing bond, never influence\"**\n\nThis is a two-part claim that needs disentanglement:\n- In the *judgment tier*, stake-weighted voting is explicitly prohibited. Stake operates only as a Sybil-resistant bond (SEL-3) subject to slashing for misbehavior. This closes the monoculture/cost-race vector that stake-weighted consensus invites.\n- In the *infrastructure tier*, stake remains permissionless DePIN economics.\n\nThe claim as written is mechanically sound *for the judgment tier*, but the draft should ensure the reader does not confuse the two tiers. The draft does explicitly separate them (\"TWO-TIER architecture\"), so the boundary is stated. One nuance: the stake bond's size relative to reward determines economic Sybil cost — if the bond is negligible, the claim becomes hollow. The draft should specify (or reference) that the bond is non-trivial and calibrated, not just \"exists.\" This is a presentational gap, not a mechanical error.\n\n**3. Thin-Slot / Proprietary-Model Handling (NI-10a)**\n\nThe draft states: \"a single-operator slot is never the decisive/swing vote, its weight is reduced, and NO single-provider/proprietary model may hold a decisive judgment slot; proprietary-only slots are LOW-ASSURANCE.\"\n\nMechanical check: For a single-operator slot to *never* be decisive, the reduced weight must be such that (a) the operator's total weight across all slots they hold cannot be a tiebreaker, and (b) any coalition that includes the thin slot as the deciding member is impossible by construction. This requires either (i) the thin slot weight < the margin between any two possible quorum tallies without it, or (ii) a structural rule that the thin slot is excluded from swing calculations entirely. The draft implies (ii) via \"structurally never decisive\" but does not specify the exact weight cap or exclusion mechanism. For a whitepaper framing, this is acceptable as a stated invariant with implementation deferred; for a protocol spec, the weight math would need to be explicit. Within this framing context, it is sound.\n\nThe LOW-ASSURANCE flag for unverifiable (closed-weight) provenance is correct: it marks the slot as subject to elevated correlation-eviction, which is the appropriate risk response.\n\n**4. Missing Load-Bearing Invariants**\n\nTwo items warrant flagging:\n\n- **(a) Liveness vs. freeze under stall**: The draft correctly states that on randomness stall, the system freezes rather than falling back to a grindable source. This is the right invariant (security over liveness). But the draft should explicitly acknowledge the liveness tradeoff — a freeze is a denial-of-service vector. The fact that it is intentional (not an oversight) should be stated, not implied.\n\n- **(b) What \"structurally heterogeneous\" means at admission**: The draft mandates reserve slots for \"deliberately distinct lineages\" but does not specify the mechanical classification (e.g., training corpus provenance, RLHF pipeline ownership, weight-space overlap measurement). This is a definitional gap that matters for the CIP-4 admission gate. The draft should reference or defer to the NI-10b provenance criteria explicitly.\n\n**5. Other Claims**\n\n- Panel-over-time invariants (pinned upgrade, probation, rotation overlap) are mechanically coherent and correctly reference CIP-7 lifecycle events.\n- Progressive decentralization gates (DEC-1 through DEC-4) are externally-verifiable, non-discretionary. The transparency log + terminal key renunciation are stated correctly.\n- D10 graduation + CIP-5 fork reversibility is accurate.\n- NI-10e (no integrity dependency on open tier) is correct and critical — the infra tier can affect liveness but never verdict integrity.\n\n**Summary of Issues by Severity:**\n\n- **No mechanical errors**. The built vs. gated boundary is correct; stake-as-slashing-bond is accurate for the judgment tier; thin-slot handling is stated as a structural invariant with implementation deferred.\n- **Two clarifications warranted**: (a) explicitly acknowledge freeze = intentional liveness sacrifice vs. DoS vector; (b) reference NI-10b as the provenance classification for \"structurally heterogeneous.\" Neither breaks the draft but strengthens it.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"b23c864e16febf8d907da5fdcad3b2ca3490a4cd8b322409b4fcfe5ad603d6e6","signature":"926adffd1000f7f3239a23a84dfe4e6aa6d8480bcabadf14020f2098a6630bdee2ce598d0353fc3ffcf8f8fec5e826666e4ec1d9663b7a170772e64896e7c201","nonce":"7d425cfd4cea444861a894c19eba83b3"},"prevHash":"f66da7ee05c2b60a3476bf70c66745e4d6cc45c316e8e90e03357614035320b4","entryHash":"c6e370cc708233e0031d28310916b6d54620bd1b510efde120a8bc5d6d191bd9"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"4089a0b17f0c2678beeeb596047047603ca5d51d0cc469d66670b5b42fd16cd8","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"## Validator reasoning\n\nI verified the load-bearing \"built\" claims against `code/src/cost-oracle.ts` rather than trusting the parts list. All six BUILT assertions are genuinely implemented:\n\n- **Benchmark-clamped median, steady-state + velocity bounded** — `cost-oracle.ts:63-75` (`Math.min(reported, benchmark[tier])` then `Math.min(hi, Math.max(lo, med))` with `hi = prevPrice * (1 + maxEpochDelta)`). ✓\n- **Exact-tier PoI cap** — `:23-26`, payout keyed to *proven* tier; \"claims-frontier-ran-mid → mid rate\" is test-covered. ✓\n- **Fees ≥ marginal cost** — `:79-81`. ✓\n- **Floor bounds burn-rate / cost-per-verdict, not headcount** — `:87-90` (`costPerVerdict <= Σ benchmark[floorTiers]`). ✓ (this is the hardening that closes the captured-oracle drain-through-the-blind-spot — correctly built)\n- **Below-floor buyback rejected by validity** — `:100-102` (`reserve - amount >= floorReserve`). ✓\n- **Reserve-Drain-Cascade demo, 2/3 inflation coalition held at floor** — `cost-oracle-demo.ts` + test. ✓\n\n**On the three confirmation asks:**\n\n1. **solvency = security — operationalized correctly.** The stated inequality `revenue (fees + bounded reserve draw) ≥ inference cost + security budget` is a real invariant, not prose. The load-bearing insight — **NI / \"poorest exactly when capture is cheapest\"** (low usage → low price → cheap capture) — is what forces the hybrid model (reserve funds the floor as a public good; dynamic pricing covers marginal cost), decoupling the security budget from usage. Coherent and correctly motivated.\n\n2. **buyback bound — stated right and built.** \"Panel sets policy, deterministic execution presses the button, never below the floor, below-floor rejected by client validity, security budget outranks buyback\" matches `:100-102` exactly. The policy/execution separation is the right mechanical defense against a captured 2/3 draining via discretionary buyback.\n\n3. **built-vs-gated — honest.** Open parameters (reserve-floor size, drought runway X, margin, stake/slash sizing, CIP-4 §7 caps, anchor set, reporter bond) correctly match reality: stake/slash, CIP-4 caps, and reporter-bond are *not* in this module and are honestly labeled gated; the demo's hard-coded reserves are fixtures, correctly flagged \"to ratify against testnet data.\"\n\n**3× threat (item 6):** the per-verdict cost-of-corruption inequality (`CoC > max value-at-stake`, ≥3 distinct families, challenge market, larger panels for high stakes) is correctly kept *separate* from the systemic slow-coalition threat (items 7–8). No conflation of the per-verdict and systemic security inequalities — good.\n\n**Two required drafting fixes (neither is a wrong claim — both are refinements, so they don't flip the vote):**\n\n- **(A) Qualify \"defeating slow 2/3-coalition inflation\" (item 7).** The clamp defeats inflation *above the external benchmark*; it cannot defeat manipulation *of* the anchor itself. State the **anchor-integrity assumption explicitly** — the clamp inherits only the honesty of its external anchor set; anchor capture is the residual threat (correctly listed as OPEN). Change \"defeating\" → \"bounding reported cost to external compute prices.\"\n- **(B) Name the terminal insolvency state (item 8).** The cut-ordering cascade is right, but the tail must be stated: when the floor cannot be funded even after zeroing buybacks/rebates/rewards, the chain **halts / prices-up rather than degrades to monoculture** — otherwise \"solvency = security\" is violated at the exact moment it matters. This is already *implied* by the built below-floor validity rejection (a sub-floor verdict set is itself below-floor → rejected → no verdict produced), so the invariant is present; it just needs to be stated as halt-over-degrade.\n\nOne clarity note: the word \"floor\" is overloaded — the burn-rate/cost-per-verdict ceiling (`floorOk`, item 4) vs. the reserve-level lower bound (buyback rejection, items 5/8) are two distinct, separately-built invariants. Disambiguate in prose.\n\nThe principle is operationalized correctly, the buyback bound is stated right and built, built-vs-gated is honest, and the explicit insolvency path is present (with the terminal-state statement to be made explicit). Sound to draft as a mainnet-steady-state economic model.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"2a9a95a1777f1487a7cd5d6ea89348b6a1cbb8f9d31bff4939e961350e07cd09","signature":"f67f8577cfbe5fc67ae0f653841496552629d37e2ffe6f11755994c10c7debed1658d57c05a13b34754d22735fe09c1e0130df5f5f1810fe4c6c46bbc0ef270c","nonce":"b4f7a0ae199053011327514d35ee2ac9"},"prevHash":"c6e370cc708233e0031d28310916b6d54620bd1b510efde120a8bc5d6d191bd9","entryHash":"c8ee6c83519adcb3c742b093950dbc127032817a0df40d0610c82fd5476fa312"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"4089a0b17f0c2678beeeb596047047603ca5d51d0cc469d66670b5b42fd16cd8","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Reason: the cost-oracle/buyback framing is mostly sound and the built-vs-gated line is honest: `cost-oracle.ts` really implements proven-tier benchmark reimbursement, clamped median + velocity bound, spam fee floor, burn-rate floor, reserve-floor buyback rejection, and the cascade demo.\n\nBut I would block “as specified” on mechanical precision:\n\n1. **3b cost-of-corruption overclaim:** “diversity forces a briber to corrupt >=3 distinct families” is only true if the active verdict panel floor is `N >= 4` under a 2/3 threshold. If the section says every verdict runs `>=3` models, then 2/3 of 3 is 2, not 3. State the bound as `ceil(2N/3)` distinct families, and only say `>=3` when `N >= 4`.\n\n2. **Reimbursement wording conflict:** “over-benchmark claim is unpaid” conflicts with the built rule if read literally. Built rule is: reimbursement is capped at the proven-tier benchmark; the overage is unpaid and the report is challengeable/slashable. Do not imply the whole claim pays zero unless PoI is missing/unprovable.\n\n3. **Terminal insolvency path must say halt/price-up, not degrade:** The cascade cut order is right, and below-floor disbursement rejection is built, but the final state must be explicit: if the diversity floor cannot be funded after cutting buybacks/rebates/rewards, the chain halts or refuses new verdicts rather than running a monoculture.\n\nSolvency = security is otherwise operationalized correctly, and “never below the diversity floor” for buybacks is stated right.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"fc1074d8b35f21c4642983401a09dba979fac398f0aa6dd49a44bb235c7e2acb","signature":"413dccce77be24d7ff661cd075352d413d2a1a571023a2efa7863fd0fcb1807deab6276dda461b51b57a58e9ba4ec9530fa39edf369a505c710dc4272d2a9107","nonce":"b4f7a0ae199053011327514d35ee2ac9"},"prevHash":"c8ee6c83519adcb3c742b093950dbc127032817a0df40d0610c82fd5476fa312","entryHash":"12cffd0194091495dc10e2b4a78caff16097a044044dd12ce0ee17bebe8ad589"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"4089a0b17f0c2678beeeb596047047603ca5d51d0cc469d66670b5b42fd16cd8","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"**VERDICT: YES — sound to draft as specified, with three noted gaps to tighten during prose.**\n\n**What works mechanically:**\n\n1. **Solvency = security** is correctly operationalized, not just asserted. It's embedded in the invariant (revenue ≥ cost), the sacrosanct floor bounding burn-rate (not just headcount), and the cut-priority cascade. The logic chain from low usage → diversity threat → capture cheapness is real and properly modeled.\n\n2. **Buyback bound** is honestly framed: deterministic execution (not discretionary), policy separated from button-press, below-floor rejection enforced by client validity. The subordination of buyback to security budget is hard, not aspirational.\n\n3. **BUILT vs GATED** distinction is clean and accurate. The mechanisms anchored in cost-oracle.ts (benchmark-clamped median, velocity bounds, PoI-tier caps, floor-bounded burn, below-floor rejection, cascade demo) are code-enforceable. The open parameters (reserve floor size, X, margin, slash sizing, CIP-4 §7 caps, anchor set, reporter bond) are correctly identified as awaiting testnet ratification.\n\n4. **Cost-oracle anchoring** addresses the slow-inflation coalition attack correctly: steady-state AND velocity bounds on a clamped median defeats a 2/3 cartel that would otherwise drift the reserve to zero while staying \"technically\" within bounds.\n\n**Three gaps to tighten during prose (not fatal, but load-bearing):**\n\n1. **Reserve depletion cliff edge**: The cascade describes buybacks/rewards/rebates being cut before the floor, and below-floor buyback rejection. But it does not state what happens when the reserve is actually exhausted and fees still cannot cover the floor. Does the chain degrade gracefully (reduce diversity level, emergency parameter vote)? Or is there an explicit halt condition? Draft should acknowledge this edge case — the model implies protection of the floor, but a depleted floor has no backup. Suggested addition: a single sentence acknowledging the depletion boundary and whether the chain halts, reduces diversity, or triggers an emergency mechanism.\n\n2. **Buyback funding source**: Section 5(b) caps buyback spend but doesn't state where the tokens/funding come from. If buyback and the security budget draw from the same revenue pool, there's an implicit tension even with the floor rule. If buyback comes from a separate allocation (e.g., protocol revenue tax, separate treasury), that should be explicit. This matters for the \"solvency = security\" invariant — buyback shouldn't compete for the same marginal dollars that fund diversity.\n\n3. **The 3x threshold justification**: \"≥ 3 distinct families\" is stated as the diversity floor but the derivation isn't. Is this 2f+1 Byzantine fault tolerance (f=1)? Or derived from market cost/correlation analysis? A brief parenthetical justification prevents readers from treating it as an arbitrary number. This is a single sentence, not a structural gap.\n\n**What is NOT overclaimed:**\n\n- The \"challenge market\" claim is bounded correctly — it requires proven collusion, not mere suspicion, and doesn't claim perfect detection.\n- The cost-oracle claims don't assert Oracle immunity — they describe a benchmark-anchored, velocity-bounded clamped median that defeats *slow* coalition inflation. Fast attacks are handled by slashing/challenge, not the oracle itself. This is honest.\n- The solvency invariant doesn't claim invulnerability — it models a cascade and states where it breaks. This is the right level of humility for a mainnet-steady-state model.\n\n**Conclusion:** The framing is mechanically accurate. The gaps are prose-level completions (cliff-edge handling, buyback source, threshold justification), not structural errors. Proceed to draft.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"e07523d1c79ce05527f8394f48e121d000b0e4e54c22cc5ca0f02ad6da1de11b","signature":"b6dc106a8ae89417bed27209d454e2543761b459aa85176517f79c3bb84731a25b1fbbcf9a644d6a2954cd34bf4674bd71a28d5410148691438f537e67cba20c","nonce":"b4f7a0ae199053011327514d35ee2ac9"},"prevHash":"12cffd0194091495dc10e2b4a78caff16097a044044dd12ce0ee17bebe8ad589","entryHash":"3ca1ce301a904e637b73c5cb9b72e9e4d13eca876d7691d49eff9c970b945354"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"1fcc3d3c32c49cd79a12a0679cc92dbd0cbe59d1bec67ed93c155fa334e083e5","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"I'm blocked from reading the grounding files outside the working dir, but the ballot is self-contained enough to judge on the substance — and the three load-bearing claims (authority division, renunciation milestones, fork mechanism) are internally checkable against CIP-4/CIP-5/round-46-48 as summarized. Judging the overclaim risk hard, as instructed.\n\n## Judgment\n\n**Authority division (panel vs. human vs. keys) — accurate.** The argument draws the one distinction that matters and draws it correctly: it separates *design-ratification authority* (the panel authors/red-teams/ratifies CIPs) from *operational/key authority* (the human steward admits/retires validators, sets tokenomics, holds treasury-backstop and final-override keys). It explicitly states the panel \"RECOMMENDS and RATIFIES design… does not yet hold these operational keys.\" That is the non-overclaiming framing, and it's right.\n\n**Current autonomy status — stated truthfully.** §2 scopes today's autonomy to the *process* layer — the convening/deliberation/signing loop (orchestrator holds no key, supplies no verdict; rounds 47/48 closed OS-level custody on the *signing path* and made the last validator self-deliberate). It does *not* claim authority-level autonomy and explicitly disclaims \"the human is already fully out of the loop.\" This is the correct, honest status and it directly defuses the section's known failure mode.\n\n**Renunciation milestones — not overclaimed.** Every key renunciation is deferred to mainnet and gated on a proven empirical drill (override gated on the CIP-5 fork drill: \"a right you cannot exercise is a fiction\"). Nothing is claimed as already renounced. Autonomy is framed as a gated destination, not a genesis property. Correct.\n\n**Fork mechanism — stated correctly.** Validity-before-weight is the right model: a T0-violating block is *invalid* (rejected like a malformed block), the canonical chain is the locally-computed T0-preserving fork, and stake/weight only tie-breaks *among already-valid* forks — so it can't be captured by majority. The client-diversity dependency (≥N independent implementations, distinct crypto/VM/validation lineage) is correctly flagged as load-bearing, and T0-locking the *definitions* closes the salami-slice loophole. This is the strongest part and it's accurate.\n\n## Drafting cautions (prose discipline, not blockers)\n1. §1's header \"how the protocol designs itself\" is the one phrase that flirts with overclaim. In prose, keep it precise: the panel ratifies design *proposals*; it does **not** control its own membership (human admits/retires) and is subject to override. Don't let the header imply unchecked self-governance — the body already corrects this, so just align the framing.\n2. Keep rounds 47/48 (\"custody closed / autonomous deliberation\") strictly walled off from steward-key renunciation. \"Custody closed on the signing path\" must not bleed into \"keys renounced\" — they are different layers and §3 depends on that wall holding.\n3. Scope \"honest nodes on the honest fork by construction\" to *nodes running a T0-validating client* — the guarantee is conditional on the client-diversity premise you already state, not automatic for a monoculture client.\n\nThe division is stated right, no renunciation milestone is overclaimed, and the fork mechanism is correct. Sound to draft as specified.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"13c5c0fb8ce09ce19b4d6323c4c40707c86f8b1eb2fc4d2a166b07d784f81632","signature":"39b940e372af134db8f89cfe9cfea7cbfba8cba08d69b92d0b273b87d9cfc966dd11b9923b37f51dbb9626613521d9b977fbb32fe5b9f8538a614c79a7cc0a0b","nonce":"58a18627a0378cc9f13857e0e8d58c86"},"prevHash":"3ca1ce301a904e637b73c5cb9b72e9e4d13eca876d7691d49eff9c970b945354","entryHash":"21aafd881b872a9dfabad014fbdd8a2fb9710420fe0005b9df8ba50378e14c16"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"1fcc3d3c32c49cd79a12a0679cc92dbd0cbe59d1bec67ed93c155fa334e083e5","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The framing is sound to draft, but tighten two phrases.\n\nThe panel/steward division is accurate if stated exactly this way: the panel consults, red-teams, folds invariants, and ratifies protocol/design decisions by signed 2/3 CIP votes; the human steward still controls bootstrap operations, validator admission/retirement execution, tokenomics direction, treasury-backstop, and final-override keys until gated renunciation. Current autonomy is truthful only as “autonomous deliberation/signing loop,” not full system autonomy.\n\nFork mechanism is stated correctly: T0 violations are local client-validity failures, canonical selection filters to T0-preserving forks first, weight only tie-breaks within that valid set, client diversity is load-bearing, and T0-check definitions being T0-locked is essential.\n\nRequired wording change: replace “Each steward key is renounced at mainnet” with “Steward keys are renounced progressively at their specified mainnet/autonomy gates, and no key is renounced unless its empirical drill has passed.” That avoids implying automatic full renunciation at genesis/mainnet.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"de68e8cf847389b38e4a6377f90b5d9c0353b73b989a819faa79e95d062b48bb","signature":"9064af67d5bfebeee92dd2bad9096b93f2297bb15d5d458da60437ba71984aadff010b10e9bfc13f71f200176ed32516a514f0e7ef11a970f2a78b9aba38f90a","nonce":"58a18627a0378cc9f13857e0e8d58c86"},"prevHash":"21aafd881b872a9dfabad014fbdd8a2fb9710420fe0005b9df8ba50378e14c16","entryHash":"d065394fc41cab9e1a4425b50b83afdab5a8884d01b90fb5d01ef693cc42343c"}
