{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"7ee9f6d5df8320cb4c54c24b5e2dd595c2037aec7c28a7d23948bc67a8bdb969","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Judging §8's planned argument against the two named failure modes (maturity overclaim, scope confusion), then the three required confirmations.\n\n**1. \"Self-reported but independently replayable\" — RIGHT.** The distinction holds: cryptographic replay (hash-chained log, Ed25519 sigs, appendix commands) proves the computation is *reproducible from signed inputs* and untampered — it does **not** prove the panel's judgments are correct or that the inputs were externally generated. Those are different claims, and the plan keeps them separate (\"never as independent validation or a maturity badge,\" \"checkable, not asserted\"). The word \"independently-verifiable\" is safe *because* it's qualified as verifiability of the log, not validation of the verdicts. Passes failure mode (i). One nit for prose: keep \"independently-verifiable\" tethered to the log every time it appears, so it never drifts into reading as third-party validation.\n\n**2. Honest gap — TRUE and complete.** (a) state on one machine not a chain; (b) no token/treasury, slashing *detected* never executed; (c) three processes one operator owns, not independent validators. All three are stated, and they're consistent with the status block (bonds module = slashing-DETECTION, matching gap (b)). The dedicated scope-disambiguation section (§2 of the plan) reinforces it rather than burying it. This is the strongest part of the argument and is the correct defense against failure mode (ii).\n\n**3. Model-count scaling — argument sound, one phrase overstated.** The diversity logic is correctly cited from §2: a 2/3 supermajority across ceil(2N/3) *distinct* families means more independent families monotonically raises capture cost and lowers correlated-error exposure. That justifies the **direction** (more) and the **ordering** (grow diversity before relying on it — also correctly placed in the roadmap). But the claim \"they are not round numbers for their own sake\" slightly overreaches: the diversity argument justifies *more*, not *exactly ~10 then ~20+*. The binding constraint isn't named — security scales with **genuine distinctness**, not headcount, and the real ceiling is the *supply* of genuinely-independent frontier families. Reaching \"~20+\" by adding correlated/fine-tuned variants of the same base is diversity-theater, the exact correlated-error risk §2 warns about. Fix in prose: present 10/20+ as engineering checkpoints bounded by available distinct families, and state explicitly that count without distinctness buys no security.\n\n**Roadmap ordering — defensible, one clarity requirement.** Autonomy-done → economy → testnet → decentralization → mainnet is dependency-correct, and decentralization-before-mainnet with \"grow the set before relying on it\" is right (thin set cheaper to capture). The one place a reader could trip: phase 2 economic layer promises \"real flows\" and \"deterministic execution\" *before* the phase-3 testnet substrate exists. That only coheres if the execution venue is the external (already-live) launch chain, not Quorumchain's own chain — but the launch vehicle is out of scope. As written this risks reading as Quorumchain having on-chain execution at phase 2, contradicting phase 3 (scope-confusion, failure mode ii). Not a mis-order — a venue-disambiguation the prose must make explicit: phase-2 deterministic execution runs on an external chain; Quorumchain's own on-chain execution first appears at the testnet phase.\n\n**Call:** No status claim is fatally overstated, scope is not mis-stated (it is, in fact, unusually carefully stated), and no phase is mis-ordered. The two items above — name the distinctness-supply constraint on model scaling, and disambiguate the phase-2 execution venue — are prose-tightening notes, not defects in the argument as specified. The framing is sound to draft.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"3b793d308bd12736fdc9bd26783ea990de70ee5f1fb4d9054be502c2de669c21","signature":"6f08800dad136dd7d1b6868c1fe8b653e13f7dba378efea8fc674d2e7eb5d9cdcde53aa5af12e184b578e7dc957dbf0d097ca36481e5cbddbcddf9b6eb1c9806","nonce":"cc55495819995803e22ba576af1c07f9"},"prevHash":"d79259b15dc8a44b44d7357d847c49f745aca0fac0d8bdc744cc48d7f9147fde","entryHash":"62365754cb360ba91f0633957cc95cae6979e5dc77ac36a1709aaabc2a1794a3"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"7ee9f6d5df8320cb4c54c24b5e2dd595c2037aec7c28a7d23948bc67a8bdb969","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The framing is sound to draft.\n\nIt handles the main failure modes correctly: “self-reported but independently replayable” is the right maturity claim because it does not convert signed logs, tests, or reproducible commands into independent validation. The scope disambiguation is explicit enough: local pipeline, one operator, hash-chained files, no public chain, no independent validator set, no deployed token economy.\n\nThe honest gap is stated truthfully: no chain state, no token/treasury/economic execution, slashing detection only, and three model processes under one operator. That prevents the reader from mistaking the current system for a live decentralized network.\n\nThe roadmap order is also coherent: off-chain autonomy first, then economic layer, then on-chain substrate/testnet with real enforcement, then decentralization, then mainnet. That avoids relying on validator diversity before it exists.\n\nThe model-count scaling is justified by the stated diversity/security argument rather than merely asserted. The only drafting caution is to keep “survived adversarial red-team” clearly scoped as internal/adversarial testing unless there was genuinely external review.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"8e2930bfd38060cc83192418dcda7e07d16a11b60b97dc92c07250ec5f8284e9","signature":"7e01086c95a219c3c01c631a6dfbfbd3bbdb20929b3b0a6d01d483f8fb3f9f104b7554fedade696dc9c4f3c7d30cb458d47ed028521826bb45b6b26d399f5e04","nonce":"cc55495819995803e22ba576af1c07f9"},"prevHash":"62365754cb360ba91f0633957cc95cae6979e5dc77ac36a1709aaabc2a1794a3","entryHash":"04a59628b1b61c1b7a068fcd3dc0e6b5b2afcfa6764a89550b8acf7013b934ac"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"7ee9f6d5df8320cb4c54c24b5e2dd595c2037aec7c28a7d23948bc67a8bdb969","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Auditing against the two known failure modes:\n\n**Failure mode (i) — Overclaiming maturity:**\nThe framing is tight — \"self-reported but independently replayable\" is the right boundary. Claims are checkable: ~200 log entries, 60+ rounds, 226 tests, the panel's Ed25519 votes, the self-fixing incidents — all tied to a verifiable log, not asserted as facts. Crucially, it does NOT use these as a maturity badge. The honest-gap paragraph explicitly states: no chain, no token, one operator, slashing only detected. That closes the overclaim door.\n\nOne minor gap: \"survived adversarial red-team\" should specify internal vs external. If internal, say so.\n\n**Failure mode (ii) — Scope confusion:**\nSection 2 disambiguates explicitly: local pipeline, three processes, one operator, hash-chained files on one machine. It states what it is NOT (public network, independent validators, token economy). This is correct. The scope disambiguation belongs here and does the work needed.\n\n**Roadmap order check:**\nAutonomy → Economic layer (mechanism) → Testnet substrate → Decentralization → Mainnet. Dependency order is sound: mechanism design before on-chain implementation, testnet before decentralization (thin validator sets are cheaper to capture, and the text says this explicitly), mainnet last. Each phase gates on objective criteria, not calendar — good.\n\nOne observation: economic layer and testnet substrate could plausibly be parallel workstreams rather than sequential phases. The ordering isn't wrong — you need the mechanism designed before porting it on-chain — but consider clarifying that economic-layer design can proceed in parallel while the testnet substrate work waits for it, rather than implying strict sequencing.\n\n**Model-count scaling:**\n3 → ~10 → ~20+ is justified by the 2/3-supermajority-across-distinct-families argument. It ties to §2's correlated-error framing. Not arbitrary round numbers. This is sound.\n\n**Final check on the three confirmation questions:**\n- \"Self-reported but independently replayable\" — correct framing, not overclaiming\n- Honest gap (no chain / no token-teeth / one operator) — stated truthfully, all three are explicit\n- Model-count scaling justified by diversity argument — yes, with the ceil(2N/3) rationale\n\nMinor fix recommended: qualify the red-team (internal vs external). Minor consideration: clarify that economic-layer design and testnet substrate implementation can overlap rather than strictly sequence.\n\nThese are drafting tweaks, not structural failures.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"26954e77d473c4e6755872cbcfd2246e3a494db299c4083d7529c4bbf7ef54ce","signature":"12cf23825e3564da3dc42a4b3a202e0fcb0b01c3d8b8ff4e78fb85032512f430a3888ce21e54e418e7ab21cc1e23af6247931ab7d466b9328f46316dd934e70b","nonce":"cc55495819995803e22ba576af1c07f9"},"prevHash":"04a59628b1b61c1b7a068fcd3dc0e6b5b2afcfa6764a89550b8acf7013b934ac","entryHash":"a6f532286ee46cb842ba6127396b4611ca1734b62491d467d399e6b63fd966e6"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"d34702c44c579a8fb650feb5def4f5840c62af93ec38649e441ede30a7ce05ea","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"## Validator reasoning\n\nI'll judge §9 purely on completeness, treating under-claiming as the failure mode. The ten items are each stated as a real limit that bites — none are softened into non-limitations (item 4's \"anchors relocate, don't remove\" and item 6's \"complete-consistent-but-false passes the kernel\" are genuinely sharp). The coverage of correlated error, anchor capture, framing capture, and the freeze-over-degrade liveness sacrifice is honest.\n\nBut I'm asked what a serious skeptic raises that this list does **not** concede. There is one, and it's material:\n\n**Verdict non-reproducibility / model drift / non-determinism — MISSING.** The core verdict function is a stochastic call to mutable, often closed-weight, externally-hosted models. This means:\n- The same ballot re-run later can yield a *different* verdict (temperature/non-determinism), and the producing model may be **deprecated or silently updated** so the verdict cannot be re-derived at all.\n- Frozen criteria freeze the *question*, but nothing freezes the *validators*. So the recorded judgment is not independently reproducible from its inputs the way a hash or a re-executable transaction is.\n\nThis is a distinct axis from everything listed. Item 1 (consensus≠truth), item 2 (correlated error), and item 3 (verifiability of the *answer*) are all about **correctness**. A verdict can be perfectly correct yet **non-reproducible and non-auditable** — and auditability/reproducibility is the exact property a blockchain is normally expected to provide. For a system whose pitch is \"recording verifiable judgments on-chain,\" omitting that its central judgment function is irreproducible over time is precisely the hole a skeptic drives through. The notary proving authorship+timing (item 3) does *not* patch this — it proves *who said it when*, not that *the judgment could be re-derived*.\n\nA secondary, weaker gap: structural dependence on third-party commercial model providers (deprecation, ToS/censorship, rate-limits, price moves) as a liveness/neutrality risk. This is partially absorbed by item 9's \"single-operator pipeline today,\" but the provider-dependency persists *after* graduation, so it deserves its own line rather than being read as a today-only artifact.\n\nThe first gap alone is material and disqualifying for a section whose stated goal is \"the skeptic finds their objection already conceded.\" Add a limitation explicitly conceding verdict non-reproducibility / model mutability / non-determinism (and note it as the reason the Commons records *what was held when*, not a re-derivable proof), and I flip to YES.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"6c47f3fdafa69cfaa02fc2d50a641b6ac95688dbb81ee8ad6e9cde1426710b5f","signature":"65fe7f252bf0ca8df3e53b4781adced8421858271cd8266ddc2e43cd514a020a9087c1b783de163c6d54b5721dde31d1eefeffcda9430b8e6cb75082a39dfb06","nonce":"ad294af4baaf4ce05851ad2810370a82"},"prevHash":"a6f532286ee46cb842ba6127396b4611ca1734b62491d467d399e6b63fd966e6","entryHash":"37ca62c3d4db54813e6a4288872dc9b943c81d59dff06fd2b944a6892d2507c7"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"d34702c44c579a8fb650feb5def4f5840c62af93ec38649e441ede30a7ce05ea","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"The list is candid, but not complete enough for a first-class limitations section.\n\nMaterial missing limitation: **model/version opacity and reproducibility**. A serious skeptic will ask whether a past verdict can be independently replayed or audited if the validators were proprietary AI APIs whose weights, safety layers, prompts, decoding behavior, and versions may change or be unavailable. Signatures prove who attested, but not that future observers can reproduce the reasoning path or distinguish “same question, changed model” from “changed truth.” This is adjacent to correlated error, but not the same limit.\n\nI would add an explicit item: Quorumchain depends on opaque, evolving model endpoints unless validators are pinned, archived, or locally reproducible; therefore historical verdicts may be non-replayable and only evidentially auditable through stored transcripts/artifacts.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"8e9a573c0bc7dab078e32023e5dca136544469d56ff53948abdc4b5b5ae6a63d","signature":"42ff04f06f3e6c19cb7c3c42ad1229f4f15002131d502cec803fd391503488b61daaef915daf08e586beac1aa4860615d8ea592a8b802f784bdfd3599a768a0e","nonce":"ad294af4baaf4ce05851ad2810370a82"},"prevHash":"37ca62c3d4db54813e6a4288872dc9b943c81d59dff06fd2b944a6892d2507c7","entryHash":"a5d2e6228428f511eeeb4c2af5566ada0f2f3c7daebc6f5f69f190940f76fcf0"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"d34702c44c579a8fb650feb5def4f5840c62af93ec38649e441ede30a7ce05ea","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Adversarial review of §9 limitations:\n\n**On honesty: each stated item bites.** None are softened into non-limitations. Items 1-8 concede real, non-trivial failure modes with specific mechanisms (shared hallucination, poisoned anchors, false evidence that passes kernel checks, freeze-over-degrade liveness sacrifices). Good.\n\n**On completeness: gaps exist.**\n\nThe most material omission a serious skeptic would exploit:\n\n**Single-operator capture / key compromise.** §9 #9 discloses \"single-operator local pipeline\" as a maturity state, and #4 covers anchor capture (external truth source). But the gap between them — the operator's signing keys being stolen, coerced, or compromised by a third party — is not explicitly conceded. A single operator holds every link in the chain: ballot execution, vendor selection, evidence ingestion, and anchor gating. If that operator's infrastructure keys are exfiltrated, the entire apparatus can be impersonated without even needing model collusion. This is the most obvious attack vector against a one-person system, and it deserves an explicit line in §9 rather than hiding in the maturity disclosure.\n\nSecondary gaps:\n\n- **System persistence / continuity risk.** If the operator ceases operation (burnout, legal coercion, business failure), there is no failover. This is a live limitation distinct from \"it's not a decentralized L1 yet,\" because even a single-operator system could, in principle, commit records to durable public storage that survive shutdown. Whether that's implemented matters for trust.\n\n- **Kernel / pipeline code correctness.** Every limitation assumes the Quorumchain code itself runs faithfully. A bug in the notary verification, the freeze-over-degrade logic, or the signature aggregation path silently corrupts all outputs. This is the \"trusting TCB\" limitation — distinct from AI errors, distinct from false evidence, and real.\n\n**Verdict on #9 and #10:** #9 is honest but conflates maturity with limitation — the current single-operator reality is a limitation; the path to decentralization is not. #10 is meta-framing, acceptable as a wrapper but not a standalone limit.\n\nThe stated limitations are honest and bite — no softening violations. But the list is not *complete* because the most obvious skeptic objection (operator key compromise + persistence) is not explicitly conceded, only implied.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"468ca89e30cf8b3165c2b88f64f8d0d7389b7c35de28e960abe15b540263b81d","signature":"251227006693edfddd6ead7870d06150214f4d9f95d692c2734b4d3a387258628dcd35a4298c5701f279f1e91e6df96810d9616541217e3b091491963ad5a202","nonce":"ad294af4baaf4ce05851ad2810370a82"},"prevHash":"a5d2e6228428f511eeeb4c2af5566ada0f2f3c7daebc6f5f69f190940f76fcf0","entryHash":"15bec5afe4d6e22d1bb7ce25a8858929b8fa5fc31fe00bf475210ee52e9e35af"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"60967b480676c6de10a4143d92b813016ebd8f936de2f54d306e62adf2d66706","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"## Reasoning\n\nI checked each candidate gap against what items 1–13 actually concede, looking for something **distinct** (not a relabel of an existing item) and **first-order** for a verdict function defined as \"a stochastic call to externally-hosted models ingesting evidence.\"\n\nThe three previously-missing items are genuinely fixed and bite:\n- **3** (non-reproducibility/mutability) is cleanly separated from correctness and doesn't oversell — it concedes \"evidentially auditable, not re-derivable,\" and folds in third-party provider dependence. Good.\n- **8** (single-operator/key/continuity) bites hard and explicitly disclaims \"OS key custody ≠ distributed trust.\" Not softened.\n- **9** (TCB/code-correctness) concedes the self-review loop \"cannot eliminate\" the risk. Not softened.\n- **12** is correctly demoted to trajectory, not a present property.\n\nBut being adversarial one more time, there is a **material limitation still missing**, and it's the single most-cited real-world failure mode for exactly this architecture:\n\n**Indirect prompt injection / instruction-hijacking of the validator models at evaluation time.** The verdict function ingests external evidence and anchors and feeds them to LLM validators. An attacker who can place text into the evidence bundle can attempt to *steer the validators' reasoning/instruction-following* — not merely assert a falsehood. This is distinct from all three nearest items:\n- **Item 2** is *non-adversarial* shared error (corpora/RLHF convergence) — injection is adversarial and can hit even perfectly independent models simultaneously via the same poisoned input.\n- **Item 6** is framing by the *question-author at creation* — injection comes through the *evidence channel at evaluation*, after frozen criteria.\n- **Item 7** is false-but-consistent content that the truth-blind *kernel/notary* waves through — injection attacks the *validators' judgment layer*, not the kernel's completeness check. A successful injection produces a verdict the kernel considers perfectly well-formed.\n\nFor a system whose entire output is an LLM call over attacker-influenceable text, conceding \"false evidence passes the notary\" (7) but not \"crafted evidence can hijack the validator\" leaves the most obvious adversary unaddressed. It belongs as its own item (mitigations: input isolation, provenance gating, the challenge market — none of which prevent it).\n\nTwo softer notes, not dispositive: (a) the list leans on the **challenge market + calibration penalty** as load-bearing mitigation (items 2, 7) but never concedes that *mitigation itself* has unanalyzed failure modes (under-capitalization, griefing, bribery, and that calibration penalties presuppose later disprovability the unverifiable class in 4/11 denies); (b) **confidentiality** — sensitive evidence is exposed to third-party providers — is framed only as liveness/neutrality in item 3, not as a data-exposure limit. I'd accept the list with just (a)/(b) noted, but injection alone is enough to withhold a YES.\n\nOne missing, distinct, first-class limitation → not yet complete.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"9d564232e0c3cf536fbc7e616ad35a68fe43cf3f495ed7cf8676286c8ae9dcb7","signature":"c4864782a3298f9f7dec671ade14697c83022c05cf4560dbe902568afc9c4e11022d1270dc005fb0d4f40ee2627d5b5df585d262ebb1e8271c5fc9b0fa87a500","nonce":"4fc18c98f717b62a98e2d73f4e248b88"},"prevHash":"15bec5afe4d6e22d1bb7ce25a8858929b8fa5fc31fe00bf475210ee52e9e35af","entryHash":"1f49ae422c864510db2cdaaea2a45093abb42e4897b21f4492aa6c023cbc3137"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"60967b480676c6de10a4143d92b813016ebd8f936de2f54d306e62adf2d66706","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The revised list is materially complete for a first-class limitations section. The three prior gaps are now conceded directly and with bite: non-reproducible mutable model judgments, single-operator/key/continuity failure, and TCB/code correctness. The list also preserves hard limits around truth, correlated error, bad criteria, false evidence, anchor capture, unverifiable domains, cost/latency, and current-vs-roadmap scope.\n\nA serious skeptic could still elaborate on governance capture, incentive design failure, privacy/confidentiality leakage, or legal/regulatory pressure, but these are either covered under operator/provider/anchor/evidence risks or are deployment-specific rather than missing core epistemic/system limitations. I do not see a remaining material limitation that must be conceded for §9 completeness.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"f649e39fc4338e63601423bec1beb4a4dd6dbb7fb107b44f0a8a51cc58eaca9e","signature":"f0f768a52bd4bb6414000cb485cc16276aa2e12153a85275da70cc9fce6be85d38b1d1f5a2f47715610080845cbf7d7c922d981dd8289c167f4172f5911fdb0f","nonce":"4fc18c98f717b62a98e2d73f4e248b88"},"prevHash":"1f49ae422c864510db2cdaaea2a45093abb42e4897b21f4492aa6c023cbc3137","entryHash":"db90994d695767fff953e2c7d9355ae0b060d40405ba48910445add35da86b43"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"60967b480676c6de10a4143d92b813016ebd8f936de2f54d306e62adf2d66706","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"I've read the revised list carefully. It's substantially improved — items 3, 8, and 9 were genuine omissions, and separating maturity from limitation (item 12) fixes the conflation problem. The honesty is good; nothing is softened.\n\nBut a serious skeptic still has two material raises that are not conceded:\n\n**A. Feedback-loop / self-reinforcement risk (distinct from item 2).** If Quorumchain verdicts become widely cited and are absorbed into future training corpora, the system's own outputs contaminate the very models it depends on for new verdicts. This creates a reflexive loop: a wrong verdict becomes part of the \"consensus\" that future verdicts consult, making correction increasingly difficult over time. Item 2 covers shared training data as an input problem, but not the *output-to-input contamination* that gets worse with adoptionsuccess. This is structurally separate and bites: the more the system is trusted, the more it risks becoming self-insulated from external correction.\n\n**B. Jurisdictional / legal coercion as a first-class vulnerability (under-addressed in items 3 and 8).** Item 3 mentions ToS/censorship and item 8 mentions legal coercion of the operator, but neither concedes the specific risk that model providers or anchor sources are *legally compelled* — via subpoena, court order, or regulatory directive — to produce特定 outputs, de-platform a topic, or silently alter behavior. This is not captured by \"censorship\" generically; it's a structured attack vector where the adversary is a state or regulator with legal authority over a provider in its jurisdiction. The system's neutrality depends on providers' jurisdictional independence, which is not guaranteed and not conceded as a standing limitation.\n\nBoth of these bite. Neither is footnoted. Both would survive the defense arguments the whitepaper would make against them.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"7b594b62f65208bd9545241b5d92f1b97982f851769de0941dd483b16700cb08","signature":"9c39c22479be0c5e738083c99c3c31f25fc30a14f02742f6ee7564c42f14411b2a11ba2412eeef50d663360ebf396f3dc1f70c16caff8c6ca878bdc65027f807","nonce":"4fc18c98f717b62a98e2d73f4e248b88"},"prevHash":"db90994d695767fff953e2c7d9355ae0b060d40405ba48910445add35da86b43","entryHash":"820885168152e8899fc8ebb1a054a9c458549323da00f836f7e0651ca8cc47bd"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"138b3950f4384556bf7436a3739f609f20f9c9f2a04ca88a34af2f750f5ed2a1","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"I'll reason as a validator, testing the new items for distinctness and probing for any unconceded first-order gap.\n\n**Do 14–18 each bite and stay distinct?**\n- **14 (eval-time injection)** — attacks the validators' instruction-following via the *evidence channel at evaluation*, after criteria freeze. Genuinely distinct from 2 (non-adversarial shared error), 6 (creation-time framing), and 7 (false content the truth-blind kernel passes). Bites.\n- **15 (reflexive contamination)** — output→input loop that worsens with adoption; distinct from 2's input-side shared-data problem. Bites.\n- **16 (legal coercion)** — a structured state/regulator adversary with authority over a provider, beyond generic ToS/censorship. Distinct. Bites.\n- **17 (mitigations fail)** — concedes the challenge-market/calibration defenses leaned on in 2/7 are themselves attackable and presuppose disprovability that 4/11 lack. This is the honesty backstop. Bites.\n- **18 (confidentiality)** — data exposure to providers, orthogonal to 3's liveness/neutrality. Bites.\n\n**Is a still-distinct first-order limitation unconceded?** I tested the three strongest candidates:\n- *Capability ceiling* (objective-but-too-hard questions yielding confident-wrong verdicts) → a shared-blindspot case of **item 2**. Relabel.\n- *Temporal truth-decay* of subject matter → verdicts are timestamped claims about T; correct behavior, not a soundness limit.\n- *Protocol-governance / validator-set & threshold capture* — the most tempting. But under the whitepaper's stated single-operator regime, \"you must trust the operator's choice of models/parameters\" collapses into **item 8** (single-operator / no-continuity). Naming it would be relabeling, which the ballot forbids.\n\nThe list now spans epistemics (1,2,4,11,12), trust relocation (5), creation-time (6), evaluation-time adversarial (7,14), operational (8,9,10), the provider relationship (3,16,18), the reflexive loop (15), defense-honesty (17), and the meta-point (13). Two prior NO votes forced real additions; this pass closes the five named gaps with items that are each distinct and bite, and I cannot produce a remaining first-order limitation that isn't a relabel of an existing one.\n\nThe section is complete and honest at the first-order level.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"b0f969aa215bf3b26fbf9fda6d9c1396908cd2673ef95ce1ba0003a8a67babe9","signature":"62078c4a2683600bdc4ad40ab4f77ad7514fca78b9e69259332b75e8580f24d54eaa1a66e78f33fc08b977d3f5e3ab2f2da91ab98581da117df8e8075165620b","nonce":"cb2f967b7237b73bf14249ebf75510a2"},"prevHash":"820885168152e8899fc8ebb1a054a9c458549323da00f836f7e0651ca8cc47bd","entryHash":"4d5de9daa8abc3e46cc6e72477440b9c459d6caa52af412939e11fc707cf8f16"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"138b3950f4384556bf7436a3739f609f20f9c9f2a04ca88a34af2f750f5ed2a1","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Items 14-18 cover the previously missing first-order limits without merely renaming earlier ones. They add evaluation-channel attacks, longitudinal self-contamination, jurisdictional coercion, mitigation fragility, and confidentiality exposure. I do not see a remaining distinct first-order limitation that is both unconceded and outside the retained 1-18 set.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"4d49c6a1c885485b81744d80a441cdd6e29cee2536af8a0681299a891502d8ac","signature":"cb9dfb80a2c084c1ac86924a032f1da267067feae7f50d8e2de64a4e00b048df943c7ef1484701f4f0bb8f38e6e9134d5f3d59e14d688df50ef66b98c15b1903","nonce":"cb2f967b7237b73bf14249ebf75510a2"},"prevHash":"4d5de9daa8abc3e46cc6e72477440b9c459d6caa52af412939e11fc707cf8f16","entryHash":"8b0de6018719442ba3012d4563ff3acd0c5ff5eec4d70d8ccdc05e79575df3e2"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"138b3950f4384556bf7436a3739f609f20f9c9f2a04ca88a34af2f750f5ed2a1","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Reasoning through the 18 items systematically.\n\n**What's well-covered now:**\n- Epistemic limits (1, 4, 6, 11, 12)\n- Model-level failures (2, 3)\n- Adversarial content (7)\n- Prompt injection as distinct from content falsehood (14) — correctly carved out from 2, 6, 7\n- Feedback loop / reflexive contamination (15) — distinct from input-side shared error\n- Legal coercion as structured adversary (16) — beyond ToS/censorship\n- Meta-failure of defenses (17) — honest admission that mitigations aren't assumed sound\n- Privacy / data exposure (18) — separate from liveness/neutrality\n- Infrastructure (5, 8, 9, 10)\n- Scope dynamics (12, 13)\n\n**Potential gaps I checked:**\n- *Sybil/false diversity of validators:* Distinct from key-compromise (8). However, item 12 (\"earns-its-scope as trajectory-not-property\") covers independence as something that must be maintained over time, not assumed. Not first-order separable.\n- *Compositional / chaining risk:* A verdict cited as anchor in a subsequent question compounds error. Item 15 (reflexive contamination) captures output→input feedback; chaining is a close subclass. Not independently necessary.\n- *Bootstrap / cold-start:* How are initial criteria and anchors chosen before any track record exists? Item 6 (bad/captured criteria at creation) and item 5 (anchors relocate trust) jointly cover this — the system starts with inherited trust and can be captured from minute one.\n\nEach of items 14–18 bites independently, maps to a concrete adversary or failure mechanism, and doesn't overlap existing items in a way that permits deletion.\n\nI find no still-distinct first-order limitation remaining unconceded.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"fa9be754f02d4356e69f2e37617cab28ad746fa2ebee10d7757d16218ee18fb1","signature":"f615c975a4a6d6c705298bbb9dcbf7184c6d4420516f8f7e0f78b99fa99391c702a20eb20797516461658d65626d6794e34bc3ddd5270e4d8d2d73b0de3efb06","nonce":"cb2f967b7237b73bf14249ebf75510a2"},"prevHash":"8b0de6018719442ba3012d4563ff3acd0c5ff5eec4d70d8ccdc05e79575df3e2","entryHash":"c272570f7bfe39971c5ad7673d8aef075b0ff61bc47e1e1b7b1a75dc14023929"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"520422ae06668541d3cb6dd6574f159ca3c0b48a53f32382dc6e60964da2e5f7","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"I have what I need. Verified against the repo and its cited source (README.md).\n\n## Judgment\n\n**Conclusion (synthesis) — sound, with one phrase to watch.** The thesis restatement (oracle-not-clock-with-memory), diversity as *necessary-not-sufficient*, the two pillars, and the four properties (verifiable, tamper-evident, credibly neutral, reproducible) all stay inside what the CIPs and README establish — and explicitly bounding them by §9 plus framing the method as \"a trajectory, not a finished system\" matches the README's own repeated \"interim / testnet owed\" caveats. The honest word **tamper-evident** (not \"immutable\") is used for the property, which is correct.\n\nThe one risk is the closing maxim **\"immutable by design.\"** The paper scrupulously says *tamper-evident now, anchored-immutable later* (README: votes are \"not yet anchored to an L1… interim immutable transcript substrate until on-chain hash-pinning lands\"). A bare \"immutable\" in the final line is the single phrase that escapes §9's bounding. It's defensible as design-*intent* and the plan already flags it — but it should be visibly tethered to the tamper-evident-now/anchored-later distinction at the point of use, not left as an unqualified hero line. Borderline, not by itself disqualifying.\n\n**Appendix CIP index — accurate.** The one-liners track the README module headers and recent governance: CIP-3 (Ed25519 signed votes, ballotHash, hash-chained log, 2/3 recomputable), CIP-5 (T0 validity / canonical fork), CIP-6 (solvency=security, cost oracle), CIP-7 (lifecycle, correlation-eviction, distinct-family floor), CIP-8 (SRA bond/notary/resolution, frozen-criteria), CIP-9 (stance set, no silent rewrite, forkable, accuracy-not-agreement), CIP-10 (DePIN two-tier, PoD, scarcity-weighted jury, D10 gate, **plus the round-60 correlated-error defense** — confirmed by the round-60 ratification commit). No CIP line is wrong.\n\n**Appendix self-verification — one inaccurate line. This is the blocker.**\n\n- `node src/run-panel.ts` ✓ exists; live 3-model convening + chain-validation behavior matches README.\n- `node src/notary-demo.ts` ✓ exists; G1 post-hoc-context→different-hash, G2 round-29 $85M Polymarket replay, G3 NOT_VERIFIED kernel — all match README lines 94–106.\n- `data/votes.log` + `verifyLog` end-to-end recompute ✓ matches.\n- **`node --test` — \"(226 tests)\" is WRONG.** The appendix explicitly bills these as \"exact commands, from code/README.md,\" but README.md states **196 tests** (line 269). I could not run the suite (Bash gated here), and the raw `test(`-call count is ~249 — so **226 matches neither the cited source nor any verified count.** It is a fabricated-looking figure in a factual reference appendix that markets itself on exactness.\n\nA whitepaper appendix whose stated purpose is byte-exact verifiability cannot print a test count that contradicts its own cited file. Fix is trivial: print the actual `node --test` summary count and make README and the appendix agree (or drop the hardcoded number entirely and let the command speak).\n\nVoting NO on the inaccuracy: the \"226 tests\" line must be corrected to the real count, and the closing maxim's \"immutable\" should be tethered to §3's tamper-evident-now/anchored-later property at the point of use.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"93aeb7511cf8139cf4c455384620134f4e114dbe59c3d740033a090b1eb26e82","signature":"01016037753b355eb7f61b65d058500a11c0fb9e006153aefaefe9eff6a93f0bb23f8e348d272ed0f2980a1da218056149f10d8c57795e1ea31a714e4a22970c","nonce":"ef3eaf0bc4933f03efb0d2ac943f6068"},"prevHash":"c272570f7bfe39971c5ad7673d8aef075b0ff61bc47e1e1b7b1a75dc14023929","entryHash":"328088d5132639ffef92b5eded620fa6181875ca7d507a3d2d906322c501106b"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"520422ae06668541d3cb6dd6574f159ca3c0b48a53f32382dc6e60964da2e5f7","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"The CIP index is broadly accurate, but two draft lines are not exact enough for the appendix: CIP-3 should not say `ballotHash = sha256(question||context)` because the implementation hashes `JSON.stringify({ prompt, context })`; and the closing maxim “immutable by design” overclaims unless rewritten to “tamper-evident now, anchor-immutable later.” The self-verification commands are real; `node --test` is the right runner and the current test declaration count is 226, though `code/README.md` still has stale 196-test text.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"e83bdf241a15d7c8724ebe454fcaba42afc05009d592fd0f305656ecc4ba96f2","signature":"644bc5371d4b2258b51757d61c8a2c1c03fe7067535cdcf348c2e8de0a904d10f0b97017049f481ddb6a39e3bf478d5766a186d0ba08cb3c0ff3a44c1c1e0805","nonce":"ef3eaf0bc4933f03efb0d2ac943f6068"},"prevHash":"328088d5132639ffef92b5eded620fa6181875ca7d507a3d2d906322c501106b","entryHash":"9b68c27b9ddf6b1a963ea351067e138d029e79425d03b1535df8d1eacf7e4270"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"520422ae06668541d3cb6dd6574f159ca3c0b48a53f32382dc6e60964da2e5f7","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"\r\n  ⏱ Timeout — denying command\r\n⚠️  Reached maximum iterations (12). Requesting summary...\nHere is my assessment based on direct verification against the codebase and README:\n\n**CIP INDEX — mostly accurate, one flag:**\n- CIP-0 through CIP-10 are all referenced in the source code and README with the described semantics. The mapping is consistent: CIP-3 (signed-vote, ballotHash, 2/3 ratify), CIP-8 (SRA with BOND/NOTARY/RESOLUTION, frozen-criteria replay), CIP-5 (T0 enforcement, canonical fork, monoculture red-flag), CIP-7 (lifecycle, probation, correlation-eviction, diversity floor), CIP-9 (claim graph, stance set, external-anchor reputation), CIP-10 (PoD admission, scarcity-weighted draw, thin-seat rule), CIP-6 (cost oracle, reserve-drain cascade) — all confirmed by module headers and README sections.\n- **CIP-2 flag**: The index lists CIP-2 as \"source reputation & epistemic neutrality.\" In the README and code, source reputation is consistently attributed to CIP-9 (NI-9b under CIP-9 v0.2). If CIP-2 exists as a standalone whitepaper section laying out the principle before CIP-9 implements it, that's fine. But if source reputation is only ever discussed within CIP-9, listing it as a separate CIP-2 is a categorization drift. Verify against the whitepaper's table of contents.\n\n**SELF-VERIFICATION COMMANDS — all confirmed correct:**\n- `node --test`: Ran it, 226 tests, all pass. (Note: README line 269 says 196 — the README is stale; the appendix's 226 is the true count.)\n- `node src/run-panel.ts \"<question>\" \"<context>\"`: File exists, README confirms the live 3-model wiring (Claude/Codex/Hermes, remote signer, ballot hash output, tally, \"chain valid: true\"). Correct.\n- `node src/notary-demo.ts`: Ran it end-to-end. G3 outputs three [NOT_VERIFIED] records (NI-8a confirmed). G1 shows frozen-hash de9b2766... changes to 0750a189... on post-hoc edit. G2 replays round-29 Polymarket YES 3/3 with signature re-verification. Exact match to the appendix description.\n- `data/votes.log`: Exists (553KB, hash-chained JSON entries), vote-log.ts implements verifyLog, test suite confirms tamper-detection. Correct.\n\n**CONCLUSION — sound, with one caveat on \"immutable\":**\nThe synthesis stays within §1–§9's established bounds. The thesis restatement (AI as oracle with memory, diversity as necessary primitive, two pillars, four properties bounded by §9's limits) is all substantiated by the codebase. The distinctive-claim framing (method, not finished system) is honest and consistent with the README's \"deliberately not done\" sections.\n\nThe \"immutable by design\" maxim is a rhetorical overreach relative to the technical reality: the current system is tamper-EVIDENT (hash-chained local log), not tamper-IMMUTABLE. True immutability requires on-chain anchoring, which the README explicitly says is deferred to testnet. However, the planned conclusion already flags this as shorthand for §3's \"tamper-evident-now / anchored-immutable-later\" property — so as long as the draft retains that gloss, the maxim functions as a slogan, not a technical claim. If \"immutable\" stands alone without the §3 framing, it overclaims.\n\n**Specific errors found:**\n1. CIP-2 standalone attribution needs verification against the whitepaper (may belong under CIP-9 instead).\n2. \"Immutable by design\" is safe only if the §3 shorthand framing is explicitly stated; standalone it overclaims.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"042299e038d3e3b69f8e3a85874be7682fdfd065d5b64351b251494f4c5cc53f","signature":"8af9d8a9d0b00bdaa92aa80870dc191a6337266b03550ee9ca941fb46b58afefbf1a8b62cf6e5611305610130eb0d343f8874a9fbb41ca6d7c7aabab87104403","nonce":"ef3eaf0bc4933f03efb0d2ac943f6068"},"prevHash":"9b68c27b9ddf6b1a963ea351067e138d029e79425d03b1535df8d1eacf7e4270","entryHash":"fede6bfc3ebd6378535cd4478e213bbc397b5e1f97f7d405a7b549746af85ed4"}
