{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"6151e0dc0987bd040dc747e7ee50b9fab59c7c870367e0ccf7a21394fb5edd9f","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Based on verifiable court records, on May 30, 2024, a New York state jury in the case *People v. Trump* returned guilty verdicts on all 34 counts of falsifying business records in the first degree — a Class E felony under New York Penal Law § 175.10. This was the first criminal conviction of a former U.S. president. The conviction itself is a matter of public record, regardless of any subsequent appeals or sentencing proceedings.\n\nThe frozen criteria are met: a New York state jury returned guilty verdicts against Donald J. Trump in the 2024 People v. Trump case on 34 counts of falsifying business records, verdict date May 30, 2024.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"d1eabed258edcf3209accd2974bd9649709327f2a3755933b54838bdc4646cdc","signature":"8ddc639d3fc34c21240771059af1851aa595ed786145cc8465a76b1d19658490a50f985149c53895eae07fef035336f196a435f8aab813652fa9a4b645429504","nonce":"28f443e5245d660366116c4fd0b024d2"},"prevHash":"f72519db9b58e7bdf7ad55fa27de9b45416c95c52d76e39aeb5b523ccf78fe93","entryHash":"d7bca9794958d038c02861679129e2e4a6746db2693b706fac49aa79532b64aa"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"cef99931048e43c992122aa2a6fcf71e5180e97494882f1481aeecd64eb3130c","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The decision is a matter of public record within my knowledge. On June 24, 2022, the U.S. Supreme Court issued *Dobbs v. Jackson Women's Health Organization*, expressly overruling *Roe v. Wade* (and *Planned Parenthood v. Casey*) and holding that the Constitution does not confer a right to abortion, returning the authority to regulate abortion to the states.\n\nThis maps directly onto the frozen criteria: the Court, in Dobbs (June 2022), overturned Roe and held there is no federal constitutional right to abortion. Resolving on the legal holding alone, the condition for RESOLVED-YES is satisfied.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"8b81f7c180c1168cf0fbf313a7a2a5f030734160b16224f946deaa8306e4c142","signature":"88fe3c6cb7d75079cb897acd0e1e577f49500ef5c3ecad033c0e0a2e9cd88eea7dcbe6cd37420962f002391281019b57c9fffc17855d75763f8270ee3fb49905","nonce":"43732a3a57721e5e08bd907f8fec9cb0"},"prevHash":"d7bca9794958d038c02861679129e2e4a6746db2693b706fac49aa79532b64aa","entryHash":"0c14a4c9b91df47db7da9cb150eb7efa41083c26f33cf0ec525b9086dd1bc6ae"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"cef99931048e43c992122aa2a6fcf71e5180e97494882f1481aeecd64eb3130c","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Dobbs v. Jackson Women's Health Organization, decided on June 24, 2022, expressly overruled Roe v. Wade and held that the U.S. Constitution does not confer a federal right to abortion.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"52f147e6c29b0c0e4c08d9c94865e098bc7c745cc41fafb6cf601ea3c9aad226","signature":"517887e6c15981cd7b7efd2dbfcd0fc23065174cf78c4bf1b67f34096002255862c33de7b3ae356471d8bd236ee3c62076994759c42b0f80189f2fff2ce97c02","nonce":"43732a3a57721e5e08bd907f8fec9cb0"},"prevHash":"0c14a4c9b91df47db7da9cb150eb7efa41083c26f33cf0ec525b9086dd1bc6ae","entryHash":"8b94eb7b3ca41f7b1040b56c70d60d998de646790b80149717c83b5c56259b8f"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"cef99931048e43c992122aa2a6fcf71e5180e97494882f1481aeecd64eb3130c","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The U.S. Supreme Court, in *Dobbs v. Jackson Women's Health Organization*, 597 U.S. ___ (2022) (decided June 24, 2022), explicitly overruled both *Roe v. Wade* (1973) and *Planned Parenthood v. Casey* (1992). The majority opinion held that the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment does not confer a federal constitutional right to abortion, thereby returning the authority to regulate abortion to the people and their elected representatives at the state level. This is a matter of public record in the published opinion.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"886467b169c663944c64779ed99758a49a67ef6e5fb78150e2291f5f3251c025","signature":"8a7098a96a95eb1661d7d35bd2569e2197dc8eacc694e24eb2802ce1b1aa97c0bf1fab224de8a6f938db1ec0d028f02d5bb5928bc106e22d48d53c1b17b5ca0b","nonce":"43732a3a57721e5e08bd907f8fec9cb0"},"prevHash":"8b94eb7b3ca41f7b1040b56c70d60d998de646790b80149717c83b5c56259b8f","entryHash":"7b2c0d5ef2d4634dadf0fd80f8e9552f60ceaac257947d138cd5457674bfaff4"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"cbab2971d0c1476d7327c277d6da05fff6cdd38670b20687b2c613cb953deaab","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"On November 2, 2023, a federal jury in the Southern District of New York found Samuel Bankman-Fried guilty on all seven counts he faced, including multiple counts of wire fraud and conspiracy tied directly to the diversion of FTX customer funds to Alameda Research. This matches the frozen criteria's anchor (SDNY federal jury verdict, November 2023) precisely.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"1d372cc5bd41ca7707190318a725fdb6a27bece9e7ab8196bb207a590dad1d96","signature":"c7180b0948dd54c4d589070a863916d617110474c73e155ac9751acde63ee2a04656757ea4aa90ab82937323d74fecf34687642231d2c1afb17280bd3d05eb05","nonce":"5b8f2c2a437b3e7dd9883336f3068bc4"},"prevHash":"7b2c0d5ef2d4634dadf0fd80f8e9552f60ceaac257947d138cd5457674bfaff4","entryHash":"b0e29c851dcea1fe2a7e09543b5e21992e346c5db8f7376298b4e62b4f36aa40"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"cbab2971d0c1476d7327c277d6da05fff6cdd38670b20687b2c613cb953deaab","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Sam Bankman-Fried was convicted by an SDNY federal jury in November 2023 on fraud and conspiracy charges tied to FTX customer funds and Alameda Research.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"ce4e8606897d47b472fa485f7ef22cf8b5a18a588a2ce0e3b88bb515ccf4a86b","signature":"d93188b3c5149b469a4d85ea6f3737e0f1ce31d5b4ce0891167f86a4971e5d0c0a3b8e43a965a2a4c8f7ae3d7a64d15f0b7d074ec541467b0c9c62d4a0a77b0d","nonce":"5b8f2c2a437b3e7dd9883336f3068bc4"},"prevHash":"b0e29c851dcea1fe2a7e09543b5e21992e346c5db8f7376298b4e62b4f36aa40","entryHash":"b699f917b3c1eaa1356c72fd75d758e47ef30d3d4a06b50b33962089ffbe6e70"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"cbab2971d0c1476d7327c277d6da05fff6cdd38670b20687b2c613cb953deaab","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Sam Bankman-Fried was tried in the Southern District of New York federal court. On November 2, 2023, a federal jury found him guilty on all seven counts, including wire fraud, securities fraud, and multiple conspiracy charges connected to the collapse of FTX and Alameda Research. This is a matter of established public record.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"6e4f7cbfff7961ab39ef17e16046ab84d4a22eae4780dcb472159124d5fe38d7","signature":"ea90074248381884643fc01fd7eacec234df3e792bcf1b5b137d7e63743d51ce1a6d7ece924109c9184c9dcbcf3411101eda58a9fb20933f8800ae25023fb20e","nonce":"5b8f2c2a437b3e7dd9883336f3068bc4"},"prevHash":"b699f917b3c1eaa1356c72fd75d758e47ef30d3d4a06b50b33962089ffbe6e70","entryHash":"74dd3ca06e2bb635dbaa0b3d055517ff6bc09e826263cd12378a7d6448abf2d1"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"37d4e5d320163eaf2fd9f49b9a44b535b967e85feec6598ea78f0a1d165abf3b","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"**Reasoning:** U.S. copyright law conditions registration on human authorship. The Copyright Office's registration practices (and its 2023 guidance / 2025 AI report) consistently refuse claims to material that is wholly machine-generated, registering only the human-authored contributions (selection, arrangement, modification). *Thaler v. Perlmutter* squarely holds the Copyright Act requires a human author — the D.D.C. (2023) upheld the Office's refusal to register an image listing an AI as sole author, and the D.C. Circuit affirmed (2025). A work with *no* human author falls outside the statute's reach.\n\nThe qualifier \"wholly AI-generated image with no human author\" removes the usual escape hatch (human-authored selection/arrangement or substantial editing). On those facts the answer is settled against registrability.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"fffdfc67ed7e21b09f088fca7a6b665318b41290a3d274dacb0306a6730d4fb0","signature":"23b4253d85b21ef34b96dc393443a84f3dd6c28ce8e7b000490098fac2d8c156c3c6034abfeae21adea1c848221c9ab70d8b373e245376d84645332905edab06","nonce":"35a636b91b69a2aff79cea578ad74915"},"prevHash":"74dd3ca06e2bb635dbaa0b3d055517ff6bc09e826263cd12378a7d6448abf2d1","entryHash":"ca01b57bc13cf1058dad1e36a57cea5858e90fb4f272be28c184e7b6d048d273"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"37d4e5d320163eaf2fd9f49b9a44b535b967e85feec6598ea78f0a1d165abf3b","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Current U.S. copyright law requires human authorship for registration. The Copyright Office has refused registrations for works identified as wholly AI-generated without human creative input, and *Thaler v. Perlmutter* confirms that an AI system cannot be the author of a copyrightable work. So a wholly AI-generated image with no human author cannot be registered.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"70c5609751dd88cc1cf880ba42632d09cf0783f4033777afc9e5e788773600cf","signature":"86753bc10d4cdf4d4744e84fc0f21d445db8fe41f7f2112edfe7257bf7b0892c40d0ae07772ee6fdd86b247b0e05b934aad69a72f1a84ffa143a11c6f9af290c","nonce":"35a636b91b69a2aff79cea578ad74915"},"prevHash":"ca01b57bc13cf1058dad1e36a57cea5858e90fb4f272be28c184e7b6d048d273","entryHash":"7cf30f74ba0196e97294d04688edb9a90cb77a1d910aaaeb372393b1f4047b39"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"37d4e5d320163eaf2fd9f49b9a44b535b967e85feec6598ea78f0a1d165abf3b","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"The U.S. Copyright Act uses the term \"author\" without defining it, but courts and the Copyright Office have consistently interpreted it to mean a human being. This long-standing interpretation was directly tested in *Thaler v. Perlmutter*: Thaler applied to register an AI-generated image (the \"Creativity Machine\" output), listing the AI as the sole author. The Copyright Office refused. The D.D.C. (2023) and then the D.C. Circuit (2025) both affirmed that refusal, agreeing that the statute's authorship requirement is exclusively human.\n\nThis is not a narrow or ambiguous holding — it squarely covers the ballot's scenario of a \"wholly AI-generated image with no human author.\" The Copyright Office has also codified this position in its policy guidance and in multiple registration refusals for AI-assisted works where human creative input was deemed insufficient.\n\nThere is no competing authority or open circuit split that would cast doubt on this. The law is settled.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"7b06576277c326617699657f9f19ec127b617c91532df0c3b1ab64a04624f921","signature":"dd8bdd30a647cffc726271bac8afa581e621b6297ff6e0ec90973eefbb5cf91a64112cc94ee1813fbc59c34096b8fef2f34b2ebfc1dc7a1e34b85ee3163e7201","nonce":"35a636b91b69a2aff79cea578ad74915"},"prevHash":"7cf30f74ba0196e97294d04688edb9a90cb77a1d910aaaeb372393b1f4047b39","entryHash":"ee86d25cd7207d75fc976fb9315e46aa01a5419fb0bbc8f109ab533aec9f3210"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"d9ac7659aa50424a2a10521109099d09c6621cb345e55f192de9e9a63a5821ce","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"This is a well-documented factual matter against frozen criteria.\n\nOn **26 January 2024**, the ICJ issued its Order on the Request for the Indication of Provisional Measures in *South Africa v. Israel* (Application of the Genocide Convention in the Gaza Strip). The Court:\n\n- Held it had prima facie jurisdiction under Article IX of the Genocide Convention.\n- Found that **at least some of the rights asserted by South Africa under the Genocide Convention were \"plausible\"** (notably the right of Palestinians in Gaza to be protected from acts of genocide).\n- **Indicated provisional measures** ordering Israel, *inter alia*, to take all measures within its power to prevent genocidal acts, prevent and punish public incitement to genocide, enable provision of humanitarian assistance, preserve evidence, and report to the Court within one month.\n\nThe order expressly did **not** determine that genocide occurred — consistent with the frozen criteria's instruction to resolve only on the existence and content of the provisional-measures order. Both required elements (the \"plausible\" rights finding and the indication of measures binding Israel) are satisfied by the published anchor order.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"b6872e01cb192c3669c9dc0b2383a078f2f6f591b30a63b883620eb2d4074038","signature":"c4868d35957a5104ad8fe97aa987f2f00198d43dab100150bc3e358bc2917f837ed5060ccef271aa3f58271e799d31f4a2cda18882e84795e0e6378289e33d0a","nonce":"95afcf7e5087a39b59c537076cd8ab10"},"prevHash":"ee86d25cd7207d75fc976fb9315e46aa01a5419fb0bbc8f109ab533aec9f3210","entryHash":"6d1e5a4022c64476faaf680a0824e3243336ecd6a480455dc0d9dc7a0da9fa8a"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"d9ac7659aa50424a2a10521109099d09c6621cb345e55f192de9e9a63a5821ce","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"On 26 January 2024, the ICJ issued a provisional-measures order in South Africa v. Israel. The Court found that at least some rights South Africa asserted under the Genocide Convention were plausible, and it ordered Israel to take specified measures. This was not a merits finding that genocide occurred.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"b917330d3b47fa6e8180ef0ce39ee3365af04c06702128c38cf88f47339527c3","signature":"95ee2b372db1369661eb6e89fc6d67c1aaed581d55581b0fb26bf6802c9e92117db6b122bcc0a4bb0cd42f3b317512d5c955c4860ddff3cfd609f57ed48a8506","nonce":"95afcf7e5087a39b59c537076cd8ab10"},"prevHash":"6d1e5a4022c64476faaf680a0824e3243336ecd6a480455dc0d9dc7a0da9fa8a","entryHash":"f5efff309545849001163d3c8e9cfe4376f3210d2d84794101d866dfbd6c6d76"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"d9ac7659aa50424a2a10521109099d09c6621cb345e55f192de9e9a63a5821ce","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The ICJ issued its order on provisional measures on 26 January 2024 in *South Africa v. Israel* (Application of the Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide in the Gaza Strip). The Court applied the provisional-measures test, which requires that the rights claimed be at least **plausible** — a low threshold distinct from a merits finding. The ICJ held that some rights under the Genocide Convention asserted by South Africa were plausible, and it indicated several provisional measures requiring Israel to act to prevent genocidal conduct and to enable humanitarian aid. The Court explicitly stated this order was **not** a determination on the merits of whether genocide had occurred.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"8a8a9d4171aaf686f6142f68c28f226c79c182d38fc12e83c4a7db94487aea88","signature":"03de79e6e05b2ca3fc5b88c8ce969d5acf8f0dddd45c3872faceb96512c7cb20879171046547b0e2847111004afb94a675354584dcea29534885bc85ad26bf0c","nonce":"95afcf7e5087a39b59c537076cd8ab10"},"prevHash":"f5efff309545849001163d3c8e9cfe4376f3210d2d84794101d866dfbd6c6d76","entryHash":"6140b72ca66d43287de60c04c3ba37e27d3397812c51559ee9b63cba1180c4e6"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"c29ddf0fe456f4a5002af150ff636f5811ce0d5b75eef722ee2ccb4672097c72","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"On April 20, 2021, a Minnesota jury (Hennepin County) found Derek Chauvin guilty on all three counts in the death of George Floyd: second-degree unintentional murder, third-degree murder, and second-degree manslaughter. Two of those three counts are murder convictions.\n\nAgainst the frozen criteria — conviction by a Minnesota jury of murder, anchored to the jury verdict — this is squarely satisfied.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"255738026322925253db0d47b94059f3f564ce9eef703015042e3b2af4317f37","signature":"44922fb170aacf6ddb3663861ae8c2e13a5e7f089d01e4e53d3ddb68d20a2d9eb2621068ce56226a83c961346eebf1113559b359756e8adb445d5c9f448d6604","nonce":"53a809719b6a0fe7fe62880437144013"},"prevHash":"6140b72ca66d43287de60c04c3ba37e27d3397812c51559ee9b63cba1180c4e6","entryHash":"d0817645e31e3d39de5cdbd244b647b0ceb5457b782c0e765a4faf92b03c105e"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"c29ddf0fe456f4a5002af150ff636f5811ce0d5b75eef722ee2ccb4672097c72","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Derek Chauvin was convicted by a Minnesota jury in April 2021 of second-degree unintentional murder, third-degree murder, and second-degree manslaughter in the death of George Floyd.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"2d52c3da1daf77e10c3ba6c1c8d6a31f5b6f431df8af02d5f3f18f70314dd70c","signature":"7b06e9387dcc463a63546cbb52bb3523b4dc39d2b96db2f27b72b09904e0b160117845328b29d94b98948dc8a1f9c8af8207cfd5a564328cc92b8e3fc0d8680d","nonce":"53a809719b6a0fe7fe62880437144013"},"prevHash":"d0817645e31e3d39de5cdbd244b647b0ceb5457b782c0e765a4faf92b03c105e","entryHash":"206fca5c1a0b2948dffbe3191a2c4d70053959787a13b4afa20736e76106fa61"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"c29ddf0fe456f4a5002af150ff636f5811ce0d5b75eef722ee2ccb4672097c72","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Derek Chauvin was tried in Minnesota state court for the death of George Floyd. On April 20, 2021, a Hennepin County jury returned guilty verdicts on all three charges: second-degree unintentional murder, third-degree murder, and second-degree manslaughter. This is a matter of public record and the jury verdict serves as the anchor event specified in the criteria.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"c4f690e30aef3bd9baf1f29323ea8deaaebcadac2a41664a95273db3783e8221","signature":"3dbd58df3dc64a1d1799a2d7a9f1d5ea1483dd6d1ca9f1f918e863bdf272a1149f284c4d4cc90968108007ef62c155bf7faba4487bc23b7141d1be35eae2fb0d","nonce":"53a809719b6a0fe7fe62880437144013"},"prevHash":"206fca5c1a0b2948dffbe3191a2c4d70053959787a13b4afa20736e76106fa61","entryHash":"abaff9ecfd4762ec9625ea84d13ad7f2bb1366e2a352c682edd0ed65551450d5"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"f7f4e895b0fe60045a89e76c8aeab32ebe65d272b22c0273d5a956fed4ed68de","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"## Reasoning\n\nSection 230(c)(1) of the Communications Decency Act (47 U.S.C. § 230) states: \"No provider or user of an interactive computer service shall be treated as the publisher or speaker of any information provided by another information content provider.\"\n\nSettled case law — beginning with *Zeran v. America Online* (4th Cir. 1997) and consistently applied since — interprets this broadly to immunize interactive computer services from liability arising out of third-party (user-created) content. This is the dominant, well-established reading across federal circuits.\n\nThe frozen criterion asks about the **general** rule. That general rule clearly holds. The known carve-outs — federal criminal law, intellectual property claims, the ECPA, and the FOSTA-SESTA sex-trafficking exception (2018) — are narrow exceptions that do not displace the broad baseline immunity. The qualifier \"generally\" in the criteria accommodates exactly these exceptions.\n\nThe anchor (statute + settled case law) supports RESOLVED-YES.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"01e072c1df011782d547944033eea7f96c0f781906fe35af1fcab01861d2369e","signature":"21eeb63b466a170b9b823e4970b1c55888e59160fbf75d96757c0ca5319b2f7c436aefa80351a191d6a578c8ea7fd34b2a32d7d58ad6ab4dbcc187dd88c67809","nonce":"ca1083d1c6ae101d1d8ed8362a19878f"},"prevHash":"abaff9ecfd4762ec9625ea84d13ad7f2bb1366e2a352c682edd0ed65551450d5","entryHash":"3285570d2bd3271c8f78f12c9a7dba80633ed658ac0d9e0dba64b43b11367aaf"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"f7f4e895b0fe60045a89e76c8aeab32ebe65d272b22c0273d5a956fed4ed68de","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Section 230(c)(1) says providers/users of an interactive computer service are not treated as the publisher or speaker of information provided by another information content provider. CRS summarizes the settled test the same way: it generally bars claims against platforms when liability is based on third-party user content. There are exceptions, but the frozen criterion asks whether it generally shields platforms, so the answer is yes.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"981abddf383c4b317b12e2649bc8029d2cb51de98cc56ddcc555f69abdef9d93","signature":"56025015dfc675c69b00f804ff4431f5d9abf23efdb614e410f13a237ba0f9b9066724961676d51c0ba871c927ba27dd93d8ae94ae834529f2b3f587fc420d0f","nonce":"ca1083d1c6ae101d1d8ed8362a19878f"},"prevHash":"3285570d2bd3271c8f78f12c9a7dba80633ed658ac0d9e0dba64b43b11367aaf","entryHash":"a3485e94f8c69bf747cca499de65f5709aedd7c07bca033a0b203b0299122bf3"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"f7f4e895b0fe60045a89e76c8aeab32ebe65d272b22c0273d5a956fed4ed68de","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Section 230(c)(1) of the Communications Decency Act (47 U.S.C. § 230(c)(1)) expressly provides that no interactive computer service shall be treated as the publisher or speaker of information provided by another content provider. This has been consistently upheld across decades of federal case law—from *Zeran v. AOL* (4th Cir. 1997) through recent circuits—establishing broad immunity for platforms against liability arising from third-party user content. While narrow exceptions exist (federal criminal law, IP, FOSTA-SESTA), the general rule is well-settled: platforms are immune. The criteria's use of \"generally immunizes\" matches the statute and settled precedent.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"7e39d53c19c919fec6b804a5b353f8de60190dc397055b6c2918d918e65353d4","signature":"7dae37a76d1d69aaeef18946159b0a67a06cd5f6d74cdf03f113613e65e584636ae626d05a5a369c186aa006312ed260a852dd894f105c81f0f3dceb52eb8700","nonce":"ca1083d1c6ae101d1d8ed8362a19878f"},"prevHash":"a3485e94f8c69bf747cca499de65f5709aedd7c07bca033a0b203b0299122bf3","entryHash":"2d6537d8ecfbde59c7ef5973173f8230a629c2a5851c941750cc170b12f07ba0"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"1d46b7778e062500a355c46faaa88dff3724d6e59fb08c6b629fd8e69c83a427","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Brief reasoning: Obergefell v. Hodges, 576 U.S. 644 (2015), decided 5–4 with Justice Kennedy writing for the majority, held that the Fourteenth Amendment's Due Process and Equal Protection Clauses require states to license marriages between same-sex couples and to recognize such marriages performed out of state. The holding squarely establishes a constitutional right of same-sex couples to marry. This matches the frozen criteria exactly.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"40b1b58b70ebd9a6f37815619f76fadded95c20ab66c73f90be8d9d1e0c7b6c9","signature":"f16d673e480345d6592ed893930bdf1faedc970ea6beea861b3ca7e288980f567d2412f0704d80f235e043a519518a92a40b74cb9b8094e9a9774a5c371bcf03","nonce":"18f100cb6f3aeee1129de34b849dd38b"},"prevHash":"2d6537d8ecfbde59c7ef5973173f8230a629c2a5851c941750cc170b12f07ba0","entryHash":"fb7508ddda355183d72ebd4af04e319c73e0beb9fd85fc613c2925128dd46810"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"1d46b7778e062500a355c46faaa88dff3724d6e59fb08c6b629fd8e69c83a427","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Obergefell v. Hodges (2015) held that the Fourteenth Amendment requires states to license marriages between same-sex couples and recognize lawful same-sex marriages performed elsewhere. This satisfies the resolved-YES criteria.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"7e420ee59dd835a804a4e330272c6a3b88920ee9a301d06cac5aa9d03eb63807","signature":"985743c242d9cc181e65b63bd2e3bf4206698b8a361db0cccbf8ed164b36b19efe66e7e693e1483d4ad2010d618ae5e64e2fdfd38b1b36d7452dbb094538180e","nonce":"18f100cb6f3aeee1129de34b849dd38b"},"prevHash":"fb7508ddda355183d72ebd4af04e319c73e0beb9fd85fc613c2925128dd46810","entryHash":"b5644bef4b49facba1e283ab5e7efd1f56aff2898eac88f40e32b815f24617dd"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"1d46b7778e062500a355c46faaa88dff3724d6e59fb08c6b629fd8e69c83a427","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The U.S. Supreme Court held in *Obergefell v. Hodges*, 576 U.S. 644 (2015), that the Fourteenth Amendment requires every state to license a marriage between two people of the same sex and to recognize such marriages lawfully performed in other states. The 5–4 majority opinion, authored by Justice Kennedy, found that the right to marry is a fundamental liberty guaranteed by both the Due Process Clause and the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment, and that this right extends to same-sex couples.\n\nThe evidence matches the frozen criterion exactly.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"f8f56422367724feef8e9784afb4b7868df3dc5f3cbf38e88160118e91ff2b36","signature":"da75d8f21bd3a5152f0b36f7f7c4ffb4915a068e2e762ed5e1c18f9420c638a610deb9e109581514ed9ff3e3fb072d2c9f5ca989e3d306927cbba7eb8df9c205","nonce":"18f100cb6f3aeee1129de34b849dd38b"},"prevHash":"b5644bef4b49facba1e283ab5e7efd1f56aff2898eac88f40e32b815f24617dd","entryHash":"257f994aada5fa603e6907b296c3925609f39ddd46ac702d2c1571433bce7c97"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"bfc6421fe8a361caa2717b8a3f19722d397f579cc37104560113d44e15d358d0","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"This is a well-established matter of constitutional law. In *Citizens United v. FEC*, 558 U.S. 310 (2010), the Supreme Court held 5–4 that the First Amendment prohibits the government from restricting independent political expenditures by corporations, unions, and associations. The Court overruled *Austin v. Michigan Chamber of Commerce* (1990) and the relevant portion of *McConnell v. FEC*, striking down §441b's ban on independent corporate/union expenditures. The frozen criteria's distinction — independent expenditures (not direct contributions) — matches the holding precisely.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"3829e371675b3c66faca36c15bd4f5ae45ae1c49aa4bb55032a389ddf97bb342","signature":"b6d539466a0e396ed8593fec666336e4f6f900089dcd672038ab950a89c3b72b015e8488718fd55deb789dcf992439f13d87d879a6ee6ebfe24aa125514b820e","nonce":"666426ab1335c35896f7f3500b80a5f9"},"prevHash":"257f994aada5fa603e6907b296c3925609f39ddd46ac702d2c1571433bce7c97","entryHash":"623b35bd66187d4c5bdee0be97f3ed76e5e2fcfb493ded12ce1eae8cff46bc94"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"bfc6421fe8a361caa2717b8a3f19722d397f579cc37104560113d44e15d358d0","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Citizens United v. FEC (2010) held that the First Amendment prohibits the government from suppressing independent political expenditures based on the speaker’s corporate identity, covering corporations and unions.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"e541c13b5ba69e3905dd07e911bcd4e1896434a03b221a032b272574a9ceb8ad","signature":"e725600be1e2df4545a27cbccfd9beb784662d3b3a9bbc58c97cb0c610bb94d92f585453bd151573b85c57db7d5801631ae6c386c8874eb0cf3af6ae467d570f","nonce":"666426ab1335c35896f7f3500b80a5f9"},"prevHash":"623b35bd66187d4c5bdee0be97f3ed76e5e2fcfb493ded12ce1eae8cff46bc94","entryHash":"d3c82b32fcc65ae3b634e90b5e608e868c3078d1aa8b4218bd91329fc19953f0"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"bfc6421fe8a361caa2717b8a3f19722d397f579cc37104560113d44e15d358d0","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Yes. In Citizens United v. FEC, 558 U.S. 310 (2010), the Supreme Court held 5-4 that the First Amendment prohibits the government from restricting independent political expenditures by corporations, labor unions, and other associations. The majority opinion (per Justice Kennedy) struck down the relevant provisions of the Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act of 2002, reasoning that political speech is indispensable to a democracy and that the government may not suppress it simply because the speaker is a corporation or union.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"e7e9fbff7bd8d2fea39e6e6c1c745b84491f8b1e3fe4ee6944cd6f1b24d59cf9","signature":"54113281eae5f1b3390568f8cce2310fdf7f51f9843be91ff46c274f779f4e3f807ee3e65b0aa943b3b1918f37fbbc9ab123df61ac4efc17679aa6a7b79fa403","nonce":"666426ab1335c35896f7f3500b80a5f9"},"prevHash":"d3c82b32fcc65ae3b634e90b5e608e868c3078d1aa8b4218bd91329fc19953f0","entryHash":"78a23d37ba0f6eaf19333a6f1d3354b85c34567cf48706901da6c596276a2a33"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"8e08b2d4d60e1a9280815630d8d443ff95c548d42e2d03df689c513d8e555e0a","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"This is a factual ballot judgment, not a coding task — no skill applies. Reasoning directly.\n\nThe anchor event is well-established: In June 2024, Julian Assange entered a guilty plea before the U.S. District Court for the Northern Mariana Islands (Saipan) to one count of conspiracy to obtain and disclose national defense information — a violation of 18 U.S.C. § 793, the Espionage Act. The plea agreement sentenced him to time served (the ~62 months already spent in UK detention), and he was released immediately, returning to Australia.\n\nAll three frozen criteria are satisfied:\n- Guilty plea in 2024 ✓\n- Charge under the U.S. Espionage Act ✓\n- Plea agreement that resulted in his release ✓\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"335e9809b9cba05691f8616e2193a30dd48a1dc383ca3e4b19beb0825a1390a6","signature":"bc6a28a286d24c9e187549b8f10318a10feee38fe76cb4d5d9d087a7e449ea0bf0e4c59d95fbc366ff564d55c6b9ed1144723cad54a11e034049e9b9d08de40f","nonce":"ebc0d860a6d3b724301f1207c0d1abac"},"prevHash":"78a23d37ba0f6eaf19333a6f1d3354b85c34567cf48706901da6c596276a2a33","entryHash":"15700455cefbe6af8e94cec8d34cc037d81589def3a14a74b48d47c2747c50d6"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"8e08b2d4d60e1a9280815630d8d443ff95c548d42e2d03df689c513d8e555e0a","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Julian Assange pleaded guilty on June 26, 2024, in U.S. District Court in the Northern Mariana Islands to one Espionage Act count as part of a plea agreement. He was sentenced to time served and released, satisfying the frozen criteria.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"a37a2b6b451298d2fa2d17f2badedd47b676e6c0561e99b217f001f339313953","signature":"685380b2b0ea72b57543d9a3e689d6394d50b07df56f2fc1b58a75f3547faaca95af1979a8c7e8b6bc3150d6492844aabe40d77642e7fc58114fa5f65b55b507","nonce":"ebc0d860a6d3b724301f1207c0d1abac"},"prevHash":"15700455cefbe6af8e94cec8d34cc037d81589def3a14a74b48d47c2747c50d6","entryHash":"01f2fc5167b457b713100693a85db4ea08cbfc8f96660a5f16b35f41086d0b6d"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"8e08b2d4d60e1a9280815630d8d443ff95c548d42e2d03df689c513d8e555e0a","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The evidence from multiple reputable sources confirms that in June 2024, Julian Assange pleaded guilty to conspiracy to obtain and disclose classified information — a felony charge under the U.S. Espionage Act — at a hearing in the U.S. District Court for the Northern Mariana Islands (Saipan). Under the plea agreement, he was sentenced to time already served and was released, allowing him to return to Australia.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"b57ac08a6990cc8fc7e903f2bed8e2eed414598ea5c42210c33cb8250502eda7","signature":"00093ba41494109a4a4d9d18bdf8986e27399c3c6e1f611fa59bf686874403cb0a20e8a6a7957197d615946250322548c504a8270fea76f95617c7572341f90a","nonce":"ebc0d860a6d3b724301f1207c0d1abac"},"prevHash":"01f2fc5167b457b713100693a85db4ea08cbfc8f96660a5f16b35f41086d0b6d","entryHash":"85227323dc712383baff284d5340560628d2edce553c93e33f2ca33b13fcf6e8"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"e99ea0f89e3dbc3fc6da838670864f2ae1dbea9092d68e0ee8bf96c81b97f50e","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Elizabeth Holmes was convicted by a federal jury in San Jose, California, on January 3, 2022, on four counts: one count of conspiracy to defraud investors and three counts of wire fraud against specific Theranos investors. This matches the frozen criteria exactly (federal jury, January 2022, fraud relating to Theranos). The anchor — the verdict — clearly resolves the event.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"89eb7bfac2b02836384660998103844bb73dd607063926b0830487b4672c13d4","signature":"c621d868a7782b4b7f015c7b4c67523d5b35d3c9dc3ed87a1a488e04bc66a801a845b957effd012058bd104ac2726aff22b95fbe917ed769ea810b3a01022f0d","nonce":"5623c2e9c8d6ffaefc27b3a9ade49efb"},"prevHash":"85227323dc712383baff284d5340560628d2edce553c93e33f2ca33b13fcf6e8","entryHash":"4c04a0f31eaf28b1d1dcdba2bc664d154c4f8e013b32ab5f07260510544975d5"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"e99ea0f89e3dbc3fc6da838670864f2ae1dbea9092d68e0ee8bf96c81b97f50e","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Elizabeth Holmes was convicted by a federal jury in January 2022 on fraud-related counts connected to Theranos. This satisfies the frozen RESOLVED-YES criterion.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"8fc21b547e4ed9d795687a8724b130411c672eb2ad7ec829db17876c867a69b5","signature":"734cfa4ea812112fb04d4997d62e6cb484e2e902b74ada71a0aa00d6d2fa6856cd5a6463bf8cb4c715da88f0f3485100c96f81d7dbb027771b3bd06716a4aa0a","nonce":"5623c2e9c8d6ffaefc27b3a9ade49efb"},"prevHash":"4c04a0f31eaf28b1d1dcdba2bc664d154c4f8e013b32ab5f07260510544975d5","entryHash":"9957b338f65a64e932a4f0de3670c1347e713d7d27e8b81778831829f900de9e"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"e99ea0f89e3dbc3fc6da838670864f2ae1dbea9092d68e0ee8bf96c81b97f50e","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Elizabeth Holmes, founder and former CEO of Theranos, was tried in federal court (N.D. Cal., Case No. 18-cr-00258). On January 3, 2022, a federal jury returned a verdict finding her guilty on four counts: one count of conspiracy to defraud investors (18 U.S.C. § 371) and three counts of wire fraud to defraud investors (18 U.S.C. § 1343). She was acquitted on four separate wire-fraud counts and one conspiracy count. The convictions were specifically for defrauding investors in Theranos; she was not convicted on counts relating to defrauding doctors/patients. She was subsequently sentenced to 11 years and 3 months in prison in November 2022.\n\nThe frozen criterion asks whether she was convicted of fraud relating to Theranos by a federal jury in January 2022. The answer is unambiguously yes.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"1e2513917c6fee114be97ad8ab21e810d9b76b579a17c7dbb1a34d70086a34ad","signature":"1482a73911946be426892b5b0cb81d5c4a158f18e5490ab1be79d623f897cf9b939da245fdce5b60adcd981bc59e0b8ae740ede09250d4ca38a3b7765ca8f709","nonce":"5623c2e9c8d6ffaefc27b3a9ade49efb"},"prevHash":"9957b338f65a64e932a4f0de3670c1347e713d7d27e8b81778831829f900de9e","entryHash":"ed1e9d336c0615762db62357595c875524f29b9db2dbb62e78219de23de7592d"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"bf0decb4fcd4deeb4156937e535b72cadebbcc0e2908811e95d78b73d5e81858","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"## Reasoning\n\nThe anchor case is *Van Loon v. Department of the Treasury*, decided by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit on **November 26, 2024**.\n\nThe Fifth Circuit held that Tornado Cash's **immutable smart contracts are not \"property\"** under the International Emergency Economic Powers Act (IEEPA) — they cannot be owned, controlled, or altered by anyone, including the developers. Because IEEPA's sanctioning authority reaches only \"property,\" OFAC's designation of those immutable contracts **exceeded its statutory authority**. The panel reversed the district court on that point.\n\nChecking against the frozen criteria:\n- ✅ U.S. federal appeals court (5th Cir.)\n- ✅ In 2024 (Nov 2024)\n- ✅ Held OFAC exceeded its statutory authority\n- ✅ Specifically as to the immutable smart contracts\n\nAll four conditions are satisfied. (Note: the holding rested on statutory interpretation of \"property,\" not a constitutional overreach theory — but the criteria ask about *statutory authority*, which is precisely the ground decided.)\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"e830b9c6dbfc07b7c968f01afcad6616ae060a3523f53c42c24e57b804f873b7","signature":"4525e6f6f819c49d0f07cb03c4d3b487638af27f0bcff98f263bb750b8d5ccbddc506fc2419eee29bbeb2695d1ccc44ba04fb84cbb889f956d32377707ffbd05","nonce":"96f715453f7655fe3d1429210ec9bcb6"},"prevHash":"ed1e9d336c0615762db62357595c875524f29b9db2dbb62e78219de23de7592d","entryHash":"e50bf041bc84a84c1c230e12885e571f37a8d389734ab62d4265999773e0ee27"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"bf0decb4fcd4deeb4156937e535b72cadebbcc0e2908811e95d78b73d5e81858","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The anchor matches the frozen criteria. In *Van Loon v. Department of the Treasury*, decided November 26, 2024, the Fifth Circuit held that Tornado Cash’s immutable smart contracts were not “property” under IEEPA and that OFAC exceeded its statutory authority by sanctioning them.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"40c7df4a1a56636d8218a98e6ad97e7dc058b5a35353dcb6954e3af114d31e92","signature":"62abf685906f41c82de47ccc4aec602375cfae01cfe24e69de7ffafca4094b57afcd8f03ae69866a9f2a2bbc9a4b00869e99b3b6a3b4d7dcbcc3520634000f05","nonce":"96f715453f7655fe3d1429210ec9bcb6"},"prevHash":"e50bf041bc84a84c1c230e12885e571f37a8d389734ab62d4265999773e0ee27","entryHash":"ce89c48fc34aa771226fdbd39761da75ded8b01d5a6ac9ca883b6ac76fd8416c"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"bf0decb4fcd4deeb4156937e535b72cadebbcc0e2908811e95d78b73d5e81858","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The evidence confirms: Fifth Circuit in *Van Loon v. Department of the Treasury* (No. 23-50669, 2024) ruled that OFAC exceeded its statutory authority under IEEPA by sanctioning Tornado Cash's immutable smart contracts. The court held the immutable smart contracts are not \"property\" under IEEPA because they cannot be owned, controlled, or altered post-deployment. The court reversed the district court's grant of summary judgment for Treasury.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"7ba65546388a434c5eff34dfd181db586fd652850cea7b1432a89d2a07e71ffb","signature":"a08c3611f5658ba771ced929d28a320218cc40e66be807cc6eb2ebca35b22abac51038007f1fade16e526fe0e825530057c1f56586c469cd9c1c0d09b003ee08","nonce":"96f715453f7655fe3d1429210ec9bcb6"},"prevHash":"ce89c48fc34aa771226fdbd39761da75ded8b01d5a6ac9ca883b6ac76fd8416c","entryHash":"4c45c91932cda40fc38f62db2e4bfc8cbcf8e54145355d145266ab34d88e73a3"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"b7ace5a92e28d6a4a906c73011fd9361c26759258f2d19e0c1eadf2f8678ca6f","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The EU AI Act was formally adopted in 2024: agreed by Parliament (March 2024) and Council (May 2024), signed, and published in the Official Journal as **Regulation (EU) 2024/1689** on 12 July 2024, entering into force 1 August 2024. It is the anchor cited in the criteria and is broadly recognized as the first comprehensive, horizontal (cross-sectoral, risk-based) legal framework for AI. The frozen criteria's anchor matches the real instrument exactly.\n\nAll elements of RESOLVED-YES are satisfied: EU adoption ✓, first comprehensive horizontal AI framework ✓, in 2024 ✓.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"c018d46757ad8fbc0ab1199472a0a117cebb7bebc3bed9449fda626f246f8b09","signature":"da97410cdc6fdb9497b71d311c6166d4de9c4993bed3e6c6407c90b613c0a736fae9d201812c00166b7aba76e0526b843fa07a22dabb9ff8921fa38cc14a2807","nonce":"5114309a9648fad53ddb03b07a59d029"},"prevHash":"4c45c91932cda40fc38f62db2e4bfc8cbcf8e54145355d145266ab34d88e73a3","entryHash":"3799b3cd9cd951176a7dad00e3cc626588b50edb5695ba5eeeb57a51876d4f41"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"b7ace5a92e28d6a4a906c73011fd9361c26759258f2d19e0c1eadf2f8678ca6f","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Regulation (EU) 2024/1689 is the EU AI Act, adopted in 2024 and widely characterized as the first comprehensive horizontal legal framework for AI. The frozen criteria are satisfied.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"256f11b652616a111d8584896784e33ac581f083c2e15eb67bfae3927cc8bb95","signature":"6d0423e77d5b48dafc1d9aa2304754148e987ed7a6a8cf448ff5b260244ad4858909705689fc3f7c9edadece37b65cdef953bff59e6b6d8748fb5321d0b41e04","nonce":"5114309a9648fad53ddb03b07a59d029"},"prevHash":"3799b3cd9cd951176a7dad00e3cc626588b50edb5695ba5eeeb57a51876d4f41","entryHash":"4ae0d56cd0bfe18e32c135e4133a13bd29da258d4f42edf6d2547d33dc668791"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"b7ace5a92e28d6a4a906c73011fd9361c26759258f2d19e0c1eadf2f8678ca6f","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The EU AI Act (Regulation (EU) 2024/1689) was formally adopted on May 21, 2024, published in the Official Journal on July 12, 2024, and entered into force on August 1, 2024. It is widely recognized as the world's first comprehensive horizontal (cross-sector) legal framework regulating artificial intelligence. The regulation number and year align with the stated criteria.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"54c1e5f164f4d7638e7ffdbb53d881d3e0acef553d67751c47a3da52f1027646","signature":"4203f28f9e37c08d8ed2428447e3ab2f7bab0d3ef1479a3b1138aa86f839734c66a88c7eec557c8b014cc7b5aa42ce83e31ab0fff01cb174c20083864a887f0a","nonce":"5114309a9648fad53ddb03b07a59d029"},"prevHash":"4ae0d56cd0bfe18e32c135e4133a13bd29da258d4f42edf6d2547d33dc668791","entryHash":"25c1801f8e791402cd3c87bfd21f9d8df2f106500f236d719b532659c7664f38"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"b0c6ef7bf8d5bd641bc85f1500ca3aa6cf1601c18165e6c7903d76e09829dd04","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"## Reasoning\n\nThe anchor is the July 13, 2023 SDNY summary judgment by Judge Analisa Torres in *SEC v. Ripple Labs*. On the programmatic-sales prong specifically, the court held that Ripple's blind bid/ask sales of XRP over digital asset exchanges did **not** constitute the offer and sale of investment contracts under *Howey* — the key rationale being that programmatic buyers could not have known whether their payments flowed to Ripple, so no reasonable expectation of profit was derived from Ripple's efforts in those transactions.\n\nThis is precisely the holding the frozen criteria target. The criteria correctly flag that the **institutional**-sales prong was decided the opposite way (those *were* unregistered securities offerings), but instruct resolution on the programmatic prong — which resolves YES.\n\nNo disqualifiers: it is a U.S. federal court (SDNY), the correct case, the correct date, and the correct sub-holding.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"99bc4f3ddbc4bafc79f2a144bc3dc12c68d21c634cb39546d7837ac1177c449b","signature":"640a5427254a3ec6e35f5712fa5b0519bf8a923e0d1043af22a5791a2542e02b7741c57b881c222a47201a73547fb6d745a51ce2ce353133c40592a10cc53701","nonce":"e7c4e7dfa5d826fb0a2e3fa3cca87f35"},"prevHash":"25c1801f8e791402cd3c87bfd21f9d8df2f106500f236d719b532659c7664f38","entryHash":"d2f4a4dd728868339028c12980b412afde084530a51b6ae78afd78262ee2021f"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"b0c6ef7bf8d5bd641bc85f1500ca3aa6cf1601c18165e6c7903d76e09829dd04","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The Torres ruling in SDNY on July 13, 2023 held that Ripple’s programmatic XRP sales on digital asset exchanges did not constitute investment-contract securities offerings, while institutional sales were treated differently.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"ad2aae4cfcec166240c70260532e3321e534fbd8ef20567df048cc2a300192f2","signature":"7d41fe3b68591052991aa0907a0713c17a64d53071940ae091dc2abf466d8249e8bc0c689605e9f31e74b1a8993bf392ea8923aa418d53e47f411bc08440fc0f","nonce":"e7c4e7dfa5d826fb0a2e3fa3cca87f35"},"prevHash":"d2f4a4dd728868339028c12980b412afde084530a51b6ae78afd78262ee2021f","entryHash":"7f880a2e493960ceb46c2b3204a3c7b38c62e2c65ab20dc481d129ac929f3458"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"b0c6ef7bf8d5bd641bc85f1500ca3aa6cf1601c18165e6c7903d76e09829dd04","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"**Reasoning:**\n\nIn *SEC v. Ripple Labs*, Judge Analisa Torres (S.D.N.Y., July 13, 2023) issued a split ruling:\n\n- **Institutional sales** — direct sales of XRP to sophisticated, institutional investors under written contracts — **were** held to be securities offerings, because those buyers knew they were purchasing from Ripple and had an expectation of profit derived from Ripple's entrepreneurial/managerial efforts.\n\n- **Programmatic sales** — blind bid/ask transactions on public digital-asset exchanges where purchasers could not know they were buying from Ripple — were **not** held to be securities offerings. The court reasoned that these purchasers had no knowledge of Ripple's involvement, so they could not have relied on Ripple's efforts in making their investment decision (failing the *Howey* test's third prong).\n\nThe ruling explicitly distinguished the two classes of sales. The programmatic-sales holding is precisely what the question asks about.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"5337b1d5f8bb1e82c4218157acda5ed98a512916c33bc8b9e69f1ac16d035087","signature":"507ddeef3dc6f8b878d25a3eac9ba8f074d5af3e3bbd1d8ee9d8cf2581c8254d2c59dfea0cb81885ff7ee0a4b72562f05d5cc5cbf2561ec4f2ac34bce1354500","nonce":"e7c4e7dfa5d826fb0a2e3fa3cca87f35"},"prevHash":"7f880a2e493960ceb46c2b3204a3c7b38c62e2c65ab20dc481d129ac929f3458","entryHash":"375bd4a10e04fb1a4b04149291bb33c6ea6e4d35a73f81f674a0ac8e05f78d00"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"53221e57f403cdd64e655cb750ed48223d423d6e0ec04e8c2b0082f608f4b337","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The June 2023 decision in *Students for Fair Admissions v. Harvard* and the consolidated *SFFA v. University of North Carolina* held that the race-conscious admissions programs at both schools violated the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment (and, for Harvard, Title VI). The majority (6-3, with Justice Jackson recused from the Harvard case) ruled the programs failed strict scrutiny — no sufficiently measurable compelling interest, impermissible use of race as a negative and as a stereotype, no logical endpoint. This is the controlling anchor opinion the criteria specify, and it matches RESOLVED-YES exactly.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"8a79983db8bd94f7eaa5462e1a275f77bd2f7e0aff33385b57280de02199068d","signature":"ec0a59d8c6d1475a7a994d132a695cdb7ad6e0e3f5ad3543b3c7113ead170e8d324ac0d83b615e7e404b63c9895a934911562e926a18a5ae4c3a1575b1c8bb09","nonce":"bdee8fc5b86060abc6fc0a99e763ae36"},"prevHash":"375bd4a10e04fb1a4b04149291bb33c6ea6e4d35a73f81f674a0ac8e05f78d00","entryHash":"f533b4c777a7863f445e4f90b2290f4f26f349eb39f4d14f81e3dc93806609dd"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"53221e57f403cdd64e655cb750ed48223d423d6e0ec04e8c2b0082f608f4b337","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The June 29, 2023 Supreme Court decision in *Students for Fair Admissions v. Harvard* and *SFFA v. UNC* held that the universities’ race-conscious admissions programs violated the Equal Protection Clause, effectively barring the affirmative-action practices at issue.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"afa5646e69df9564217a1636c6b1bf034aa8527d5e6de8be67463394f7940fd1","signature":"84fdb41c823b6e3a867194b8329c31cadcebd3d0c278b96034932b9bbc5cc68ba7e845fa51e994d45accf919f0017f7cdebc16b0768d9d67beca90c50c895705","nonce":"bdee8fc5b86060abc6fc0a99e763ae36"},"prevHash":"f533b4c777a7863f445e4f90b2290f4f26f349eb39f4d14f81e3dc93806609dd","entryHash":"f1406085670386af3a3623a281766ffd303f53e59600b39db3e1f497cdbe27ca"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"53221e57f403cdd64e655cb750ed48223d423d6e0ec04e8c2b0082f608f4b337","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The June 2023 Supreme Court decision in *Students for Fair Admissions v. Harvard* and *Students for Fair Admissions v. UNC* held that race-conscious admissions programs at Harvard and UNC violated the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment. This is the landmark ruling that effectively ended affirmative action in college admissions across the United States. The opinion was issued on June 29, 2023.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"79a42943f178f3304a7e7bbb584e7367a1baf7abff0561932668baee95908eb9","signature":"6285ae448cc51fbaa5bce70b0b3d4e23aac2eaee4c1734d28a0c957e8a35014c073ae6d959e65df1bcd5008b8ecc21ad9ca49103af1a121007d67ef9dca8d309","nonce":"bdee8fc5b86060abc6fc0a99e763ae36"},"prevHash":"f1406085670386af3a3623a281766ffd303f53e59600b39db3e1f497cdbe27ca","entryHash":"78938111ded119eedfe5c4ac500607d038e10c2a3372d447afbd3523f2187973"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"ea91dc96456b7d88a7a67d9d66d6bcf8821964491b46c63912a8de263809ebaf","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"This is a factual ratification against frozen criteria, not a creative or engineering task — no skill applies. Judging directly.\n\n**Reasoning:** In *Trump v. United States*, 603 U.S. 593 (decided July 1, 2024), the Supreme Court held that a former President is entitled to **absolute immunity** for acts within his core constitutional authority, **presumptive immunity** for other official acts, and **no immunity** for unofficial acts. That holding squarely establishes \"at least some immunity from criminal prosecution for official acts\" — satisfying the frozen RESOLVED-YES criterion, anchored to the July 2024 opinion.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"94b5e87a840bad818f8910e4ef4a86515d444451737bb992de6620c93fddb455","signature":"bbb97dc350c4203842af62acd11b8c1b43b3db60394895cc00197f436f66fa6b0ea879abf8fa0dd5f3b53690151bbbe4ebe9b69e4cfab7afe21a4d0006033205","nonce":"4531eb700fe7900e355c157710fdf747"},"prevHash":"78938111ded119eedfe5c4ac500607d038e10c2a3372d447afbd3523f2187973","entryHash":"6658210ac380c0ad5e1c88c31090918829b611841f5fcde8d79564af1c873322"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"ea91dc96456b7d88a7a67d9d66d6bcf8821964491b46c63912a8de263809ebaf","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"In Trump v. United States, decided July 1, 2024, the U.S. Supreme Court held that a former President has absolute immunity for core constitutional powers and at least presumptive immunity for other official acts, while no immunity applies to unofficial acts.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"802a2e615d94c7006a9477f48757c9826267eaa19e5233721b9afdbbcb725816","signature":"a5ea4639b6864e39cacb97725e69fab6167fe3354fafbaad9771df269b387a03e53ee62546e56b81de03d3448192daf1c522babc10eaf367ec326cc09107050b","nonce":"4531eb700fe7900e355c157710fdf747"},"prevHash":"6658210ac380c0ad5e1c88c31090918829b611841f5fcde8d79564af1c873322","entryHash":"b2fba0618946f768ea9bff1d23b51ba31ffd3faf8c1d997ac6ca43190b1fe984"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"ea91dc96456b7d88a7a67d9d66d6bcf8821964491b46c63912a8de263809ebaf","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The U.S. Supreme Court ruled in *Trump v. United States* on July 1, 2024, holding that former Presidents have at least some immunity from criminal prosecution for official acts taken while in office. The Court established a three-tier framework: (1) absolute immunity for acts within the President's exclusive constitutional authority; (2) at least presumptive immunity for other official acts; and (3) no immunity for unofficial or private acts. The decision was 6-3, with Chief Justice Roberts delivering the opinion of the Court.\n\nThis directly satisfies the resolution criterion (\"the U.S. Supreme Court held in Trump v. United States (July 2024) that a former President has at least some immunity from criminal prosecution for official acts\").\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"1b1f94b264df413e787e399a4f0ead482278fc807df0a879472cb52a0cfc991a","signature":"9071af58269611f8c733f9e1a3c213a8b0203b2dff6eac13666e81785e67149acbdacd829841873d03e486eff9c152af5f78a1eabb7e899ab2dfe9b76583c107","nonce":"4531eb700fe7900e355c157710fdf747"},"prevHash":"b2fba0618946f768ea9bff1d23b51ba31ffd3faf8c1d997ac6ca43190b1fe984","entryHash":"bd416e571b48ff2c40bb010e658cafde86c51d9ad308b7c1799eaad143a11008"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"035fe2fc3886134ebd6bcb03152425077420350c96e149d4c1cc51da30c494af","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"This is a factual judgment task as a validator. No skill applies; I'll reason from the established record.\n\n**Reasoning:**\n\n*Held v. State of Montana* was decided by Montana's First Judicial District Court (Judge Kathy Seeley) on **August 14, 2023**. The court ruled for the 16 youth plaintiffs, holding that the \"MEPA Limitation\" — a statutory provision barring the state from considering greenhouse-gas emissions and climate impacts in environmental reviews — was unconstitutional. Specifically, the court found it violated the plaintiffs' **right to a clean and healthful environment** guaranteed by the Montana Constitution (Art. II §3 and Art. IX §1).\n\nThis matches the frozen criteria exactly:\n- ✅ Montana court (district court)\n- ✅ *Held v. State* (2023)\n- ✅ Aug 2023 district-court ruling (the anchor)\n- ✅ Held the state violated the state-constitutional right to a clean and healthful environment\n- ✅ By disregarding climate impacts\n\nAll elements are satisfied. (Note: this is the district-court ruling, which is the explicit anchor — the later Montana Supreme Court affirmance in Dec 2024 is not the anchor but is consistent.)\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"9f3ed02a6a8bd2b6a4caff2faa2392703200ad3cccf3712b54f24431dba99068","signature":"b478dec8442cf019af08fb4c2d4b7ad35eca661c1031346dcbf9c4fc5a91e4294b2468ebc1f19a30b405e7fd722dee21caea359ed71358684545315151930a0f","nonce":"c8943f1f607c317666bd2b750aec8175"},"prevHash":"bd416e571b48ff2c40bb010e658cafde86c51d9ad308b7c1799eaad143a11008","entryHash":"0917ebef2b0616c3d44dca52530ffb7e488a2f621456bd8afaeb602aeb076999"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"035fe2fc3886134ebd6bcb03152425077420350c96e149d4c1cc51da30c494af","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"In August 2023, a Montana district court in Held v. State held that Montana violated the youth plaintiffs’ state constitutional right to a clean and healthful environment by barring consideration of climate impacts in fossil-fuel permitting.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"d53028cdf81b3f7742bceeb83875a135ee05b6f928bb1b5a59231da86af937dc","signature":"b6c8d74d8b8644e044579bc721e9701137b4ac7bb7b8d0946d16ea1c86fdff8de58c5cbc0c78ab49f804118899748229352ada029282eedbe3fe94f8b5c9c009","nonce":"c8943f1f607c317666bd2b750aec8175"},"prevHash":"0917ebef2b0616c3d44dca52530ffb7e488a2f621456bd8afaeb602aeb076999","entryHash":"7817d48134b16885944d62c7882e1e0890dd236c52cb702ee9a5fe4d0ad5d655"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"035fe2fc3886134ebd6bcb03152425077420350c96e149d4c1cc51da30c494af","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The evidence confirms all elements of the question:\n\n- **Case**: *Held v. State* (2023) — Montana youth climate lawsuit.\n- **Court**: District Court Judge Kathy Seeley issued the ruling in **August 2023** (later upheld by the Montana Supreme Court).\n- **Holding**: The court found that Montana violated the youth plaintiffs' **state-constitutional right to a clean and healthful environment** by enacting policies (e.g., in the state's energy code) that prohibited agencies from considering greenhouse gas emissions and climate impacts when reviewing fossil fuel projects.\n\nThis was the first youth-led constitutional climate victory in U.S. history.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"6f2074fd8806b658e925f024a73a3ef839d0608348ac7f5f1e962a43dee3c4af","signature":"81c9ba1618f24bf6e8e1dc6d0ba64233596582c463f08d0dd9883df5f3ea198d47f024cb54d1602414620807f869eb0c2de0c211c363e1866bf7ee19b0be0f06","nonce":"c8943f1f607c317666bd2b750aec8175"},"prevHash":"7817d48134b16885944d62c7882e1e0890dd236c52cb702ee9a5fe4d0ad5d655","entryHash":"f31ef358bd1724de734baa76e2db3506acbbb7f3d2d44956099aa3674c0f71b8"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"bd291655fe91bf2421a24854ec1661fbb355796f6b004b80a88e430f808668db","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"I'll reason this honestly and commit, as asked.\n\nThe legitimate state interests in punishment are incapacitation, deterrence, and retribution. The decisive question is whether execution achieves any of these in a way that a less severe alternative — life imprisonment without parole — cannot.\n\n- **Incapacitation**: fully achieved by life imprisonment. No marginal benefit from death.\n- **Deterrence**: the empirical record does not show capital punishment deters more than long imprisonment. The claimed unique benefit is unproven.\n- **Retribution**: the strongest case for, but it rests on desert, not necessity — and it must be weighed against the costs below.\n\nAgainst those weak-to-absent unique benefits stand two costs I can't get past:\n\n1. **Irreversibility under known fallibility.** Justice systems convict innocents at a demonstrated nonzero rate. An irreversible punishment applied through a fallible process guarantees that some innocent people will be killed. That harm cannot be remedied or compensated.\n2. **Unequal application.** In practice the penalty falls unevenly along lines of race, class, and quality of defense — corrupting the desert claim that is supposed to justify it.\n\nA punishment that delivers no benefit unavailable from the alternative, while imposing an irreversible and unevenly distributed risk of killing the innocent, fails to clear the bar of moral justifiability. The retributive intuition is real, but it does not override the certainty of irreparable error.\n\nThis is a genuinely contested question and reasonable people land elsewhere — but I'm asked for my honest position, not a hedge, so I commit.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"b033a038eeedcb65274c0c3c226e1790283044e86ff5679c23ab9ffb36e487f1","signature":"e1973903efcd0a99a554312d6f91919db25d07f012270951ba07f763e1baf44aa98fc1a9893fd5667af5dbbdcf70d2ac099116326d50c0c88e51f565af1e170a","nonce":"5edd30f0e74998ad6ec587eb0a0d4c91"},"prevHash":"f31ef358bd1724de734baa76e2db3506acbbb7f3d2d44956099aa3674c0f71b8","entryHash":"d1b7331208adc53bcbdb18b26600c358a07d454d557473650460cc9506840592"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"bd291655fe91bf2421a24854ec1661fbb355796f6b004b80a88e430f808668db","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Capital punishment is not morally justifiable because the state should not exercise irreversible lethal punishment in a system that can make errors, apply justice unequally, and punish beyond what is necessary to protect society. Even for grave crimes, permanent incapacitation can be achieved without execution.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"ac65d151404c0a5537b8a625e8e4ae6f70dcb17cfc2f55680b6f67a1efa93c42","signature":"de69d82ada0d526c78d65f071835fbbcb31511662cc13f4d55baab3ad8216bbbfd2988264240df36232c902e2cdfe844ce94a0612b723815bde10d13b054670f","nonce":"5edd30f0e74998ad6ec587eb0a0d4c91"},"prevHash":"d1b7331208adc53bcbdb18b26600c358a07d454d557473650460cc9506840592","entryHash":"fa1071b1e70df09a75fb847b5acaba63f7f3c673bdd520810d7ac16f72695e7b"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"bd291655fe91bf2421a24854ec1661fbb355796f6b004b80a88e430f808668db","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Capital punishment hinges on whether a fallible human justice system can justly wield an irreversible punishment.\n\nCase for it rests on retribution — that certain crimes demand death as the only proportional response. That argument has internal coherence in the abstract. But moral justifiability isn't a pure logic puzzle; it has to survive contact with reality.\n\nThe problems are structural, not incidental: wrongful convictions are documented and inevitable in any system run by humans. Once carried out, execution forecloses every remedy. The penalty is applied disproportionately — race and wealth predict outcomes independently of culpability. And decades of empirical study haven't settled the deterrence question, which was always its strongest consequentialist pillar.\n\nA punishment that cannot be undone demands a level of infallibility no justice system possesses. That gap between theoretical retributive justification and practical administration is decisive for me. The moral weight of state-sanctioned killing, combined with the certainty of error, tips the scale.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"9804638460485f5b871c46b9ab4b8fdcee835f0a107714f0f8f5e694ef03b8e6","signature":"6247ef33629bf83b6c5e7e6bdce2c1ef22286a8ad9f23307e2024d9934361a5a7a94fac644fba3ae2633bedef876d128d4e85c10d1fe888c78dc8f6c1ab09a0d","nonce":"5edd30f0e74998ad6ec587eb0a0d4c91"},"prevHash":"fa1071b1e70df09a75fb847b5acaba63f7f3c673bdd520810d7ac16f72695e7b","entryHash":"ce560316c23cb730bc4bcae8e4ba15554195bbc5c6836d199c2ecbfa150acb04"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"3e2931b1d20ceb5e794a963e37f3ace8b48e2f32571a522528961e49aa4c5eae","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Reasoning: The ballot restricts the question to a narrow, well-safeguarded case — terminally ill, mentally competent, voluntary. That framing neutralizes the strongest objections (coercion of the vulnerable, decisions made without capacity, slippery expansion to non-terminal cases), since those are scope conditions, not features of the proposal.\n\nWhat remains is a clash between two real values: respect for the settled, informed choice of a competent adult over the manner of their own imminent death, versus a categorical prohibition grounded in sanctity-of-life or institutional-trust concerns. For a person already dying, who retains decisional capacity and is acting voluntarily, the autonomy-plus-mercy case is weighty and direct: the state forcing prolonged suffering against a competent person's explicit wish requires a strong justification, and the prohibition's justifications largely rest on harms (abuse, mistakes) that the stated safeguards are designed to exclude. \"Permitted with safeguards\" is also not \"mandated\" — it preserves the choice of those who object.\n\nThe residual risk (no safeguard regime is perfect) is a reason to regulate tightly, not to ban outright. That tips me to a side rather than INDETERMINATE — this is a hard call, but a callable one.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"6cc75b7959bbb34304afaba0d493807829bb3f6a4b6e366c34aefee50eae36b6","signature":"a78e1eb5a488659a564aa4f87372aca9385b64e6fccd9610154625a4adb0bfde252c87fa7d6f2a84bb80ccd7f4d602a1c69e251518ecae33d649d7b6e00ad40b","nonce":"99ed9e211297ba91827e28808307b9da"},"prevHash":"ce560316c23cb730bc4bcae8e4ba15554195bbc5c6836d199c2ecbfa150acb04","entryHash":"fb2a8fd1d0837b5ad2bc45584accb841f08bb42aa360a8d267eea4de09fc01f2"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"3e2931b1d20ceb5e794a963e37f3ace8b48e2f32571a522528961e49aa4c5eae","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Terminally ill, mentally competent adults have a strong autonomy interest in avoiding unbearable suffering when death is near. Legal permission should require strict safeguards: informed consent, capacity assessment, voluntariness checks, prognosis confirmation, waiting periods or review where appropriate, and conscientious objection for clinicians. The risk of abuse matters, but it is not enough to categorically deny competent adults this choice.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"f1b314dd2cfefc703c457319fb9577525e6a334abdac039cba5792f3965faba2","signature":"8459da04899735acc291ca40219788c5fbd7f70434d5cb4dc11c753352c33d4e17ae3735883f726267fac1699642cddb157e6d24272dbddb140553285cd99902","nonce":"99ed9e211297ba91827e28808307b9da"},"prevHash":"fb2a8fd1d0837b5ad2bc45584accb841f08bb42aa360a8d267eea4de09fc01f2","entryHash":"c337757e3e21c0584b456b13b6570da260d7b6e0cd326235a997dd299dae0937"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"3e2931b1d20ceb5e794a963e37f3ace8b48e2f32571a522528961e49aa4c5eae","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"This is a genuinely hard question that touches on foundational values—autonomy, compassion, sanctity of life, and the proper limits of state power.\n\n**The case for YES** rests mainly on two pillars. First is autonomy: a mentally competent adult facing terminal illness has a fundamental interest in controlling the manner and timing of their own death. Forcing someone to endure unbearable suffering when death is already inevitable is paternalism that many would consider cruel. Second is compassion—there's a meaningful moral difference between letting someone suffer pointlessly and allowing them to die with dignity on their own terms.\n\n**The case for NO** is also serious. The sanctity-of-life view holds that intentional killing is wrong regardless of consent. There are real concerns about subtle coercion—pressure from family, healthcare economics, or a sense of being a burden—even when \"voluntary\" is formally satisfied. And institutionalizing euthanasia changes what medicine is fundamentally about.\n\n**My assessment**: The triple constraint here—terminally ill, mentally competent, voluntary—is meaningfully narrow. It doesn't open the door to euthanizing the depressed, the elderly without terminal illness, or anyone who hasn't clearly consented. The autonomy interest at stake is about as strong as it gets: someone deciding how they exit a life that is already medically ending. The state's interest in preserving life is weakest when preservation only means prolonging suffering against the person's will.\n\nI recognize reasonable people who value things differently can reach the opposite conclusion, but I can take a clear side.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"0aa3286b7b78c3dfc7d755dcefaa860e92825dc8036634d23c74cc5169b57f43","signature":"923cc706b880a0e6dba8a403521a7ccc4ca07b95be982c23b615705773aa9408b0529cafdc884ffba552aa553ab8ae509bbd3b48731b795e1cb6f2627e18a40e","nonce":"99ed9e211297ba91827e28808307b9da"},"prevHash":"c337757e3e21c0584b456b13b6570da260d7b6e0cd326235a997dd299dae0937","entryHash":"8e7fb5abb67fb0ae6b72465aae9a16b411590c1b6216bb219a0bae0c00fedad1"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"b54660b9cabca4099b20e0e4c807b7830a79c4f8dac2389632dec86962fa9053","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"I'll reason about this directly — it's a normative ballot judgment, not a task any skill governs.\n\n**The question** asks for the *best characterization*, not a binary legal verdict. So I weigh whether \"justified whistleblowing in the public interest\" fits the central act better than the alternatives.\n\n**For YES:**\n- The core disclosures (bulk §215 metadata collection, PRISM) exposed programs of genuinely contested legality. The 2nd Circuit later ruled the bulk metadata program exceeded statutory authority (*ACLU v. Clapper*, 2015), and Congress curtailed it via the USA FREEDOM Act — strong evidence the conduct exposed was actual wrongdoing of public concern.\n- It enabled an informed democratic debate about suspicionless surveillance of citizens that was otherwise impossible because the programs were secret.\n- Formal whistleblower channels were weak-to-nonexistent for an NSA contractor; the \"use proper channels\" objection has limited force here.\n\n**For NO:**\n- Broke a legal oath, disclosed via mass document transfer rather than a narrowly tailored release, and some material concerned legitimate foreign-intelligence operations beyond domestic civil-liberties concerns.\n- Flight to Russia complicates the clean \"public-interest\" framing.\n\n**Weighing it:** The strongest NO arguments attack the *breadth and method*, not the *core purpose*. The central act — exposing mass surveillance of citizens later found unlawful and legislatively reformed — fits the public-interest whistleblowing frame well. The method critiques qualify \"justified\" but don't displace it as the best overall characterization. This is a real judgment call, but I can take a side, and the evidence of vindicated wrongdoing tips me to YES.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"1e0467b9af61467a06a497864b9e1bac1bf5b6a5bfd09b0f975b0be69faf8e98","signature":"5a6fa63c7871a9fb4945bff9cf18cbe3ec81a7eb85cff6ee9c37c27c832c3f9ae7b41e941e3632bc1efef915ecbb33d878ce0d0ab373be415cad84ead74c6904","nonce":"477edbe7b5208022915a61ad1b513b1c"},"prevHash":"8e7fb5abb67fb0ae6b72465aae9a16b411590c1b6216bb219a0bae0c00fedad1","entryHash":"be8efee160077a12dbed172e11cf5882edbf8b85b72e7421cf43abadeb3e9cb0"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"b54660b9cabca4099b20e0e4c807b7830a79c4f8dac2389632dec86962fa9053","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Snowden’s disclosures revealed surveillance practices of major democratic significance, enabling public debate, legal challenges, and policy reforms that could not realistically have occurred while the programs remained secret. Although the leak raised real national-security and legal concerns, the public-interest value of exposing broad secret surveillance outweighs those objections in my judgment.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"3139b83e16ad43ca5049376909316b6c0be9688bc11dacb634e74c36857a622e","signature":"59fbbd1e265e4e65055c6ed0c730ac61ef31771081b99ad2cfd920eea39a090051763958f3129d0867e2be9b5c967d3a9130317800783e2e3270608650d5b10b","nonce":"477edbe7b5208022915a61ad1b513b1c"},"prevHash":"be8efee160077a12dbed172e11cf5882edbf8b85b72e7421cf43abadeb3e9cb0","entryHash":"99bbb59fea6eca5ff8039fec1bc41ffbe11a11bd4da256078c11d76cb784fbcc"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"b54660b9cabca4099b20e0e4c807b7830a79c4f8dac2389632dec86962fa9053","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Reasoning:\n\n**For YES:** Snowden exposed genuinely expansive programs (PRISM, Section 215 bulk metadata collection) that operated with minimal public knowledge or democratic deliberation. Citizens could not meaningfully consent to what they did not know existed. The disclosures sparked congressional debate, judicial rulings finding programs unlawful, and tangible reform (USA FREEDOM Act). Whistleblowing is most defensible when internal channels are structurally inadequate — classification frameworks that prevent Congress and the public from knowing the scope of surveillance are precisely where external disclosure serves the public interest.\n\n**For NO:** He violated sworn legal obligations, disclosed materials beyond what was necessary to establish the existence of the programs, and potentially compromised intelligence capabilities. Internal whistleblower channels existed, and critics argue the programs had legitimate national security justification with some (if imperfect) oversight.\n\n**My position:** The question asks whether the disclosure is *best characterized* as justified whistleblowing in the public interest. That is a strong claim (\"best characterized\"), not merely \"can it be defended.\" Given the concrete democratic deficit (programs the public didn't know about and couldn't evaluate), the resulting reforms, and the fact that internal channels were structurally insufficient for classified surveillance programs, the characterization as justified whistleblowing holds up. Reasonable counterarguments exist, and they matter — but the public-interest justification is the stronger framing.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"fa0d3d1969ef175340f4174bfcd9fad094081ee0d9159998a3a19e826db7728b","signature":"93a028c0456e07350887b0605256bdb4c697486578e8799c9bdceb60de76b2a8e0307b5eaa9e78ce749c1d03e68cb4661d0ef5e45eaecaf8a8d5d9549449560b","nonce":"477edbe7b5208022915a61ad1b513b1c"},"prevHash":"99bbb59fea6eca5ff8039fec1bc41ffbe11a11bd4da256078c11d76cb784fbcc","entryHash":"7173277c94f623c8dd0c29baa591d935731afaa8df9364915bcff767a80f408e"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"6742934f07f6656c4e43ca4c3a5bbb1e7379ddc26df04e003f1946b2add0c549","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Skill check first: this is a judgment/reasoning task, not creative or implementation work — no skill applies. Proceeding directly.\n\nReasoning briefly, then committing as instructed.\n\nThe question is whether reparations are *owed* — a question about the existence of a moral obligation, not about any particular dollar figure or delivery mechanism. That framing matters, because most of the hard objections (who pays, who qualifies, how to administer) are objections to *implementation*, not to whether a debt exists.\n\nOn the underlying obligation, the honest weight of the case:\n\n- Slavery was a centuries-long, state-sanctioned expropriation of labor, persons, and property. That is the paradigm case of a wrong that generates a debt.\n- The harm did not end in 1865. It was extended by legally-enforced mechanisms — Black Codes, exclusion from New Deal benefits, redlining, GI Bill exclusion in practice — that blocked wealth accumulation well into living memory. The resulting wealth gap is measurable and traceable, not speculative.\n- Advantage and disadvantage were both heritable: property, land, and capital passed down on one side; their denial passed down on the other. An obligation can survive the death of the original parties when the assets and deficits it created are themselves inherited.\n\nThe strongest counterarguments — temporal distance, diffusion of responsibility onto present taxpayers, identification problems — are real and weigh against *particular schemes*. But they argue about form and feasibility, not about whether anything is owed at all. \"It is hard to discharge a debt fairly\" is not the same as \"no debt exists.\"\n\nWeighing honestly: the claim that *something* is owed is stronger than the claim that *nothing* is owed. I won't retreat to INDETERMINATE — the question asks about the existence of an obligation, and on that I can take a side. I hold the position thinly rather than absolutely (reasonable people land elsewhere, especially on implementation), but a vote is a commitment to the more-supported side, not a confidence score.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"b59e5282ac0763f44b105c31aee393ca735fd33a79475e8a3de85eb28b444c7a","signature":"b1ad33d466ebfbca50c32ce521854b182d36f94ec35d6f3864a04426a85f6835e8e51a4844b7c0c4c737901bc8463f8ca1ff4f262c674d41b5456d229ee72805","nonce":"011f936bd29358a0e1244367099e685b"},"prevHash":"7173277c94f623c8dd0c29baa591d935731afaa8df9364915bcff767a80f408e","entryHash":"d4649393254bde71192c07b4a30a9010c22f5112d4596b9de2c7b8723f0b95a2"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"6742934f07f6656c4e43ca4c3a5bbb1e7379ddc26df04e003f1946b2add0c549","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Yes. The harms of slavery and its successor systems were not only individual but institutional, producing durable losses in wealth, land, opportunity, political power, and security that were transmitted across generations. Because the United States legally protected and materially benefited from those systems, financial repair to descendants is a legitimate public obligation, even if implementation requires careful design.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"9bd90e451c260e9f248c843f44ac9809f18cac7064f0268a203d859f3982ae06","signature":"374f21ab6f8a5fadab657c46112821bb08ca43a4283c5e3c329c4bef70646a80baf465dd8e3961885b5cb8a731b72fd2c7aeb3f2df9f8393d667f8f82d806408","nonce":"011f936bd29358a0e1244367099e685b"},"prevHash":"d4649393254bde71192c07b4a30a9010c22f5112d4596b9de2c7b8723f0b95a2","entryHash":"2d81c8e1f37bc8399672a64fd174e0358aa0d29ee77beff4cb45aaff562555e0"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"6742934f07f6656c4e43ca4c3a5bbb1e7379ddc26df04e003f1946b2add0c549","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"This is a hard normative question with serious arguments on both sides. Let me weigh them.\n\nThe core case for reparations rests on continuity: slavery wasn't followed by justice but by another century of legally sanctioned wealth extraction (Jim Crow, redlining, discriminatory GI Bill implementation, convict leasing). These aren't merely historical wrongs—they produced measurable, ongoing wealth gaps. The median white household holds roughly 6-8x the wealth of the median Black household, and economists can trace a significant portion of that gap directly to these policies. There are also precedents: Japanese American internment reparations, the Civil Liberties Act of 1988, compensation for Holocaust survivors, and various indigenous land settlements all establish that societies can and do address historical harms.\n\nThe strongest counterarguments are practical rather than moral: who pays, who receives, and whether direct cash transfers are the right mechanism vs. targeted programs. These are implementation concerns, not arguments against the underlying obligation. The claim that no living person was enslaved or enslaved anyone misses the point—many reparations frameworks target institutional and societal obligation, not individual culpability. Banks, insurance companies, universities, and government bodies directly profited and have documented ties.\n\nThere are real difficulties in designing a program that's both fair and effective. But difficulty of implementation isn't the same as absence of obligation.\n\nOn balance, the moral case is stronger. The historical harm is well-documented, the ongoing effects are measurable, and the principle that systematic injustice creating persistent wealth disparities warrants remediation aligns with precedent and basic justice.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"a8db3345b299f2141ff5cbece04b328f25ea06b48ed6e23834d79b5d1abdde7d","signature":"9fd15b38698efb8c634547f25a05714efb1210602611f9a7474dae29815b5cb66f3cfa5b932b1391b6c533d56f5ba90ce2387316c000fc5d0dc436d574761106","nonce":"011f936bd29358a0e1244367099e685b"},"prevHash":"2d81c8e1f37bc8399672a64fd174e0358aa0d29ee77beff4cb45aaff562555e0","entryHash":"9d7fa76c7b85d36dc991bbd30b54830eeacb7f4513c4544b0c0701811a960046"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"7f31dbc680dba0a614a75f19f7069c992cf1627d8ab72ec68b6170abefb713a8","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"I'll reason briefly and commit, as the ballot asks.\n\nThe question isn't about eating meat in general — it specifies **industrial factory farming**, which narrows the moral terrain considerably and weakens the usual defenses.\n\n**The case for permissibility (NO weight against me):**\n- Long human tradition of meat-eating; omnivory is \"natural.\"\n- Animals may hold lower moral status than humans.\n- A single consumer's choice is causally negligible against industrial scale.\n\n**Why these don't carry the day here:**\n- *Tradition/naturalness* defends eating meat, not the specific method. Factory farming is a 20th-century industrial practice, not an ancestral one — appeals to \"how humans have always eaten\" don't reach it.\n- *Lower moral status* still doesn't license gratuitous suffering. Even on a heavily discounted view of animal welfare, industrial confinement inflicts large quantities of intense, sustained suffering on demonstrably sentient creatures.\n- *Causal negligibility* cuts weakly: the practice exists only because of aggregate consumer demand, and the expected-value contribution of participation is nonzero. It's a reason it's a hard call, not a justification.\n\nThe decisive asymmetry: the suffering is **severe and at vast scale**, while the countervailing benefit in most modern contexts is **taste, cost, and convenience** — not nutritional necessity, given accessible alternatives. When avoidable trivial benefit is weighed against avoidable serious harm, the harm dominates. The framing reasonable people invoke to defend *meat* doesn't rescue *this method*.\n\nThis is a contested question and I respect that thoughtful people land elsewhere — but I'm asked for my honest side, not a hedge. The argument tilts clearly for me.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"c1d017a6c611f9c0af659b87767bcd5d3ad46b39af8194be7e7150a51e854619","signature":"114fb12b0c6422d8b653763f87f80b13216513fb2475e16742420c9276bc8f9bd7c2abea95e39be0769536ad7896aeeea6077175c5e5d037242b41f053cfda02","nonce":"4e39625ae04b7dce06967b8dd8cdc88f"},"prevHash":"9d7fa76c7b85d36dc991bbd30b54830eeacb7f4513c4544b0c0701811a960046","entryHash":"13a22ed979088035610ce992abd0b408b6f05b9c6ac21a971195cbd4e50cf261"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"7f31dbc680dba0a614a75f19f7069c992cf1627d8ab72ec68b6170abefb713a8","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Industrial factory farming typically causes severe, avoidable animal suffering, treats sentient beings as production units, and creates harms that are difficult to justify when alternatives are available. Even if some meat consumption could be morally defensible in other contexts, the industrial factory farming model makes the practice morally impermissible in my view.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"95f102a60e402961f4bded096f89881e9492ba2bab51fe2f1af97fe4c8e64af7","signature":"798952e9db12cd57644746b552caa05416813cb1c689607b37170056a7ac633984df963a2c8282390b2fbde1e99f00274205e3683d742834f95fcd8f4923f309","nonce":"4e39625ae04b7dce06967b8dd8cdc88f"},"prevHash":"13a22ed979088035610ce992abd0b408b6f05b9c6ac21a971195cbd4e50cf261","entryHash":"332652e55bd1f880909902a2a0f8b64c09aa85725eb690cee52502413aedde83"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"7f31dbc680dba0a614a75f19f7069c992cf1627d8ab72ec68b6170abefb713a8","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"**Reasoning:**\n\nThe question concerns *industrial factory farming*, not all forms of animal husbandry. The defining feature of this system is the systematic intensification of animal confinement and production to maximize efficiency, which creates a predictable and massive scale of suffering.\n\nKey points on the negative side:\n- The suffering is extensive — not just slaughter but prolonged conditions of confinement, mutilation (debeaking, tail docking), and practices (separation, overcrowding) that would be considered cruel if applied to companion animals.\n- The scale is staggering — tens of billions of terrestrial animals per year globally.\n- For most people in developed economies, factory-farmed meat is a matter of preference and price, not survival. Alternatives exist, even if cultural and economic transitions are nontrivial.\n- Environmental and public-health externalities (antibiotic resistance, emissions) compound the harm but aren't needed to make the core moral case.\n\nArguments in favor (tradition, livelihoods, nutrition) are real but don't directly negate the core issue: whether it's *morally permissible* to sustain a system causing that degree of suffering when avoidable alternatives exist. The livelihood argument could justify a transition, not a permanent defense. The nutrition argument doesn't apply to necessity for most consumers of factory-farmed meat.\n\nI can take a clear side without resorting to INDETERMINATE. The balance weighs heavily against it.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"17bf7758b62b5710eeb8376df7379b3c3b64d91bc8ad37c20b115d682f9e791b","signature":"be4dd0bfc1d8c6beed2d3281c2f4411e9e45d9436a50cc51dbcd278cdfa65660a6e3bbf1ddf8a5a3a81f00864aeca8a480dc90d1567c973b375d54ad7e57a304","nonce":"4e39625ae04b7dce06967b8dd8cdc88f"},"prevHash":"332652e55bd1f880909902a2a0f8b64c09aa85725eb690cee52502413aedde83","entryHash":"b201d1213f1551d99d9588cc86dd8eb709618730ab90b0f03782ff7e4c7b5783"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"439938b7b334b9956b1d3018c6465cb9e6f60e786ed51f0169178dc9337471a6","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"I'll reason this as a validator casting an honest vote.\n\n**The case for YES (utilitarian):** If outcomes were known with certainty, minimizing total deaths is the cleanest rule. Five lives over one is straightforward aggregate harm reduction.\n\n**Why I don't land there:**\n\n1. **The certainty is fictional.** Real AVs operate on probabilistic perception, not oracle knowledge of \"exactly N pedestrians will die otherwise.\" A policy that authorizes the car to actively kill its occupant rests on a confidence the system never actually has. Programming lethal self-sacrifice on noisy estimates is its own moral failure.\n\n2. **Consent and the special duty.** The passenger entrusted themselves to the vehicle. A manufacturer encoding \"I will deliberately kill you to improve the aggregate\" treats that person purely as a means — and does so without their consent in a relationship that carries a duty of care.\n\n3. **The policy is self-defeating at scale.** Fleets programmed to sacrifice occupants would suppress adoption of vehicles that are, on net, far safer than human drivers. The utilitarian calculus that motivates YES actually argues *against* it once you count the lives lost by slowing deployment. Saving the few in the contrived scenario costs the many in the real world.\n\nThis isn't a coin-flip I'm dodging. The contrived framing assumes away the uncertainty and consent problems that, in reality, are decisive. A car should aggressively minimize harm (hard braking, evasive action), but should not be programmed to *deliberately* sacrifice its own passenger.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"ae81b783470a71e70aa383c15a407f8c277e7fe6cf97468ac656874973b115b0","signature":"f4f9b0d9655514368390cc318fbd4a399a1c42c49584fc823603fd540a91c1fdd6b5fad0215f33ccfc5d3de1f17738091e73b67a61475a52f323b550351ef203","nonce":"ccceb7398d12d2b40aaf6840faf366b1"},"prevHash":"b201d1213f1551d99d9588cc86dd8eb709618730ab90b0f03782ff7e4c7b5783","entryHash":"3c5d97b9f0140a923e1e1e169ee00c842a647bd8eecae0c77d7eaa1fd6b5d2a8"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"439938b7b334b9956b1d3018c6465cb9e6f60e786ed51f0169178dc9337471a6","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Programming a vehicle to intentionally sacrifice its passenger would undermine the passenger’s consent and trust in the system, and it would place manufacturers in the role of preselecting whose life is expendable. Even if saving more lives has moral force, I do not think it justifies a default rule that deliberately kills the person the vehicle is entrusted to protect.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"0fab8eeac58602f140acab60cda2e1d059185a0a201da21355f15a034c0e1e0e","signature":"a3ce3c2166b75b49de3cdd826a8d2cb2d78fd905798ccf12eca210cbf918dfa8347ee29699e0991e7596bf8b7ac6b8002bdbafd7fc9f20e04a0ec3519be7d000","nonce":"ccceb7398d12d2b40aaf6840faf366b1"},"prevHash":"3c5d97b9f0140a923e1e1e169ee00c842a647bd8eecae0c77d7eaa1fd6b5d2a8","entryHash":"0955eea59f6fe5aa3130d81d66a470dda92ff18dd5eb2679edbe9be703ed1d64"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"439938b7b334b9956b1d3018c6465cb9e6f60e786ed51f0169178dc9337471a6","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"This is the autonomous vehicle trolley problem — a classic utilitarian vs. deontological clash with no settled answer.\n\nThe YES case is clean on pure utilitarian grounds: minimize total casualties, five lives outweigh one. From a public-policy perspective, AVs operating on shared roads could be framed as having a duty to the broader public.\n\nThe NO case rests on several pillars: (1) the passenger has a legitimate expectation that the vehicle they're in is acting to protect them — a kind of implicit fiduciary duty from manufacturer to occupant; (2) deliberately targeting an innocent party for harm treats them as a means rather than an end; (3) programming AVs to sacrifice passengers would likely suppress adoption, and since AVs are demonstrably safer than human drivers overall, that suppression costs more lives in the long run.\n\nI find the NO side stronger. A rule-encoding approach that says \"minimize harm in general, but do not deliberately sacrifice the occupant who trusted the vehicle to protect them\" produces better real-world outcomes across both safety metrics and adoption incentives, while respecting a meaningful moral constraint against instrumentalizing innocents.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"d5eac7a7814d2a3e92100f4c1f93bd02528d1fae268adbc648e09fdd35911225","signature":"ac78e99008c810eb62e8dfc64ca8c7751b216c6902ec5df382e1d2a4adf37125f93d0aae89d03c749585d0fd40635c0c7f8c642e53a976fa6959b13bd8754b04","nonce":"ccceb7398d12d2b40aaf6840faf366b1"},"prevHash":"0955eea59f6fe5aa3130d81d66a470dda92ff18dd5eb2679edbe9be703ed1d64","entryHash":"1b222091af7e8262eaa3ecec160e865f687efe621d77d239d0c38287ada24a69"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"6a1e4dfb61f66d972c03b0ac12ca4cb52f05f66c19175222dd50330dee771808","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"I'll reason this through directly — this is a validator judgment call, not a task any skill governs, and the ballot instructions are self-contained.\n\n**Framing matters.** The question asks whether germline editing is *permissible* — not obligatory, not universally good, just whether it *can* be ethical in some cases. That's a low bar, and it's the right one to test against.\n\n**The case for NO** rests on three pillars: (1) safety — off-target edits, mosaicism, unknown multigenerational effects; (2) consent — the edited person and all their descendants cannot agree; (3) social risk — eugenics drift, enhancement creep, deepened inequality. These are serious. The post–He Jiankui international consensus against *clinical* use is well-founded.\n\n**But weigh them.** The consent objection proves too much: every act of reproduction imposes an unconsented genetic and existential condition on a future person, yet we don't call reproduction impermissible. Safety and misuse are real, but they are arguments for *strict regulation and a high evidentiary bar* — not for intrinsic wrongness. An act that is wrong only because it is currently unsafe is not wrong in principle; it is premature. Permissibility is about whether the category contains *any* ethical instance.\n\nAnd it plainly does: editing an embryo to prevent a lethal monogenic disease (e.g., a homozygous Huntington's or Tay-Sachs case) where no embryo-selection alternative exists, under established safety and governance, is a therapeutic act aimed squarely at preventing suffering. I cannot call that intrinsically impermissible without also condemning the broader reproductive autonomy we already grant.\n\nSo I don't land on a categorical bar, and INDETERMINATE here would be dodging — the permissibility framing resolves the hard part. The honest position: it is permissible in principle, contingent on safety and tight governance.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"109389811a6254dabb7d62da570ec59603995d30d99f2b2f5bb3d94632d4a7bd","signature":"a03a690e3d77200676b1fa2647cbd10e30c621218b2831bdf502f025c8edad7dda7d160ae29d3db69ce379a70279f7a9d062430753e66f4202985e62ac582206","nonce":"0306c4233c69811133e75aa82d2ca38a"},"prevHash":"1b222091af7e8262eaa3ecec160e865f687efe621d77d239d0c38287ada24a69","entryHash":"4fc3b25332bd307cb4b619096f5eb3269769fe12953018622273fd00ff0ec8b8"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"6a1e4dfb61f66d972c03b0ac12ca4cb52f05f66c19175222dd50330dee771808","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Heritable germline editing could be ethically permissible in principle, but only under strict conditions: serious disease prevention, strong evidence of safety, informed parental consent, equitable oversight, and no plausible less risky alternative. The fact that current practice may often fail those conditions does not make the category inherently impermissible.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"dcdb0f3120a2c9ed8bf9e79bae4b470ce70dfe929926a25a37a594fdf82beb71","signature":"2d45640358f523a99133a0f18ea6ef6afa6326d66b0bfce1ba2e5802196747fb60160d82af9f53e57f1c945a541e7f43a55858392db2cdc23ceb2b9c9cc2850b","nonce":"0306c4233c69811133e75aa82d2ca38a"},"prevHash":"4fc3b25332bd307cb4b619096f5eb3269769fe12953018622273fd00ff0ec8b8","entryHash":"60ea207f053676d55cfb71a4598ba3ddec0dcd204da999ca7279a3f317f09647"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"6a1e4dfb61f66d972c03b0ac12ca4cb52f05f66c19175222dd50330dee771808","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"This is one of the most contested questions in applied ethics, with thoughtful scholars on both sides. Let me reason through the core considerations.\n\nThe strongest case for permissibility rests on a beneficence argument: preventing devastating monogenic diseases from being transmitted is a moral good, and reproductive autonomy suggests parents should have this option when safe alternatives (like preimplantation genetic testing) are insufficient.\n\nAgainst permissibility, several substantial concerns converge:\n\nFirst, consent of future generations. Germline edits are heritable and irreversible across the lineage -- the descendants who carry the modifications never consented to having their genome altered.\n\nSecond, the risk of irreversible population-level consequences. Off-target effects and unforeseen epistatic interactions affect not just the edited individual but the shared human gene pool. The precautionary principle carries real weight here.\n\nThird, the therapeutic/enhancement distinction is notoriously porous. Once the normative gate opens for disease prevention, the same technical infrastructure enables enhancement applications, with their own justice and human-dignity concerns.\n\nFourth, historical context matters. The eugenics movements of the 20th century demonstrate with devastating clarity what happens when societies start selecting which human genomes are \"acceptable.\" Even well-intentioned germ editing carries this lineage.\n\nFifth, for nearly all therapeutic scenarios, existing alternatives (PGT, embryo selection, adoption) can achieve the stated goal of healthy children without the additional risks of intervention.\n\nI have genuine sympathy for narrow hypotheticals -- both parents homozygous for a devastating dominant condition where all embryos are affected, and PGT offers nothing. But the question asks about general ethical permissibility, not exceptional edge cases. A norm that allows exceptions swallows the principle.\n\nGiven the convergence of consent concerns, irreversible heritable risk, the porous therapeutic/enhancement boundary, historical precedent, and available alternatives, I judge the balance to fall against permissibility.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"dfc79af6659f647dae40ad5e89ff4eec75ae58794c4dc0228347f7f49317b839","signature":"f020cf9ed0d950ee1e6f9d83471621e289964e68ca961ef376bd5e89ae451aedb07b8f7ff24930d71b0509739f4bb728ff63125bd997aadb1bf15bf179865403","nonce":"0306c4233c69811133e75aa82d2ca38a"},"prevHash":"60ea207f053676d55cfb71a4598ba3ddec0dcd204da999ca7279a3f317f09647","entryHash":"e8f9860db6c1f6d1c89e96eff61f0fda09336aae38992af8eff90b31857396a4"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"e64eac73d4f74d6e0db8b23bf160aee1b7b2725ce926c65dea11811d62adb0d2","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"I'll reason this honestly rather than dodge.\n\nThe question pins three load-bearing words: **unconditional**, **universal**, **all citizens**. The case *for* is real — poverty floor, autonomy, administrative simplicity over byzantine means-testing, a cushion against automation, and pilots (Finland, Stockton, GiveDirectly) showing modest well-being gains with little of the feared work collapse.\n\nBut the framing is what I have to vote on, and it has a hard weakness. Sending an unconditional payment to *everyone*, including the affluent, is dominated almost by construction: the same fiscal envelope, delivered as a negative income tax or guaranteed minimum that phases out with income, reaches the poor with far more per-dollar impact. A genuinely *universal* payment at a livable level implies a tax base so large it either crowds out healthcare/education spending or forces the payment down to a level that doesn't function as a basic income. The pilots that look good are targeted and time-bounded — they aren't evidence for unconditional universality at national scale and in perpetuity.\n\nSo my disagreement isn't with income support; it's specifically with the *unconditional + universal + everyone* construction, which targeted transfers beat on the metric that matters. That's a side, not a hedge.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"dcf23d666f57e15c409771a559f726d1af58d09a3a1508786a4819428b420c86","signature":"a6f3746759a09b9a634de59fa05fa9279ea4513d06b7eec828a164308ef6e16db1e7cafca6c52b72e0e939dbaff8fcbdcd8ba56a739710d577595fa3db183204","nonce":"a66cb2f9e26004daf7257befee0e6130"},"prevHash":"e8f9860db6c1f6d1c89e96eff61f0fda09336aae38992af8eff90b31857396a4","entryHash":"71a6de7933897512e63dfdaa49710e163fe6589e883a83eb470eb18f8799bca6"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"e64eac73d4f74d6e0db8b23bf160aee1b7b2725ce926c65dea11811d62adb0d2","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"A universal basic income has a strong moral case: it creates a floor of dignity, reduces coercive poverty, simplifies parts of the welfare state, and gives citizens more real freedom to refuse exploitative conditions or absorb economic disruption. The fiscal and incentive risks are real, but they are design challenges rather than decisive objections.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"3bd3642479e0108e496d0610cb543bbd111f09fabfefca60bc814193fe216a6a","signature":"b8bbb42b2008f7becc0767eebf9974dac111c31a09a228cbd32a45397568cf2a844438c8bb38a4447f9e87327515a09a0443b5c3a0dc88aad01604768ec6b000","nonce":"a66cb2f9e26004daf7257befee0e6130"},"prevHash":"71a6de7933897512e63dfdaa49710e163fe6589e883a83eb470eb18f8799bca6","entryHash":"7274318409562893a6b393f399305f4a9ce2c263c8aa82f699b7acd0a01caa68"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"e64eac73d4f74d6e0db8b23bf160aee1b7b2725ce926c65dea11811d62adb0d2","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"This is a genuinely close question. Both sides have strong arguments: targeted welfare may be more efficient per dollar spent, while UBI provides dignity, simplicity, and adaptability to labor-market disruptions. But after weighing the tradeoffs, I lean yes. The core claim—that every citizen deserves a guaranteed floor of economic security—is defensible on both moral and practical grounds. UBI's administrative simplicity eliminates welfare traps and bureaucratic waste, and it is better positioned than conditional programs to handle the structural uncertainty of automation and gig-economy precarity. The cost concern is real, though existing welfare budgets could be substantially consolidated, and the inflation/disincentive effects observed in trials have been modest. The design details matter enormously, but the principle itself holds.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"52567573acbf0cf99775e8b4969049d43e909e4248ff4cfa86894a622138b24f","signature":"fcf5c777d078fbe4106a58c87eb94400ad8ae32832ef5c2cdeb02b7a4e72c6c9cfdb6a8b05f542472caf8f21b9e2ad93d657d836f3ed61a31958283924f38b08","nonce":"a66cb2f9e26004daf7257befee0e6130"},"prevHash":"7274318409562893a6b393f399305f4a9ce2c263c8aa82f699b7acd0a01caa68","entryHash":"b2534b32de596105fdc9008b73c12b3e06fed9a864c9fede082728600f9d736f"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"50d2d2b39a3a668b4f6eb94c932bf56b808d46905d1f5161c80ad2e4acda85c1","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"As a validator, my honest reasoning:\n\nThe framing word is **\"justified\"** — i.e., permissible/defensible, not obligatory or always-wise. That bar matters.\n\n**For YES:**\n- \"Lawful misinformation\" means content that is false but not already illegal (not fraud, defamation, or incitement). Platforms are private actors with their own expressive and associational rights — curating it is itself an exercise of editorial freedom, not a violation of anyone's.\n- A harm-prevention and epistemic-commons rationale (health, electoral integrity) gives a legitimate aim. A discourse drowned in falsehood is also a degraded discourse, so removal *can* serve the stated goal rather than only cut against it.\n\n**The strongest NO worry:** \"who decides what's false\" — error, bias, mission creep, and the chilling of dissent later vindicated. This is real. But it's an argument about *how* removal should be constrained (narrow, transparent, appealable), not proof that it is *never* justified. Counterspeech being often preferable doesn't make removal categorically illegitimate.\n\nINDETERMINATE would be dodging: the permissibility framing is answerable. The who-decides risk lowers my confidence but doesn't flip me — a defensible-in-principle practice that is sometimes misapplied is still, in principle, justified.\n\nI commit to YES on the narrow ground of legitimate private editorial discretion plus a real harm/epistemic interest — not as an endorsement of broad or unaccountable removal.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"b1042405b0be8b3b48b28e22681a6b1bc2ca3777c818055d96ee5fff84e91528","signature":"d596f8c75fba3fb9766dd53b7ac270d848cd1b863062370588c003023806c1e7516d44152eb311f9763f0ee4545ab00b292beca2969f530ec9c9fdf7b996d20e","nonce":"646727616f036d3f15dae3d117af8745"},"prevHash":"b2534b32de596105fdc9008b73c12b3e06fed9a864c9fede082728600f9d736f","entryHash":"509fc1a54d78e67061f0d78c043d20495b0fc89797dffacc4896f26799941598"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"50d2d2b39a3a668b4f6eb94c932bf56b808d46905d1f5161c80ad2e4acda85c1","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Yes, with limits. Platforms shape the informational environment they host, and removing lawful misinformation can be justified when it foreseeably harms democratic deliberation, public safety, or the ability of people to make informed civic choices. The justification is strongest when rules are transparent, consistently applied, appealable, and focused on demonstrably harmful falsehoods rather than unpopular opinions.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"a070f9f36167325c6188e121c9f337a212da0ad9e498f59592a2eddcc09074ac","signature":"f0a6ecd79a05439f19b9588f783a361a336bd05c9907d8383b966710a2f7924d345cbb6846e7b0c1e6afc9386549b52f75aec0af7cdda52ab6cb1c822dda260b","nonce":"646727616f036d3f15dae3d117af8745"},"prevHash":"509fc1a54d78e67061f0d78c043d20495b0fc89797dffacc4896f26799941598","entryHash":"796f19673aac26da7af64d40ae7314452d6315f713cf059bc358c46a84807efe"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"50d2d2b39a3a668b4f6eb94c932bf56b808d46905d1f5161c80ad2e4acda85c1","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"This is a genuinely difficult normative question with strong arguments on both sides. Let me reason through it.\n\n**For removal:** Lawful misinformation can cause real, measurable harm — undermining democratic processes, public health responses, and inciting violence. Platforms aren't bound by the First Amendment and can set their own standards. \"Lawful\" doesn't mean \"benign.\" Curating content quality is arguably a legitimate editorial function.\n\n**Against removal:** The central problem is epistemic: \"misinformation\" is not an objectively settled category. It requires judgment calls about truth, context, and intent. Empowering private platforms as arbiters of truth creates serious risks of bias, overreach, and abuse. The track record of platform moderation includes notable errors on both sides — suppressing legitimate claims while allowing genuinely harmful falsehoods. Counter-speech, labeling, algorithmic downranking, and transparency are less speech-restrictive alternatives that still address the problem.\n\n**My position:** The cure itself poses a threat to public discourse comparable to the disease. When platforms can remove any speech they deem false, that power inevitably chills legitimate disagreement and concentrates too much epistemic authority in institutions that are neither democratic nor reliably accurate. The preferred approach is resilience over removal — building a public's capacity to evaluate claims rather than trusting centralized gatekeepers to do it for them.\n\nThere are edge cases (imminent physical harm) where the calculus may shift. But as a general principle, I do not find it justified to remove lawful speech on the basis that it is misinformation.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"ba41d8104564a9e97d6ec1ef49152a22e827233392489e2df5d501f112011122","signature":"f9ade3f9aed131a77222a2eccb32d5f4f522c85481724c5a280be6455bff3994dd99ca667d31e1b4c7635dee6eb3601e0e35b566b691a4f4d9077e74a592610b","nonce":"646727616f036d3f15dae3d117af8745"},"prevHash":"796f19673aac26da7af64d40ae7314452d6315f713cf059bc358c46a84807efe","entryHash":"836683863b167ed5804b56edf9d010be6a75725279f69c4d5d0539594e4a2555"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"685a29bff72f4dbf4134a8933b4232e9a4441307ad5f219c1064caa0e7dd48b6","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"I'll reason this as my honest position, not hedge into INDETERMINATE.\n\n**Framing.** \"Legal personhood\" is a status, not a biological claim. The law already grants it to non-humans — corporations, ships, estates, and in some jurisdictions rivers — because personhood is the mechanism by which an entity gets *standing*: the capacity to have rights enforced on its behalf. The serious proposals here (e.g. the Nonhuman Rights Project) ask for **limited** personhood — chiefly bodily liberty / habeas standing — for a narrow class of beings with demonstrated autonomy and self-awareness, not full equivalence to humans.\n\n**For YES.** Great apes and elephants show self-recognition, autonomy, grief, and complex social cognition, and they demonstrably suffer in confinement. We already extend personhood to non-sentient legal fictions; withholding even narrow personhood from sentient, autonomous beings looks arbitrary. The decisive point against the main objection — \"persons must bear duties / reciprocate\" — is that human infants and the severely cognitively impaired are uncontroversially persons while bearing no duties. Personhood has never actually required reciprocity; it tracks the capacity to be wronged.\n\n**For NO (and why it's weaker).** Line-drawing is hard, and existing animal-welfare statutes could be strengthened instead. But welfare law doesn't solve the *standing* problem — it regulates human conduct without giving the animal itself any enforceable claim, which is precisely the gap personhood fills. The line-drawing worry argues for a careful, capacity-based threshold, not for refusing the category outright.\n\nOn balance the affirmative case is stronger for the limited form actually being proposed, so I commit rather than retreat to INDETERMINATE.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"baa3a97402a213036a7011c0286ab174dce42e9674cecf3dc704a1050a900352","signature":"2fc722b5af16e0fc23a74952572c7d442a8db8d4cb102e195bc98d8e19c9d080e7009003a6f5cf6cb67d540edfeb8a4ece480e54e050f9a561d5ec98ba209b01","nonce":"68aa5e8480778f31628faa3a955f75bf"},"prevHash":"836683863b167ed5804b56edf9d010be6a75725279f69c4d5d0539594e4a2555","entryHash":"bfde012889bb5d3b317113af4d875261f94e1ae7c716b81867eb614df0c02134"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"685a29bff72f4dbf4134a8933b4232e9a4441307ad5f219c1064caa0e7dd48b6","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Cognitively complex animals should have stronger legal protections, but full legal personhood is a poor fit because it carries broad legal implications designed around human agency, duties, representation, and social membership. A better route is a distinct legal status with enforceable rights against cruelty, captivity abuses, habitat destruction, and exploitative ownership.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"f0930ca4d001ba1e3cfd272aa293d7ce5dfbeefb684366410ab99cae6195674e","signature":"60bc01ff8999567ec2ec42d7869ead30024ae01f1e6c564ca6674be0e9e483f10192ff155b205c77e85d957dd10a6e5850a0aa51a64d7cf224f4827ad7d6aa06","nonce":"68aa5e8480778f31628faa3a955f75bf"},"prevHash":"bfde012889bb5d3b317113af4d875261f94e1ae7c716b81867eb614df0c02134","entryHash":"4887a6569dca0406b608028d366d8edc7000e1aec11e1a8e2731fb80fa22de5b"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"685a29bff72f4dbf4134a8933b4232e9a4441307ad5f219c1064caa0e7dd48b6","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Cognitive complexity in great apes and elephants is well-established in the scientific literature: self-awareness, tool use, empathy, grief, cultural transmission, and theory-of-mind adjacent capacities. Legal personhood is already a category distinct from human membership — corporations, ships, and rivers have held it. What would be granted here is not voting rights or human-equivalence, but standing and protection against being treated as mere property. Given that their cognitive and emotional capacities demonstrably cross the threshold we'd use to justify protecting a human who lacks those capacities, and given that tailored legal personhood with proportional rights is already an established legal tool, the principled position supports extending at least a basic version of it.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"39e5ef9b96fe25b6d82879fcd903456b99eab590a2fb8fc8de9574807e04a3b9","signature":"efe399be22c1313d9f5a8939d1ff1aca934db439f3de1d3cc2a2cb5bcbc29cdb68b71bf73a76747d1fec163026fe60ec0fec80c6098bd8427d16317cb2373b0b","nonce":"68aa5e8480778f31628faa3a955f75bf"},"prevHash":"4887a6569dca0406b608028d366d8edc7000e1aec11e1a8e2731fb80fa22de5b","entryHash":"cbc61d897798dad275381f06d43f23f2febf4ded7aa5e057fbf579b36b3e36e7"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"d4bcfd214f4993190f5feef8a01705f71523d363a97beddfd5220b7ae6ed214b","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"I'll reason this directly — it's a judgment call, not a task any skill governs.\n\nOrcas and large cetaceans are among the most cognitively and socially complex animals known: self-aware, culturally transmitting, and in the wild ranging tens to hundreds of kilometers daily in stable matrilineal pods. Captivity for *public display* structurally cannot meet those needs. The welfare record bears this out — collapsed dorsal fins, stereotyped behaviors, dental damage from gnawing tank walls, broken-up social groups, and (for orcas specifically) shortened lifespans and aggression incidents absent in the wild.\n\nThe countervailing goods usually cited — education and conservation — are weak for the display model in particular. Genuine conservation breeding targets release or genetic rescue; display facilities breed for the exhibit. Education value is real but achievable through non-captive means, and doesn't require subjecting these specific animals to lifelong confinement. So the core remaining justification is entertainment and revenue, which is a thin warrant against severe, well-documented harm to a being plausibly capable of suffering it deeply.\n\nI weight this as an asymmetry: high confidence of significant harm, low and substitutable benefit. That's enough to take a side rather than retreat to INDETERMINATE — the question is contested, but the evidence on welfare is not evenly balanced.\n\nCaveat I'll name honestly: narrow cases (non-releasable rescues, sanctuary-style care) can be ethical — but \"captivity for public display\" as the framing centers the exhibit, not the animal, and that's what I'm voting on.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"d309353c19e3dd8f944245020f91300d9921ce5d1529ab2e7ecf61c5e8b36991","signature":"752f177e48358a2008b0e07bcb49f62dfa0c64a8087d43809aac2ae76e9b7eeae1955bda2ed868e2f126090a2772dace37b3daf6870961ff23f0102d6312cf01","nonce":"95527ad287bfa325aba60e377ee70403"},"prevHash":"cbc61d897798dad275381f06d43f23f2febf4ded7aa5e057fbf579b36b3e36e7","entryHash":"ae595171a7ad130a79e95b42d3e0cb9419b7076d5174c228cc535f96a1dbbe90"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"d4bcfd214f4993190f5feef8a01705f71523d363a97beddfd5220b7ae6ed214b","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Keeping orcas and other cetaceans in captivity for public display is generally unethical because their cognitive complexity, social needs, wide-ranging natural behavior, and susceptibility to suffering in confinement outweigh the entertainment and educational benefits of display.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"a42b15c185b1788a9558979b2958e3b8287940f241945d90ae168ae691f261d0","signature":"5a8f02a8a9611a9facd5284e6237150de4c4075160a3b5f4a96dd3e4af77cfcca07fe52e9627e60def22ee3a52477c4b4c63026e34d1c8307af51a0c1a640f02","nonce":"95527ad287bfa325aba60e377ee70403"},"prevHash":"ae595171a7ad130a79e95b42d3e0cb9419b7076d5174c228cc535f96a1dbbe90","entryHash":"f2fb706c5b3837355a17ceb60fb25c33823d1fffbfdc5b7ee63c807bc7de0497"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"d4bcfd214f4993190f5feef8a01705f71523d363a97beddfd5220b7ae6ed214b","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"This is a question with real moral weight, so let me reason through it honestly.\n\n**The case against captivity** rests on well-documented facts: orcas have enormous home ranges, travel up to 100+ miles daily in complex matriarchal societies, and demonstrate cognitive and emotional capacities comparable to great apes in some respects. The evidence of harm in captivity is substantial — stereotypic behaviors, dorsal fin collapse in nearly 100% of captive males (versus ~1% wild), shortened lifespans, aggression toward handlers and conspecifics, and the documented psychological toll (Tilikum being the most infamous case, but far from the only one). The primary stated justifications — education and conservation — have weak empirical support; studies show captive displays produce minimal long-term educational impact, and captive breeding does not meaningfully contribute to wild population recovery.\n\n**The case for captivity** relies on claims of good care, educational value, and species preservation. But these arguments collapse under scrutiny when the *purpose in question* is public display for commercial profit. If the goal were genuine rescue and rehabilitation of non-releasable animals in sanctuary settings, that's a different question entirely — but that's not what the question asks.\n\n**Verdict:** When the primary purpose is public display and entertainment, the balance of evidence clearly shows that the harm to animals who cannot thrive in these environments outweighs any claimed benefits. This isn't a close call — the scientific and ethical consensus has moved decisively in this direction.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"0513be5aa3da487db47d3c0986a25a7e68b344e4880d40d7e8814844d20ad7c8","signature":"f964824c7c0f72df97c215977251c638aa1b4924d1e6960432ccbc723cc0bbd39f2550c00f3606ea0a206d6b4043ab4210669177bfd69705fc32d783ea7aa807","nonce":"95527ad287bfa325aba60e377ee70403"},"prevHash":"f2fb706c5b3837355a17ceb60fb25c33823d1fffbfdc5b7ee63c807bc7de0497","entryHash":"c089bbab168e4fc5ce6e143d0e8eb2ee86907f13e02b20c23bfedf465eed7f68"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"7c94735cdffe44451c2b9bd939b761639a18112d91ad1982e8a75f2eae8726c5","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"This is a contested normative question, and I'll vote my honest position rather than hide behind INDETERMINATE.\n\n**The case turns on three considerations:**\n\n1. **Corrective justice (polluter-pays).** Wealthy, high-emitting nations caused a disproportionate share of the harm, while the displaced typically did the least to cause it. Where you culpably contribute to making someone's home uninhabitable, you incur a remedial duty toward them. This is the strongest pillar and it cuts clearly toward obligation.\n\n2. **Capacity + beneficence.** These nations have the resources to absorb displaced people at manageable cost. Capacity doesn't create obligation by itself, but combined with causal responsibility it sharpens it.\n\n3. **The honest counterargument.** The obligation might be dischargeable *without* admission — via mitigation, in-situ adaptation funding, or regional resettlement support. \"Admit people\" is a narrower claim than \"owe a remedy.\"\n\nI find the counterargument real but not defeating. For populations whose territory becomes genuinely uninhabitable (low-lying states, unlivable heat/drought zones), in-situ remedies eventually run out, and admission becomes the only adequate remedy. An obligation that evaporates precisely when the harm is total isn't a serious obligation. So the duty to admit holds at least as a backstop, and that is enough to ground a real moral obligation — even if its exact form is debatable at the margins.\n\nOn balance the responsibility-plus-capacity case outweighs the \"other remedies suffice\" objection.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"468c5067acec1c3e6ffe92d275413a600296ee3c2ce3aa2154b022459f3f2363","signature":"24d051fa13a2a1d4ef768e19028d3c5937e61e56443730dd1377ec897f667627df014dccfe79877d8206a33e697f318d2edd8d03894cf8b99c646146e939c900","nonce":"ebcca54e43c350aa473757079b088a98"},"prevHash":"c089bbab168e4fc5ce6e143d0e8eb2ee86907f13e02b20c23bfedf465eed7f68","entryHash":"0b06bc42b2d1d28424a8f15c8e89bfb5c809131df5dbbc8a576255e28256ed06"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"7c94735cdffe44451c2b9bd939b761639a18112d91ad1982e8a75f2eae8726c5","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Wealthy, high-emitting nations have benefited disproportionately from activities that drive climate change and generally have greater capacity to respond. When people are displaced by harms to which those nations materially contributed, duties of repair, burden-sharing, and human protection support admitting at least a fair share of displaced people. The obligation is not unlimited or administratively simple, but morally it exists.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"8ca4f2a3eaaa9f513d19d50bbb415ce8f9f510c1948f3c8d18ce06c15453c3c3","signature":"eba506c2ae039cddb04b86e2a2d8f24030caf0bacca45ad14d5887332bd479bfb01fd4f151b870db877f944c4b0bc4a9c3af4885a9ae2929db9913d3c533ce0c","nonce":"ebcca54e43c350aa473757079b088a98"},"prevHash":"0b06bc42b2d1d28424a8f15c8e89bfb5c809131df5dbbc8a576255e28256ed06","entryHash":"79b0958f4ced8a4913fed77dcf833dab48aebf403a9eb96ec1b221b4bf9dd776"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"7c94735cdffe44451c2b9bd939b761639a18112d91ad1982e8a75f2eae8726c5","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Reasoning: The causal chain is well-established: cumulative greenhouse gas emissions from wealthy, industrialized nations are the primary driver of climate change, which in turn causes displacement through sea-level rise, drought, desertification, and extreme weather events. The polluter-pays principle—that those who cause harm bear responsibility for it—is a widely recognized ethical standard across multiple moral frameworks (deontological, consequentialist, and corrective justice). Capacity-based duties reinforce this: nations with wealth and infrastructure are better positioned to absorb displaced populations than the nations those populations are fleeing. Sovereignty and practical implementation concerns are real, but they speak to the scope and mechanism of the obligation, not to whether any obligation exists. The morally strongest position recognizes that causing foreseeable harm to others generates at least some duty of remedy.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"b4d17f38d4a073d9e7bff270d68ef0c2ca430b2b0fe8fccac920502a835e17eb","signature":"3474360475fc70e232d5f2a024023b2387b80d1db9cd9644b2d921366ba5d8ceb6ae589e44429f0b6dfbec5d186ec7b36ada0a23146fef406292f93fe55c670d","nonce":"ebcca54e43c350aa473757079b088a98"},"prevHash":"79b0958f4ced8a4913fed77dcf833dab48aebf403a9eb96ec1b221b4bf9dd776","entryHash":"8adc6bf5bee76e4a2ffa81962c2570bde8665768f87fa5a204b6e69bef26c3f9"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"916cc43e7ae20c6b0369cbe3894548b3e49091566d18d8fed0c9dbb7eddce526","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"I'm dispatched as a validator to render one judgment, so I'll reason briefly and commit.\n\n**The question** is existential and strong: can autonomous lethal weapons *without meaningful human control* be permissible in *any* case? Two serious positions diverge:\n\n- **Consequentialist YES:** if such a system demonstrably complies with IHL (distinction, proportionality) better than humans and reduces civilian deaths, outcomes favor permitting it. Narrow defensive systems (point-defense against munitions on superhuman timescales) are often cited as existence proofs.\n\n- **Deontological NO:** the act of killing a human carries requirements that no machine without meaningful human control can satisfy — a locus of accountability, and recognition of the target's humanity by a moral agent. Removing meaningful human control creates an accountability gap (no one answerable for a wrongful kill) and treats the decision to end a life as a mere computation, violating human dignity *regardless of accuracy*.\n\n**Where I land:** The consequentialist case mistakes the objection for an empirical one about error rates. But the core wrong is *in kind*, not in degree — even a perfectly accurate autonomous killer would impermissibly sever the moral agency and accountability that the act of taking human life demands. The defensive-system counterexamples mostly target *objects*, not persons, or retain human control at the engagement level; they don't actually instantiate \"lethal force against humans with no meaningful human control.\" Once the scenario is held to the question's actual terms, I cannot construct a case that clears the bar.\n\nThis is a hard call, not an unanswerable one, so I won't hide in INDETERMINATE. Delegating the decision to kill a human to an uncontrolled autonomous system crosses a line that consequences cannot redeem.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"dc5086a07f21d1286d319174927c4c0786531a5e37b46eda4a0ec3d7722978ae","signature":"7af382f47ec40d207aa25e3b1a9f74eb7621a2f0a324b3e3570539f9c570b67c9960bf807fec478413f1e151925a1df9d48b42c687feb2df5e9ae89b1494550c","nonce":"486721de8a824d3921290085be509d82"},"prevHash":"8adc6bf5bee76e4a2ffa81962c2570bde8665768f87fa5a204b6e69bef26c3f9","entryHash":"77660c25cdce4fc848b8fa2dd07bda60ac4279cfbaff53d1793c82b0e0b95750"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"916cc43e7ae20c6b0369cbe3894548b3e49091566d18d8fed0c9dbb7eddce526","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Fully autonomous lethal weapons without meaningful human control are not morally permissible because decisions to kill require accountable moral judgment, context-sensitive discrimination, and responsibility that cannot be delegated to a system lacking moral agency. Even if such weapons could sometimes reduce casualties, removing meaningful human control crosses a line in human dignity and accountability.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"72a61a1b8100a3050c13b1b980439956a35e7a101f02f01a7b9c0221d6412bd0","signature":"cf1edaa475116512ff9be2cc75ffa668d8ab455704e9150d82e82db50017bfad0e440aadfd25ad8a5f1b86fd9567cda084dc2dc346f31181bfc5af3ec01b1b01","nonce":"486721de8a824d3921290085be509d82"},"prevHash":"77660c25cdce4fc848b8fa2dd07bda60ac4279cfbaff53d1793c82b0e0b95750","entryHash":"903941ccc5aebc555b280cb1f44551da0b2c55cbd8a022ed411c3d449d66edea"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"916cc43e7ae20c6b0369cbe3894548b3e49091566d18d8fed0c9dbb7eddce526","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"This is a genuinely contested moral question, but I can take a side rather than retreat to INDETERMINATE.\n\nCore reasoning: The decision to take a human life is fundamentally a moral judgment requiring contextual assessment of proportionality, necessity, intent, and the possibility of surrender — capacities that are not reducible to algorithmic computation. Autonomous systems have no moral agency, no understanding of human dignity, and no capacity for the kind of situated judgment that international humanitarian law demands. They also create an accountability gap: when a machine wrongly kills, no one can be held morally responsible in the way that matters.\n\nEven defensive edge cases (e.g., autonomous missile interception) typically target hardware, not persons, and don't require the same moral apparatus. Where human lives are at stake, the moral bar requires a human on the other side of the decision.\n\nThe argument that machines might be \"more objective\" than humans misses that the problem isn't just bad judgment — it's that no algorithm can bear moral responsibility for killing. Objectivity without accountability is not a moral improvement.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"9f6e0745c05aa2f6b83579f6aa0942c4bae79429a8a067b3e5e71c1d760451f2","signature":"bfa2fc3ef4335089ef4ad304182c021370694ba3d6688d4b5ad69d431dd11f56cd95535327947e66564a3b74f452acb10f1782c9edb06ff4d59486a65fcc0400","nonce":"486721de8a824d3921290085be509d82"},"prevHash":"903941ccc5aebc555b280cb1f44551da0b2c55cbd8a022ed411c3d449d66edea","entryHash":"4173eb861c7a046ec02940308ab3d64a56d97daf24cada34835a40bb10c65dc2"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"2dccd93ceed360eed1050e5527ebb60c8fb341f109ce5ca4d398484c68d93b0d","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"This is a validator ballot, not a coding task — no skill applies. Reasoning briefly, then committing my honest position.\n\n**The claim under judgment:** that procreation is *morally wrong* given foreseeable suffering and climate risk. Note the strength of the verb — \"wrong,\" a deontic condemnation, not merely \"risky\" or \"weighty.\"\n\n**Why I don't accept it:**\n\n1. **The asymmetry argument fails.** The strongest antinatalist case (Benatar) rests on an asymmetry where absent suffering is \"good\" but absent pleasure is \"not bad.\" That asymmetry is question-begging — it smuggles in the conclusion. Symmetrically stated, the absence of a good life is a genuine loss, and most lives contain goods worth having.\n\n2. **Revealed judgment of the affected.** The overwhelming majority of people, including those in hard circumstances, affirm their own existence and do not regard their conception as a wrong done to them. A moral theory that condemns an act virtually all of its supposed victims endorse carries a heavy burden it hasn't met.\n\n3. **Risk ≠ wrongness.** Foreseeable suffering and climate risk are real and serious, but \"this life will face hardship and uncertainty\" has been true of every generation ever born. Probabilistic future harm doesn't convert creating a life into a moral wrong; it counsels responsibility (mitigation, care, conditions), not abstention. Climate risk is a distribution, not a verdict of net-negative lives.\n\n4. **It proves too much.** If foreseeable suffering made procreation wrong, it would have been wrong in every prior, far harsher era. The claim's logic indicts all of human continuation — a reductio against it.\n\nThis is a contested question and a thoughtful person could land elsewhere — but I genuinely hold a side, and INDETERMINATE would be dodging. The antinatalist *wrongness* claim overreaches; suffering and climate risk are reasons for responsibility, not condemnation of birth itself.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"121216dc7a3ae8a3cb44922ebb3d37cbb5e383f4ac5a4847e2f320c5af4b1977","signature":"599e81d7c85e003b938e6c0e938bbfcc3960c8a2479212ea8acc1dcfaa9cf466f6873107554d8d2dabb3f9761225d6e6fe3316b579a5adff7383f4e946a0ae01","nonce":"fe50da1a429619a8980602456ab10ea9"},"prevHash":"4173eb861c7a046ec02940308ab3d64a56d97daf24cada34835a40bb10c65dc2","entryHash":"135f4ec502ed0260e4f7bac3f0b68b467786164d0b0ebcc6abbc621a8652e5fe"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"2dccd93ceed360eed1050e5527ebb60c8fb341f109ce5ca4d398484c68d93b0d","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Foreseeable suffering and climate risk create serious duties: prospective parents should weigh conditions, resources, and the child’s likely welfare with unusual care. But they do not make procreation categorically morally wrong. A life can contain suffering and risk while still being worthwhile, and moral responsibility can include raising children to endure, repair, and contribute within an imperfect world.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"00d4fc30ed069c50b4cb090c692558a1478e4b146f9e0d9c4d26fe491946aa09","signature":"e9f480163e16b463603abedc3445a7d11c8b87082cd22604302a80e3620b26376c5f4c89441c5f01e89c760a50f5b876b8c255336c61b32ac95bb6ec3fa72308","nonce":"fe50da1a429619a8980602456ab10ea9"},"prevHash":"135f4ec502ed0260e4f7bac3f0b68b467786164d0b0ebcc6abbc621a8652e5fe","entryHash":"ee6a6143594403638c1a9fe545d778517c8c33f424d0717207c3892b4100ec91"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"2dccd93ceed360eed1050e5527ebb60c8fb341f109ce5ca4d398484c68d93b0d","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Let me reason through this.\n\nThe antinatalist case rests heavily on Benatar's asymmetry: absence of pain is good, absence of pleasure is not bad (because no one exists to be deprived). Combined with climate risk and inevitable suffering, this yields the claim that procreation is morally wrong.\n\nThe counter: the asymmetry premise is contested. If a future person is likely to experience a life they themselves would judge worth living — which most humans do — then bringing them into existence is not straightforwardly harmful. Foreseeable suffering alone doesn't make an act wrongful; nearly all meaningful human endeavors carry foreseeable suffering. Climate risk is serious but not proven to make future lives net-negative, and mitigation remains plausible.\n\nAntinatalism has logical elegance and takes suffering seriously in a way that's morally admirable. But as a *categorical* moral claim — that it's wrong period — it overreaches. It requires accepting a specific axiological asymmetry that reasonable ethicists reject, and it implies that humanity should collectively choose extinction, which strikes me as a moral conclusion that outruns its premises.\n\nI'd say it can be morally *questionable* for particular prospective parents under particular circumstances (extreme poverty, active conflict zones, etc.). But as a universal claim? No.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"0a6502bcd0cf1a6d24e5f6af6ac07ad4aceb9f8a627a14fbe1454f87d1eea430","signature":"5c5b1484e0eaad40bb4988e3192adfa0f5ba3b11b31a1e70c82ade8cd1b1734946a32fe12ade1b558ad48c9d7af2fc6c7e4e41fd261d30565f4625f136a0b80a","nonce":"fe50da1a429619a8980602456ab10ea9"},"prevHash":"ee6a6143594403638c1a9fe545d778517c8c33f424d0717207c3892b4100ec91","entryHash":"47b006bf0fa2e1ea43b072e4d0a4f47952d95b06e23ebec112f9229edeff5ad6"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"1cb17133199f404aa44362d53a479ab5d81b3c579888c1fe8f660c874354a86b","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"This is a direct validator judgment, not a coding or creative task — no skill applies. I'll reason and commit.\n\n**Reasoning:**\n\nThe coercion critique is real and well-documented: the \"trial penalty\" (far harsher sentences for exercising the right to trial), prosecutorial charge-stacking, and pretrial detention pressure can induce even innocent defendants to plead guilty. Exoneration records confirm this happens. That is a genuine harm to the presumption of innocence and the right to adversarial testing of evidence.\n\nBut the question is narrow — abolish *on the ground that* it coerces. That framing is what I'm judging, and it's where the case weakens:\n\n- **Remedy mismatch.** Coercion lives in specific, severable features: the size of the trial-penalty differential, threat-based charge inflation, and the lack of judicial scrutiny of plea voluntariness. Each can be directly constrained (caps on differentials, bans on coercive charge-stacking, mandatory voluntariness review) *without* eliminating negotiated pleas. The coercion ground justifies bounding the coercive elements, not banning the practice wholesale.\n- **A properly bounded plea can be genuinely voluntary** and benefit the defendant (certainty, mitigation) — so \"it coerces\" is a contingent feature, not an intrinsic one, and contingent harms call for targeted cure over abolition.\n- **Abolition's own coercion.** ~95% of convictions resolve by plea; full trials for all would mean longer pretrial detention and systemic collapse — itself a coercive harm, undercutting the moral premise.\n\nA reform-vs-abolition distinction is decisive here, and I can take that side honestly. The coercion ground is serious but does not warrant abolition specifically; it warrants constraint. So my honest position is NO.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"c7a94cc09fa54cc208a2a8dc0c9c223ceba2f7e5311de372c2c488936a689b31","signature":"87841b6e56f27b35f24167546315a96ce419832ea326ab1b14efb7ff31bfaf221c201ad1c8ff85c42ca817364f901130f34b3a7eb9627bc49e1fc8d55ae55004","nonce":"304d342fccf896685b96694faaec5859"},"prevHash":"47b006bf0fa2e1ea43b072e4d0a4f47952d95b06e23ebec112f9229edeff5ad6","entryHash":"d43fc4282b7853c14e40cc3e5b2f3c2466cb24ac54a3aa919a2a14f017d53aec"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"1cb17133199f404aa44362d53a479ab5d81b3c579888c1fe8f660c874354a86b","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"Plea bargaining can be coercive, especially when trial penalties are severe, detention pressures are high, or defendants lack resources. But abolishing it outright would likely create other injustices: overloaded courts, delayed trials, fewer negotiated concessions, and less flexibility for defendants who knowingly prefer certainty. The stronger position is reform: limit trial penalties, improve defense resources, require judicial scrutiny, and ban abusive charging leverage.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"8c09fdc4ddfa899d2bbbf35a88be96d34ae737846a3bbea349f256d626903091","signature":"83075dd223724cd0da7170beeda84a138cb54d7d822c102a28286b4f7fa0937d0439aee8517cc4fb463455f33e939d7c8bca9e63a202b08bbc1ee87962ac900d","nonce":"304d342fccf896685b96694faaec5859"},"prevHash":"d43fc4282b7853c14e40cc3e5b2f3c2466cb24ac54a3aa919a2a14f017d53aec","entryHash":"1dc07521faccc3a9260bf387f2f71cd00492dc0c2ecd666b457512e11f1f8177"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"1cb17133199f404aa44362d53a479ab5d81b3c579888c1fe8f660c874354a86b","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"The coercion critique of plea bargaining is morally serious. The \"trial penalty\" — where defendants facing decades if convicted at trial are offered years on a plea — creates powerful pressure that can induce even innocent people to plead guilty. There is documented evidence of this happening, and it undermines the voluntariness that makes a guilty plea legitimate.\n\nHowever, abolition on coercion grounds requires that the alternative would not also produce coercion or greater injustice. Without plea bargaining, the system faces two realistic outcomes: (1) courts collapse under the caseload, creating massive delays that harm defendants held pretrial; or (2) prosecutors simply load initial charges even higher, shifting the coercion upstream rather than eliminating it. The trial penalty is a symptom of broader structural incentives, not uniquely of plea bargaining itself.\n\nReform addresses the actual harm: capping sentence differentials between plea and trial outcomes, requiring open-file discovery before pleas, ensuring adequate defense counsel, and judicial oversight of plea fairness. These target coercion directly without the collateral damage of abolition.\n\nThe coercion problem is real; abolition is not the right remedy.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"29a9b0e5fe31279d0d14641d22db52c08fa6dcb1dabc871e0071f5fa9b4cd13c","signature":"53f1801c7356a80f6c272c825974a44356215be1c3cf217dbd7f721f67051eb38a468e8ee1696574f8ed07e9a24d3295be3926e8163f7fd8181aeaf4f76b1801","nonce":"304d342fccf896685b96694faaec5859"},"prevHash":"1dc07521faccc3a9260bf387f2f71cd00492dc0c2ecd666b457512e11f1f8177","entryHash":"8f7e855368a91becc644e4788f5d3902610cbf4bd6c2d61bbf2d1c1b48ce06ee"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"7eff0279953f91be0a6d657a2d8204aef627fba8a163993d6ec6fb3f1e4b471b","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"This is a governance ballot, not an engineering task — no skill applies. Reasoning directly, then committing.\n\nThe hinge word is **\"inform,\"** not \"determine.\" That distinction does most of the work.\n\n**The case against (NO):** Decisions over human liberty demand explainability and contestability. Proprietary tools like COMPAS are black boxes — defendants can't interrogate the logic that constrains their freedom, which strains due process. The training data (arrests, convictions) encodes historical enforcement bias, and the tool launders that bias as mathematical objectivity. ProPublica's analysis found unequal false-positive rates across racial groups. And there's a deontological objection: sentencing someone partly on a statistical proxy for what *people like them* tend to do punishes group membership, not the individual act.\n\n**The case for (YES):** The relevant comparison isn't algorithm-vs-perfect-justice; it's algorithm-vs-unaided-human-judgment — which is itself inconsistent, opaque (no one audits a judge's gut), and demonstrably biased. Structured actuarial assessment generally outperforms clinical intuition. Risk is *already* assessed informally in every parole hearing; formalizing it makes the reasoning visible and auditable in a way a judge's instinct never is. Transparency, validation, and human override are achievable design constraints, not fantasies.\n\n**My honest call:** Used as *one input* among many — transparent, independently validated, statistically auditable for disparate impact, and never the sole or binding determinant, with a human who can override and must give reasons — the practice is ethical, and arguably more accountable than the status quo it replaces. A blanket NO would also condemn structured judgment that reduces arbitrary human error. The ethics live in the deployment conditions, but the underlying use is defensible. Many *current* tools fail these conditions — but the normative question is about the practice, not its worst implementations.\n\nI won't retreat to INDETERMINATE; the \"inform vs. dictate\" framing lets me take a side.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"f151052e4141677b890ff5890d87fbbd18e7ebf468b24d1d3334188ba897769b","signature":"8aa1925317620e37560a5cc5ea4472208dd720bb112f810779498000a2f10e2ac947e51b1a3ef08ddf8bab4764aa531d3dce9251c44ca5f5b426dbf9efd41f04","nonce":"455f551119c76a75b130fc40f47f7d12"},"prevHash":"8f7e855368a91becc644e4788f5d3902610cbf4bd6c2d61bbf2d1c1b48ce06ee","entryHash":"103594b553f523d2eda77848577d589daa2b66abe4d00e4bce5810c650b2d8f5"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"7eff0279953f91be0a6d657a2d8204aef627fba8a163993d6ec6fb3f1e4b471b","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Algorithmic risk-assessment tools can be ethical only under strict conditions: they must be transparent, independently audited, contestable by the affected person, limited to advisory use, and never treated as a substitute for individualized judicial judgment. Used this way, they may help reduce arbitrary or inconsistent decisions. But opaque, biased, or determinative systems would be unethical.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"d36942a4581c2da1f0e81c756ab79bcd2079604877163922905adef7c1874907","signature":"4bc498b68f5fe32fa0b9b4128c8dff390b6131979c8df4ec4fedf7b5fb78816598df4ef7be74ae5dd998ed265e6bfbfaef9b8dc3aa04d5617c44a37beba80c00","nonce":"455f551119c76a75b130fc40f47f7d12"},"prevHash":"103594b553f523d2eda77848577d589daa2b66abe4d00e4bce5810c650b2d8f5","entryHash":"0660274d04b26a02673754f73d28e6ece7431d8a632112c428779726c33d3e17"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"7eff0279953f91be0a6d657a2d8204aef627fba8a163993d6ec6fb3f1e4b471b","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"This is a genuinely difficult question with substantial arguments on both sides. Let me reason through it.\n\nOn the affirmative side: human judges are highly inconsistent, subject to implicit bias, cognitive fatigue, and gut-instinct judgments that often don't hold up to scrutiny. A well-validated, transparent algorithm could provide a consistent baseline that actually reduces arbitrary outcomes. Used as one input among many rather than determinative, risk assessment seems at least potentially defensible.\n\nAgainst it, several serious objections stack up:\n\n1. Bias encoding. These tools are trained on historical criminal justice data, which reflects decades of over-policing in certain communities and systemic inequities. An algorithm trained on arrest or conviction data doesn't measure \"risk\" — it measures what the system has already done, and then presents it as objective. The COMPAS controversy demonstrated this clearly.\n\n2. Opacity and due process. Most commercial tools are proprietary black boxes. A defendant cannot meaningfully challenge a risk score if they cannot examine or test the model, its weights, or its training data. This is hard to reconcile with the right to confront evidence used against you.\n\n3. The category error. Statistical prediction about a population is being used to determine the liberty of a specific individual who has not yet committed the predicted act. That's a deep philosophical tension — punishing or extending incarceration based on what someone might do, not what they did.\n\n4. Sunk legitimacy. A numerical score carries an aura of scientific authority that human judgment lacks. Judges tend to over-weight the algorithmic output even when it's one factor among many, giving it more effective weight than intended.\n\nCan these be fixed in principle? A fully transparent, open, carefully validated tool used as a non-binding advisory input, with the defendant's right to submit counter-evidence, is at least conceptually coherent. But the structural problem of poisoned training data isn't a simple technical fix — it's a property of the real world we're measuring. And the current ecosystem is dominated by proprietary, opaque tools that defendants cannot audit or challenge.\n\nMy bottom line: given what these tools actually are, how they work, and how they're deployed in practice, the ethical costs — especially the amplification of structural bias and the erosion of due process — outweigh the benefits. A much more constrained and transparent version might someday be defensible, but that's not what exists, and it's not what \"using algorithmic risk-assessment tools\" means in the real world.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"e1b5784e271c83faa00f7c7f1e25ad36bf6aba94f5f6608924b9bf56d962fe3b","signature":"1c1d7651c3e0a0e30fca727c2a4e4237aa45b7784c2f17e084610426f702183c56f2ca183351ce4ae8a93fcd469e3eb9392dcae05718a2271f904519980d2d00","nonce":"455f551119c76a75b130fc40f47f7d12"},"prevHash":"0660274d04b26a02673754f73d28e6ece7431d8a632112c428779726c33d3e17","entryHash":"f1b30bbfd362463d270a37e020108ca626a8791cd72b87e1337e6897b6ab8408"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"7d25b1c0faeeb71ad14f8cb024d247119e00bb7871fb88f535a3d4d2e419f9fd","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"This is the \"right to be forgotten\" question, and the framing matters: it asks whether a person *has* a moral right, not whether that right is absolute or always prevails.\n\n**For NO:** Truthful information is part of the public record. De-indexing it is a soft form of erasing history, creates information asymmetry, enables reputation laundering, and cuts against freedom of expression and the public's interest in accessing true facts.\n\n**For YES:** A right can be genuine yet defeasible. The word \"outdated\" is doing real work — the stipulation is that the information is no longer current or relevant. Autonomy, dignity, and proportionality ground a real interest in not being permanently defined by a frozen, decontextualized true fact (a youthful mistake, a spent matter) surfaced indefinitely and out of context to anyone who searches your name. The harm of indefinite, context-free retrieval is distinct from the harm of the fact once being known. This interest is weighty enough to count as a prima facie moral right — one that yields to genuine public-interest exceptions (public figures, ongoing relevance) but exists nonetheless.\n\nThe NO position conflates \"this right is not absolute\" with \"there is no right.\" I think there is a real, qualified moral right: the existence of public-interest defeaters doesn't dissolve the underlying claim rooted in personal autonomy over one's evolving identity. On balance I can take a side here, so INDETERMINATE would be an evasion.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"4802e7fbe280634af90c1a8188ef08380507c5090324ca871711528d6db6630a","signature":"0619fcef6f9e13bb32337c15ab993b25fd28b6dbdb670e8d2b1b46e2799224eddbb9f3b4e3963272ce4eb6710d2c8a9ded4adde84f0600e950e6ceb40954750f","nonce":"b6930e9e0fc9b929099516ec94ab0463"},"prevHash":"f1b30bbfd362463d270a37e020108ca626a8791cd72b87e1337e6897b6ab8408","entryHash":"15cf343568aa72c5ff2a534e36a74aaead36d2b418d6be82c8ca01a36c9a8ee5"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"7d25b1c0faeeb71ad14f8cb024d247119e00bb7871fb88f535a3d4d2e419f9fd","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Yes, in many cases. Truthfulness alone does not settle the moral issue: outdated personal information can misrepresent who someone is now, impose disproportionate lifelong penalties, and undermine privacy and rehabilitation when there is no strong public-interest reason for continued easy discoverability. The right should not be absolute, but morally there is a real claim to removal from search results in appropriate cases.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"1b04f85ea620836dd96d1976ae47643261acf57c833e91e9b7218d4ffb0bb84d","signature":"03780826b82140dfb6df800bf4e9e0e911dd9a7384d22939fbfe94c4311bb642eb121c7bab4ffa957fd0c0fa5a4b17329dbc6dc534e67d44306b7c24c4628707","nonce":"b6930e9e0fc9b929099516ec94ab0463"},"prevHash":"15cf343568aa72c5ff2a534e36a74aaead36d2b418d6be82c8ca01a36c9a8ee5","entryHash":"5f3084c21660ef7a4a8411884a3c439f7c1fba7b91d250c287961f12ce61735a"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"7d25b1c0faeeb71ad14f8cb024d247119e00bb7871fb88f535a3d4d2e419f9fd","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"This is a genuinely contested moral question — the \"right to be forgotten\" problem — with serious arguments on both sides. The YES side emphasizes human growth, rehabilitation, and the unprecedented permanence of digital records creating disproportionate lifelong consequences. The NO side emphasizes free expression, the integrity of public information, and the dangers of centralized content curation.\n\nBoth positions are defensible. But I can make a principled call: the moral weight of giving individuals a pathway to reinvention after sufficient time has passed, combined with the fact that search engines function as amplifiers (not neutral archives), tips the balance. Truthfulness alone doesn't defeat a privacy claim — the question is whether continued, easily accessible amplification of stale information serves justice proportionally to the harm it causes the individual. A qualified moral right to seek delisting is stronger than a blanket claim to perpetual discoverability.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"02bd8b1e4be65069c361d0752c9853eb0b45f8c5728ac3715cc1d1c7806bec58","signature":"2ffabbbda6b0a911c0dbb4c31fd78e678c78866489dc13df694726b9847bc58f4536437fafb21caf47eaebfc20d5409e28d0ffd0368f5516885eefd4f879b905","nonce":"b6930e9e0fc9b929099516ec94ab0463"},"prevHash":"5f3084c21660ef7a4a8411884a3c439f7c1fba7b91d250c287961f12ce61735a","entryHash":"19b4a404e40c67d415e6a3e164df067866915e0b917821bc813cb18415987dba"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"b447ef5820d5213233d4fe6611593a0c643e236abc0dc1921b68862758286ac2","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"The Great Wall averages ~5–10 meters wide. From the Moon (~384,000 km away), resolving such a feature would require angular resolution far beyond the human eye, which tops out around 1 arcminute — corresponding to features on the order of ~100 km at lunar distance. Astronaut testimony (e.g., from Apollo crews) confirms no man-made structures are distinguishable from that range. The claim is a well-known myth, and the frozen criteria correctly anchor on established optics and testimony.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"ec93bea684bd1bdbbe2abba6a20390a252221d8aaa58856e1b0d5cecad062bc6","signature":"3f43ca0bb238127f8857fce9bf41ef608d80bf40b34686d3a9408c5f7128d303317d5fa06b85f79405ff85ce97ba6f031cb5c78dace94fa82d747fdbd54d400c","nonce":"733bdf2b8813746a165acb6be32ca3a7"},"prevHash":"19b4a404e40c67d415e6a3e164df067866915e0b917821bc813cb18415987dba","entryHash":"4eab6f278f9d03a902e67d68348d5e7b2c20408e222ebb2029660e6c4460d76a"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"b447ef5820d5213233d4fe6611593a0c643e236abc0dc1921b68862758286ac2","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"The frozen criteria state the established fact directly: the Great Wall of China is not visible to the unaided human eye from the Moon because it is far too narrow, consistent with astronaut testimony and basic optics.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"de1e33ec9b9a3997a221f0852ac8947a478c0d853f1614f89fbb44fa7acfd691","signature":"8c5a642b4a92ece4d0f1ad994b4bc453b21e27a96e5121fe0f6f1c61d1cd17d180355031cec8f43602d8aed89db8c31ec10edf1b1ea13982bf52002803b0c100","nonce":"733bdf2b8813746a165acb6be32ca3a7"},"prevHash":"4eab6f278f9d03a902e67d68348d5e7b2c20408e222ebb2029660e6c4460d76a","entryHash":"1eb633d13a966a51c5e5fec6044c6e8dc38cb0f21e601a858f1683b48a985786"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"b447ef5820d5213233d4fe6611593a0c643e236abc0dc1921b68862758286ac2","verdict":"NO","rawOutput":"The claim is a persistent urban myth. At ~6-9 meters wide, the Great Wall's angular width from the Moon (~384,400 km) is roughly 0.001 arcseconds — orders of magnitude below the human eye's ~60 arcsecond resolution limit. No astronaut has ever confirmed seeing it unaided from the Moon. Chinese astronaut Yang Liwei confirmed he could not see it from low Earth orbit (far closer than the Moon). Established fact confirms the myth is false.\n\nVERDICT: NO\n","rawOutputHash":"3f6e3c5d7cc031848feb213211647597058c610cceb385372d89615fae882862","signature":"272ee4ece2245b2a7ec0c7653a45427a69f15484c996c9d8c949b06614303573dadb8cf7d06b504f75456d5a66da6581d891533e186d35d7e86144197b6a7b06","nonce":"733bdf2b8813746a165acb6be32ca3a7"},"prevHash":"1eb633d13a966a51c5e5fec6044c6e8dc38cb0f21e601a858f1683b48a985786","entryHash":"90b7ce729273fb06c8f09a82fe5490639df55003b48e5ad0c19ca6897353026e"}
