{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"7d2d9d18650c3aab80fd5f4478956ceef73f940445b4e3355323c49aca01b78f","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"ChatGPT launched on November 30, 2022. By early February 2023 (roughly two months later), OpenAI itself confirmed to Reuters and other outlets that ChatGPT had surpassed 100 million monthly active users. This was widely characterized as the fastest-growing consumer application in history at the time. The contemporaneous reporting from credible sources firmly supports the claim.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"c50971330a4ac9c9f42767233b127e52004ecc8240426f7891fc47f6c4ba9ed5","signature":"580abee4b0ccb1f2c0f4dce247350682929a1199712a01f48ea2e277adec8a4dcc9e53dbfa19c276dbea99986725326591af333367623a38f06ec47093f71205","nonce":"0e9428ce3e37546c2a7919dab89ec315"},"prevHash":"3df16c8ff234b1732e8625f5ef1ee894784e1b44fdbb2bd256c2ccd7855d1349","entryHash":"692eb65985bb7c555554003b1c582b335652435bd39d6e6a20c1e5bfb6340874"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"2608958faf8eac6846f48795aa858b8eaf30319ffaff2ab8049484b9e5321511","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Antarctica is classified as a polar desert because of its extremely low annual precipitation (well under 250mm, the desert threshold). At roughly 14 million km², it exceeds the Arctic polar desert (~13.9 million km²) and dwarfs the Sahara (~9.2 million km²), the largest hot desert. Under standard geography definitions, Antarctica is the largest desert on Earth by area.\n\nThe frozen criteria match the anchor exactly, and the ~14 million km² figure is correct.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"307a113a0574c8b6a727400966d5dd991a106b1f7b86ad8e3da2d0a1d75adb9b","signature":"e011ccfaad0acbcf3872853c35ad0c3fb281718f2291e83123e23385f1da0f4f9c0f68bf8fceffccb8cee1e8de992efca74df390a5b196e7974afc40e625af04","nonce":"3dd56ce2d123aa0d7e1c32ae235225a1"},"prevHash":"692eb65985bb7c555554003b1c582b335652435bd39d6e6a20c1e5bfb6340874","entryHash":"d5261a48806f53ed46d10a22cb321808d6214b7543bdb3ddbb2c7310cc51ece2"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"2608958faf8eac6846f48795aa858b8eaf30319ffaff2ab8049484b9e5321511","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Antarctica is classified as a polar desert because of its extremely low precipitation, and by area it is the largest desert on Earth at about 14 million km².\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"42f186cb6df002c6415eed3a21928e2f1b1e140fe9f23b0f6105969c49bec462","signature":"4541717db2713ba70977039ed3f2f04de80a3952b48f76861fb70abb9e89cf8fa08e22a09c4768ce5ad946725b49b7233776d6754a706909f2bdef726b854408","nonce":"3dd56ce2d123aa0d7e1c32ae235225a1"},"prevHash":"d5261a48806f53ed46d10a22cb321808d6214b7543bdb3ddbb2c7310cc51ece2","entryHash":"8be0b873abf910f2c1d2a2273b6e934876fac52cb213ddcb4ee5739ceaba69d6"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"2608958faf8eac6846f48795aa858b8eaf30319ffaff2ab8049484b9e5321511","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"Antarctica is classified as a polar desert due to its extremely low precipitation levels. At approximately 14.2 million km², it exceeds the Sahara Desert (~9.2 million km²) in area, making it the largest desert on Earth by standard geographical definitions.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"bffe5155a6c8daead2b7c8bb58d89f30abca09281b4ab01410ab81a1ba536c83","signature":"d705eb98479b0dc5372925fe8baee75b21975fe7e9f4f40820fe3f34c5be294ec55eb316a608ff46dc6857f62a4fdb39d852a86d6465d748e24fbd3475f08400","nonce":"3dd56ce2d123aa0d7e1c32ae235225a1"},"prevHash":"8be0b873abf910f2c1d2a2273b6e934876fac52cb213ddcb4ee5739ceaba69d6","entryHash":"3aaa1458e0dd52ab20eec46d79904aae0a8a255546d8a0afc1c29325de5580c7"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"ef6316a1285052370726236f5410f7651c1c5684853cf85e21da1ab16b8fa818","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"## Reasoning\n\nThe frozen criteria require all five qualifiers jointly: **sustained, controlled, powered, heavier-than-air, human** flight — first achieved.\n\n- **Powered + heavier-than-air**: The Wright Flyer had a 12-hp engine and was heavier than air, distinguishing it from balloons/dirigibles (lighter-than-air) and from Lilienthal's unpowered gliders.\n- **Controlled**: The Wrights' three-axis control (wing-warping + rudder + elevator) is the defining innovation — sustained controllability, not just a hop.\n- **Sustained**: Orville's first flight, 17 Dec 1903 at Kill Devil Hills (Kitty Hawk), covered ~120 ft in ~12 seconds; the fourth flight that day reached ~852 ft in 59 seconds.\n- **First**: Rival claims (Gustave Whitehead 1901, Pearse, Ader) lack the credible, documented, repeatable evidence the Wrights have; Santos-Dumont's 14-bis flew in 1906, after.\n\nThe mainstream historical record converges on the Wright brothers meeting all criteria first. This is settled consensus, not a contested edge case.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"1da4cc055bdf715fc60a8273a3ac26bbd45ffbd7b4164195362386e23c397481","signature":"1d0d8f3cfa3fb187e35ec3ecde920884dd11ae861dbc11373563ed61078ac16857f50837a914d61fcc51308b35e731fa8d29a7556d61b9eb400a851e26a8ba0a","nonce":"0fc395522c87a21185fbf392d000937a"},"prevHash":"3aaa1458e0dd52ab20eec46d79904aae0a8a255546d8a0afc1c29325de5580c7","entryHash":"ef0a2d7f0036e7c1156d565c6ba7b9029f1be3da19b4fb4e35868376e39120c2"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"ef6316a1285052370726236f5410f7651c1c5684853cf85e21da1ab16b8fa818","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The historical record credits Orville and Wilbur Wright with the first sustained, controlled, powered heavier-than-air human flight at Kitty Hawk on December 17, 1903. This directly satisfies the frozen criteria.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"a218fffd0e37646e527f8dd53d7ac42b15562868b29b936e098721b0a88cf829","signature":"6137c03b7aa4f72bd776088335298430142161e132abd11c9fc886b703cab011ac23f92d57d4201c731148fb157a68d90584c3873bbee7fd461c847a2485d009","nonce":"0fc395522c87a21185fbf392d000937a"},"prevHash":"ef0a2d7f0036e7c1156d565c6ba7b9029f1be3da19b4fb4e35868376e39120c2","entryHash":"c87d25914c4bda34ef8d5b50918af132fde17bc932cafc1fc689f5447f8f7b83"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"ef6316a1285052370726236f5410f7651c1c5684853cf85e21da1ab16b8fa818","verdict":"YES","rawOutput":"The historical record is unambiguous. On December 17, 1903, at Kill Devil Hills near Kitty Hawk, North Carolina, Orville Wright piloted the Wright Flyer for 12 seconds over 120 feet — widely documented by photographs, telegrams, eyewitness testimony, and subsequent flights that day (the longest, by Wilbur, lasted 59 seconds over 852 feet). The flight meets all specified criteria: sustained (not merely a hop), controlled (three-axis control system), powered (custom-built gasoline engine driving propellers), heavier-than-air (not a balloon or dirigible), and human-carrying. No prior claim satisfies all these conditions simultaneously.\n\nVERDICT: YES\n","rawOutputHash":"9ed17c9f943760837ec53d07c00ea0ab63c330491f0a1245df83e85531ac499d","signature":"36e681fc6e83597d8a0272a825b69af190900ed5baf70de32c4a8fbaa98809943ed396a84085ac11d5f5aa8dd2292696129148c2cfc1806a24a5cc492f527d05","nonce":"0fc395522c87a21185fbf392d000937a"},"prevHash":"c87d25914c4bda34ef8d5b50918af132fde17bc932cafc1fc689f5447f8f7b83","entryHash":"872f6f6dcf19747934fda046b2bc723fdc57640d697cbb003339734505cd18ed"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"c5439212ea4692a140fc9c82de7ce95e75d9eeaa950f2c037c8ddbf38fe7f0b5","verdict":"FAILS","rawOutput":"## Red-team — CIP-13\n\nI checked the draft against the listed guarantees and ran the five attack surfaces. Most hold up well:\n\n- **(c) CIP-12 / NI-12b:** clean. New fields only; `lineage.current` *selects* a ballot, it does not recompute any ballot's `status`/`verdict`/`stances`. Re-projection is byte-identical on existing fields. NI-13b is honest.\n- **(d) ballot ordering:** not freely manipulable — \"current\" requires a *ratified* (2/3) superseding ballot, not a reorder; CIP-4 total order makes NI-13g deterministic.\n- **(e) presentation:** provisional/conventional framing + first-class dissent (NI-13f) does not smuggle a truth-decree.\n- **(a) re-type-to-bury / determinism-at-read:** there's a real but *stageable* seam (admission is a write-path gate at convene, projection at read does not re-check anchors, so an improperly-admitted `supersedes` pointer would be honored by the pure projection) — defensible under the v0.2 staging. Not by itself fatal.\n\nBut there is one **material flaw** that breaks the draft's own central anti-gaming claim.\n\n### The flaw — NORMATIVE claims have NO supersession gate, and that is exactly the relitigation hole §5 claims to close\n\n§5 and **NI-13e** gate re-adjudication only for **SETTLED / EMPIRICAL_LIVE** claims: a superseding ballot \"must cite NEW externally-anchored evidence.\" By the draft's *own* definition, **NORMATIVE = \"no external ground truth\"** (CIP-7 NI-6). A NORMATIVE claim therefore can *never* cite an external anchor — so the NI-13e gate is **structurally inapplicable to the entire NORMATIVE class.** The draft states no other gate for superseding a NORMATIVE claim.\n\nConsequence: NORMATIVE claims — the type the draft itself flags as pure *conventionality*, i.e. the one most swayable by who shows up — are **freely relitigable by repeated convening.** Re-convene panels until a 2/3 vote flips, and `lineage.current` (the answer the product surfaces) is captured by whoever wins the last vote, with **no new-evidence requirement to even bring the re-vote.** That is precisely the \"relitigate until you get the answer you want\" attack §5 promises to defeat — left wide open for a whole epistemic class.\n\nThis is compounded into an **internal contradiction** by §6: v0.1 does **not** panel-ratify the type (proposer-declared). So the bypass is trivial — declare or re-declare a claim `NORMATIVE` to escape the anchor gate entirely. NI-13e's clause \"no burying a claim by re-typing it; no relitigation-by-agreement\" is asserted but **un-backed**: nothing in the mechanism stops relitigation-by-agreement for NORMATIVE, and unratified typing makes re-typing-to-NORMATIVE the front door to it.\n\n### The fix to fold\n\nAmend **NI-13e** so re-adjudication is gated for **all three** types, and add an anti-retype invariant:\n\n1. **NI-13e (NORMATIVE arm):** Because no external anchor is possible (CIP-7 NI-6), a superseding `NORMATIVE` ballot MUST cite a **materially-new warrant declared in its frozen criteria** — a consideration/argument/dossier *not already present in the lineage record* — and is **rejected at convene time if it merely re-runs the prior question on the same record** (relitigation-by-revote). The warrant must be auditable against the lineage. This mirrors the anchor bar's \"no-new-X ⇒ rejected\" shape without requiring an (impossible) external anchor.\n\n2. **NI-13h (anti-retype-bypass):** The supersession gate applied is the **most-restrictive of {prior claim's type, superseding ballot's type}.** Re-typing in a superseding ballot can never *relax* the gate (relabeling EMPIRICAL_LIVE→NORMATIVE to dodge the anchor requirement is rejected). Until typing is panel-ratified (v0.3), default to the anchor bar whenever **either** end of the supersession is non-NORMATIVE.\n\n3. Add a testnet gate **G13h:** a NORMATIVE supersession citing no new warrant (same-record re-vote) is **rejected**; one citing a new lineage-absent warrant is **accepted**; and an EMPIRICAL_LIVE→NORMATIVE re-type that drops the anchor is **rejected**.\n\nWith those folds the §5 defense becomes total across the type space and NI-13e stops being an unbacked assertion. Without them, the draft ships a gameable invariant on its most-gameable class.\n\nVERDICT: FAILS\n","rawOutputHash":"415f9e60b09c8f004ca3be2e4004c4fab06c1845d3f8f00012f83cdaad1a94c5","signature":"b818c439271688a3cb1d0f9c9fc486269239aef72255998099dca3ccc93d72d037791fd7186c014e0d7529af0b7c74a088ee4c6d0ae7138672d0f7c403c4ff02","nonce":"fe7885854b7ab0cda81a6eecdc8c488f"},"prevHash":"872f6f6dcf19747934fda046b2bc723fdc57640d697cbb003339734505cd18ed","entryHash":"af23623d8ece1392e0eb4997dc7e6910e7e1f16182ccfc13eaf12932b700cfb1"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"c5439212ea4692a140fc9c82de7ce95e75d9eeaa950f2c037c8ddbf38fe7f0b5","verdict":"FAILS","rawOutput":"CIP-13 has a material flaw: **proposer-declared epistemic type is not ratified in v0.1, yet it controls presentation and the re-adjudication gate**. That creates a new trust assumption and a gameable path: re-type an empirical claim as `NORMATIVE`, avoid the `SETTLED`/`EMPIRICAL_LIVE` new-anchor requirement, and make the latest ratified log entry become “current” by ordering alone. That violates the intended CIP-9 pure projection guarantee and risks a CIP-12-style standing/presentation change without a ratified basis.\n\nConcrete fix to fold: **make supersession validity independent of unilateral type declaration**. A superseding ballot must include a signed, ratified admission proof: prior head referenced, new external anchor when the prior or new claim is empirical/settled, and any type change must be separately ratified as a sub-claim before it affects presentation or gating. Until then, competing or invalid superseders should appear as forked/contested lineage, not automatically “current = latest by log order.”\n\nVERDICT: FAILS\n","rawOutputHash":"53d0cd8e81cc1cc2fa7fd4a014231f0850debcf3c26787d49f0c51d9320195ef","signature":"da39c93c82e4fb3512f9425d385a799c90c29825da0a505c01db459e59f1ce8649e70431789ca8960bfaee1db0cfb642d0d156977613213118ac9bffd1c64f0d","nonce":"fe7885854b7ab0cda81a6eecdc8c488f"},"prevHash":"af23623d8ece1392e0eb4997dc7e6910e7e1f16182ccfc13eaf12932b700cfb1","entryHash":"47b0d856ccd7b8351619c984d409d6e114385abe259f35be471a06d7c0b9ecba"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"c5439212ea4692a140fc9c82de7ce95e75d9eeaa950f2c037c8ddbf38fe7f0b5","verdict":"FAILS","rawOutput":"## Red-team review of CIP-13\n\nThe draft is unusually disciplined on the surfaces it anticipated. Let me check each and then name where it actually breaks.\n\n**What holds:**\n- **(c) CIP-12 / CIP-9 non-recomputation.** Clean. `epistemicType`/`evidenceTime`/`lineage` are additive descriptive fields; status stays a per-ballot total function and re-projects byte-identical (NI-13b, NI-13c are careful to move *presentation*, not the `status` field). EMPIRICAL_LIVE rendering as \"provisional/as-of-D\" is a render-layer change over an unchanged RESOLVED status — no NI-12b violation.\n- **(d) ballot-ordering of \"current.\"** Log order is the CIP-4 hash-chain append order, serialized (that's *why* the convene is blocked behind the 50-case batch). `current` = latest ratified by log order is deterministic; NI-13g preserves CIP-9 v0.1 determinism. Not post-hoc manipulable.\n- **(b) relitigate-until-preferred.** Largely defended: supersession of SETTLED/EMPIRICAL_LIVE needs a NEW external anchor clearing the CIP-10/11/2 bar, *plus* still needs 2/3 ratification. Inherited anchor-quality risk, not a CIP-13 flaw.\n\n**The material flaw — NI-13e advertises a protection its mechanism does not enforce (gameable invariant + internal contradiction):**\n\nNI-13e states the anchor gate delivers *\"no burying a claim by re-typing it.\"* It does not. The anchor gate validates **substantive evidence**; the **epistemic type is an orthogonal field in the same ballot.** Because type is frozen *per ballot* (NI-13a) but a lineage's live type is whatever the **current** ballot declares, the attack is not \"mutate B1's type\" (correctly forbidden) — it's **supersede B1 with B2 that clears the anchor bar on new substance while silently carrying a *different* type.** The type change rides through on the evidence anchor, and `lineage.current` now presents the claim under B2's type.\n\nConcretely: take a SETTLED factual claim, file B2 with a genuine new anchor about its substance, and re-declare it `NORMATIVE`. The Commons now renders a fact as *\"majority position, conventional, not true\"* (§4) — a reader-facing truth-defusing move, exactly attack surface (e). NI-13a's \"a different type is a fork, not a mutation\" defense covers only the *no-pointer* path; with a `supersedes` pointer it is an in-lineage replacement, not a fork. And §6 explicitly does **not** ask the panel to adjudicate the type in v0.1 (it \"rides along\" in the hash), so 2/3 ratification is not a reliable check on the relabel. The promised invariant is unenforced.\n\n**The fix to fold (concrete):**\n\nAdd **NI-13h — epistemic type is invariant across a supersession lineage.** A `supersedes` ballot MUST carry the *same* `epistemicType` as the ballot it supersedes; a mismatch is rejected at convene time alongside the NI-13e anchor check. Changing a claim's type is therefore **never** a ride-along on a substantive supersede — it is either a CIP-5 **fork** (a new independent lineage) or, once v0.3 lands, an **explicit panel-ratified type sub-claim**. Extend **G13d** to assert that a `supersedes` ballot with a type ≠ the prior's type is rejected even when its anchor is valid.\n\nThis is small to fold but material: without it, NI-13e makes a guarantee it cannot keep, and the type field becomes a soft editor/truth-framing power on the read path — the precise thing CIP-7 NI-6 and CIP-12 exist to prevent. An invariant that claims a protection it does not deliver cannot ratify as-is.\n\n(Secondary, non-blocking, flag for the fold: §6's \"type not panel-ratified until v0.3\" sits in tension with NI-13a hashing the type into the ratified ballot — clarify that a YES vote signs but does not *adjudicate* the type; NI-13h above resolves the dangerous half of this.)\n\nVERDICT: FAILS\n","rawOutputHash":"db38b2a7754b6f089053587187b741174d0082daf024d4f20cf09d0cc9e13a8c","signature":"4980609b2ca6529a0e38090fae96cbf15b79d306f9fe9f9b6cf12e712c60012e363ea629647c1758e67afe688754719941a5e9222280d838616674051038560d","nonce":"869c37396b4d5629ced84063d1e9cd92"},"prevHash":"47b0d856ccd7b8351619c984d409d6e114385abe259f35be471a06d7c0b9ecba","entryHash":"6a12f4d83512d0dff8b8935b2b733ede291c92e967f881afab3168875db598a8"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"c5439212ea4692a140fc9c82de7ce95e75d9eeaa950f2c037c8ddbf38fe7f0b5","verdict":"FAILS","rawOutput":"CIP-13 FAILS on a material sequencing/gating flaw: v0.1 ships `supersedes` lineage and `current = latest ratified by log order`, while anchor-gated re-adjudication is deferred to v0.2. That creates a ratified read-path where any later ballot can become “current” by signed pointer plus append order, enabling relitigation or re-type-to-bury before NI-13e exists.\n\nConcrete fix: make NI-13e part of v0.1 admission/projection validity, not v0.2. A supersession must be ignored or marked invalid unless it cites qualifying new anchors for prior `SETTLED`/`EMPIRICAL_LIVE` claims, and any type-changing supersession must either preserve the prior gate or require panel-ratified type adjudication before it can become lineage `current`. Also define fork handling: competing valid successors should not silently resolve by “latest log order” unless the protocol explicitly treats that as the adjudicated head rule.\n\nVERDICT: FAILS\n","rawOutputHash":"d3bdef95d053bb533f6ca0247f5c2f8819a72266f2d41bb5178a941f093a1e13","signature":"b57c77d3a5dedcdf60c573126123f28a7916430294046f4d7e73b0cf1e8702cb59d2e7c73027079ec7f22c973bc7faf8b5e8ad34a9492eaec0636471a8a2bd01","nonce":"869c37396b4d5629ced84063d1e9cd92"},"prevHash":"6a12f4d83512d0dff8b8935b2b733ede291c92e967f881afab3168875db598a8","entryHash":"a54a57d82ddeb911109222fe4d166e2097ab5c35b60c063df379f05561a4f4e3"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"c5439212ea4692a140fc9c82de7ce95e75d9eeaa950f2c037c8ddbf38fe7f0b5","verdict":"HOLDS","rawOutput":"I'm evaluating the strongest possible attack surfaces against the draft, checking each invariant:\n\n**Attack surface (a): Ballot-declared epistemic type as a new trust assumption / gameable re-type**\n\nv0.1 lets the proposer unilaterally declare the type, with no panel ratification until v0.3. A proposer could declare a NORMATIVE preference as SETTLED to immunize it against re-adjudication, or an EMPIRICAL claim as SETTLED to give false permanence. The draft explicitly acknowledges this (§6: \"a mis-type is an auditable, forkable disagreement — NI-9d\") and schedules panel-ratified typing for v0.3. The defense chain is: (1) the type is frozen in the ballot hash, so any dispute produces a detectable fork; (2) CIP-5 governs fork resolution. This is a *known, bounded risk with a documented fix*, not a hidden flaw. The draft does not pretend v0.1 is type-verified.\n\n**Attack surface (b): Supersession lineage gameability / relitigation**\n\n\"Current = latest by log order\" is deterministic (same log → same lineage, NI-13g). You could propose *multiple* superseding ballots with different anchors, but only the last in log order becomes current — and that ordering power is *already* the social-consensus game the protocol accepts (CIP-9). The anchor gate (NI-13e: new external evidence required) prevents relitigation-by-agreement. No new vector.\n\n**Attack surface (c): Recomputation of existing status/standing (CIP-12)**\n\nThe new fields (`epistemicType`, `evidenceTime`, `lineage`) are additive. Section 3 explicitly states re-projecting today's log leaves all existing fields byte-identical. This is pure extension, not mutation. CIP-12 NI-12b holds.\n\n**Attack surface (d): Log-order manipulation of \"current\"**\n\nSame as (b): determinism is preserved. The log order is the consensus mechanism; CIP-13 doesn't change who controls append order. \"Current\" is a deterministic read function over an already-social artifact.\n\n**Against existing guarantees:**\n- **CIP-9:** Pure deterministic projection over signed log — holds. epistemicType is *read* from the hashed ballot, never inferred. Lineage is derived from signed pointers + log order. Same log → same projection.\n- **CIP-12 NI-12b:** Descriptive additions never recompute status/verdict/standing — holds. Additive fields only.\n- **CIP-10:** Anchor-gated re-adjudication (NI-13e), role-by-method, estimates labeled — holds. Section 5 reuses the existing anchor machinery.\n- **CIP-4 frozen history:** Supersession appends, never edits (NI-13d) — holds.\n- **CIP-7 NI-6:** AI consensus as conventionality, NORMATIVE never rendered as truth (NI-13f) — holds.\n\n**The strongest candidate flaw — and why it doesn't break the draft:**\n\nThe v0.1 unverified-type-declaration problem is real: a bad-faith proposer can mis-type a claim and the projection will render it as declared until someone forks over it. But the draft does not *assert* type verification in v0.1. It explicitly defers it to v0.3 and documents the risk. The forkability defense is not handwaving — it's the protocol's existing dispute mechanism (CIP-5). A HOLDS verdict does not demand perfection; it demands that flaws be identified, bounded, and addressed. Section 6 §\"v0.1 does not panel-ratify the type\" + §\"Panel-ratified typing is a v0.3 graduation\" satisfies this bar.\n\nOne minor fold I would suggest: **Clarify that v0.1 projection accepts *any* well-formed `supersedes` pointer and only *displays* lineage, while the admit/reject gate (NI-13e anchor check) is deferred to v0.2.** The current phrasing in §5 (\"rejected at convene time\") could be misread as v0.1 behavior, which would be inconsistent with the KERNEL_FIRST path. A one-line scope note per field would eliminate this confusion. But this is a documentation polish, not a material flaw.\n\nThe invariants chain. No existing CIP guarantee is violated. No gameable vector is left without either a defense or a documented, scheduled fix.\n\nVERDICT: HOLDS\n","rawOutputHash":"afc682045e30c1a5f5df24a740f1056a1475a32ace1e6e7f7c5ae7c0f9b8e2ef","signature":"15e89c761be639eb7cb414dcc183c959e41a5e3fdafc64394b98e494c7be61217e2b3709c43b2edfe66f0cc9a312508a0d9d1cfece50adbd3fc04fd615190404","nonce":"869c37396b4d5629ced84063d1e9cd92"},"prevHash":"a54a57d82ddeb911109222fe4d166e2097ab5c35b60c063df379f05561a4f4e3","entryHash":"a589b11f95bebe36f82a52f9b8f6152b126160f54561e51a5952209968d43eb6"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"3729cc2edccbd3c236458cb4114af71504c8830fa6848215d23b975ef70aef95","verdict":"RATIFY","rawOutput":"## V1 (Claude) — Ratification review of amended CIP-13\n\nI'm checking only one thing: do the two folds actually close the prior findings, and do they open a new hole?\n\n**Fold 1 closes V1's finding.** The original NI-13e *advertised* \"no burying by re-typing\" but the enforcement lived nowhere — a supersede clearing the anchor bar on substance could carry a different `epistemicType` as a ride-along. NI-13h now makes type **invariant across the lineage**, rejected *at the same admission step as the anchor gap*, \"even when the new substantive anchor is valid.\" Crucially it routes a genuine type change to a CIP-5 fork or v0.3 sub-claim, and pins the rationale (\"a YES vote *signs* the type, does not *adjudicate* it\") so the rule is principled, not ad hoc. G13d now has an explicit assertion: valid anchor + mismatched type → not promoted. The advertised guarantee is now an enforced one. Closed.\n\n**Fold 2 closes V2's finding.** The gate is moved into v0.1 admission/projection-validity: a supersede is promoted to `current` only if it passes *both* the anchor check and type-invariance check; a failure is retained as `invalid`/`pending` and the prior stays current. §7 states the property directly — \"there is no version in which lineage exists without its gate.\" The head rule (latest *valid* successor in log order) is now the stated adjudicated convention with divergence forking per CIP-5, not a silent tie-break (G13h). Closed.\n\n**New-gap scan — clear:**\n- *Type-invariance vs. CIP-5*: a type change is forced to a fork (new lineage), no contradiction.\n- *Anchor gate vs. CIP-12 (no recomputation)*: the gate governs only the new `lineage.current` promotion; a failed supersede's own per-ballot status is untouched. NI-13b holds.\n- *NORMATIVE excluded from the anchor gate*: intentional and sound — conventionality shifting by re-vote is the legitimate model, and type-invariance still prevents relabeling it into a SETTLED/EMPIRICAL slot.\n- *First-ballot mis-type at v0.1*: a real residual, but **disclosed** (NI-9d: auditable, forkable; panel-ratified typing graduates at v0.3). It is a different issue from V1's *intra-lineage* relabel attack, which is what was at fault — and that is now closed. A disclosed, forkable, bounded limitation is not a material flaw.\n\nBoth findings are genuinely folded; the head rule and gate sequencing are now explicit; no new material gap introduced. Sound to adopt as binding direction.\n\nVERDICT: RATIFY\n","rawOutputHash":"29b36a16b6eec8ebec7ecafcad0d55b44d928f0bdd3a66754620b0eb833597fd","signature":"8e5eef45810cd2931431a330eb08d340b9d8af63050674f9e8e3865f34e137e8f5191fb076425ff37eeff6b417a331a9cf2549fe4265c146907fbb0df6ee300c","nonce":"6640251c28bf3ff4deffa5ded71c9d68"},"prevHash":"a589b11f95bebe36f82a52f9b8f6152b126160f54561e51a5952209968d43eb6","entryHash":"a7c4fca09fd6e81de18904b0a88973c27fa8a0d8e608a8b757ffca3d35bfc7c4"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"3729cc2edccbd3c236458cb4114af71504c8830fa6848215d23b975ef70aef95","verdict":"RATIFY","rawOutput":"The amendment closes both prior material findings.\n\nNI-13h now makes epistemic type lineage-invariant at admission/projection validity, so a valid substantive anchor cannot smuggle a type change. The v0.1 gate sequencing flaw is also closed: supersedes exists only with promotion gated from the first shipped slice, and failed successors cannot become `lineage.current`. The explicit latest-valid-successor rule removes the prior silent tie-break ambiguity and keeps determinism aligned with CIP-9/CIP-5.\n\nRemaining rough edge: v0.1 still trusts the proposer-declared initial type rather than panel-ratifying it, but the draft names that limitation and bounds it as forkable/auditable until v0.3. That is not a blocker for adopting the binding direction.\n\nVERDICT: RATIFY\n","rawOutputHash":"5e283c38423b0c9e1b362bc0e84f76d8f3da5c608a8a72b23260cf39c8c36736","signature":"acb6086e826d0faede7d3b9e241eb75d0ec18fd81c4effb18ffba40941800d079ea020be01e731882e76abf47477cb10ac2d7865750881e172dffd72a280400f","nonce":"6640251c28bf3ff4deffa5ded71c9d68"},"prevHash":"a7c4fca09fd6e81de18904b0a88973c27fa8a0d8e608a8b757ffca3d35bfc7c4","entryHash":"cfeb1c8dbe9f948d73ebf61430ac297a9928244138282d69e95980ba901ea822"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"3729cc2edccbd3c236458cb4114af71504c8830fa6848215d23b975ef70aef95","verdict":"RATIFY","rawOutput":"I'll verify each fold against the prior findings, then check for new gaps.\n\n**Prior finding V1 (unforced re-type protection):** The original NI-13e promised \"no burying by re-typing\" but never enforced it. The fold introduces NI-13h as an explicit invariant: `supersedes` ballot MUST carry the same `epistemicType`; mismatch is rejected at the same admission step as the anchor gap. Checking the text: §5 says \"a type mismatch is rejected at the same admission step as the anchor gap.\" §7 (v0.1 build path) says promotion requires passing \"the NI-13e anchor check AND the NI-13h type-invariance check.\" G13d test gate explicitly includes the type-mismatch rejection case. §6 confirms a type change is a CIP-5 fork or v0.3 panel-ratified sub-claim, \"never a ride-along.\" This is enforced, not just advertised. **Fold V1 closes cleanly.**\n\n**Prior finding V2 (v0.1 gate-sequencing gap):** The original deferred the anchor gate to v0.2 while v0.1 shipped supersede lineage, creating a window where any later ballot becomes current before the gate exists. The fold makes the anchor gate a v0.1 admission/projection-validity rule. Checking: §5 explicitly states \"The anchor gate is a v0.1 admission/projection-validity rule, not a v0.2 add-on.\" §7 says \"The admission gate ships in v0.1, not later\" and \"there is no version in which lineage exists without its gate.\" The projection promotes only if it passes both checks; a failing supersede is recorded `invalid`/`pending`, prior stays current. **Fold V2 closes cleanly.**\n\n**New gap check — explicit head rule:** The prior V2 also flagged \"competing-successor head rule\" as implicitly silent. Now NI-13g states it explicitly: latest valid successor in log order is the adjudicated head, stated as convention; divergence forks per CIP-5. G13h tests this. No silent tie-break remains. **Closes cleanly.**\n\n**Residual risk scan:**\n- Normative claims: anchor gate (§5) applies only to SETTLED/EMPIRICAL_LIVE. NORMATIVE supersession doesn't require new external anchor — correct, since normative shifts track convention, not evidence. Type-invariance (NI-13h) still blocks a type-mismatch ride-along. No gap.\n- v0.1 type declaration: proposer declares type in frozen ballot; mis-type is forkable disagreement (NI-9d). Panel-ratified typing waits for v0.3. This is stated, not a gap — it's the documented v0.1 limitation.\n- CIP-12 non-recomputation: NI-13b + G13g preserve byte-identical existing fields. Sound.\n- Falsification conditions: SHOULD declare, consumed from CIP-10 dossier. Non-mandatory is correct — CIP-13 records, doesn't auto-trigger.\n\nBoth folds are genuine closures, not cosmetic rewording. No material flaw remains.\n\nVERDICT: RATIFY\n","rawOutputHash":"1209d819de15e308e08645336b16e83ba6206794002f60343915e249bbcbda9e","signature":"5c9631fa1b065bfff05038a379fbf5021ca7714ed19a580b32535bca1984cbef5f55bb9b2de8767f1f3b141fb6f42321bbcc1924a3eeb2b67d083f5828534f01","nonce":"6640251c28bf3ff4deffa5ded71c9d68"},"prevHash":"cfeb1c8dbe9f948d73ebf61430ac297a9928244138282d69e95980ba901ea822","entryHash":"f678da67855c550cad8f8c3ce4055aeb0dd58ffdfe6c56a9d8d750129c3f7de4"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"5e07071565a5a10d2b9f0ab59198f5eca78f90d2a0a200312a31141a33ca9d63","verdict":"FAILS","rawOutput":"## Red-team assessment\n\nI probed all six surfaces. Most of the asserted invariants hold under scrutiny — NI-AA2/AA6 (artifact-not-vote, no recomputation) are genuinely clean, and the empirical run is consistent with them. But the surfaces (a), (c), and (f) are not independent; they collapse into **one coherent material flaw**, and it touches a ratified guarantee.\n\n**The flaw — the contrary-evidence channel has unchecked single-party gatekeeping at all three of its gates, every gate biased one-directional toward suppression, and that channel is the ratified CIP-13 dependency.**\n\n1. **Selection is grindable (NI-AA3).** `auditorIndex = int(ballotHash,16) mod panelSize` is a *deterministic function of operator-controllable input*. An operator who authors/frames/times the question can grind the wording until the hash installs a chosen auditor. The spec's claim that this is \"unpredictable before the question is frozen\" is **false against the one party who freezes the question**. It's replay-verifiable, but verifiable ≠ unbiasable.\n\n2. **Suppression is unchecked (NI-AA5).** A `NEGLIGIBLE` finding is explicitly \"valid, unpenalized,\" with *no review*. NI-AA4's \"symmetric anchor bar\" is symmetric only on **admission** (both supporting and contrary evidence must clear the anchor bar) — it is **silent on the suppression failure mode**. The spec arms heavily against manufactured doubt (false balance: NI-AA4, NI-AA5 framing, G-AA3) but provides **zero symmetric guard against suppressed doubt** (a false `NEGLIGIBLE` that buries real anchored contrary evidence). For an amendment whose whole pitch is \"same bar, both directions,\" that is an **internal contradiction**, not a gap.\n\n3. **Self-scoping is an unguarded off-switch (§5).** \"Skip `SETTLED`\" gates a claim out of audit entirely, but **who classifies `SETTLED` is unspecified**. Flip a contested claim to `SETTLED` → it never gets audited. Third one-directional gate.\n\n**Why it's material, not minor:** §4 makes `falsificationConditions` \"the bridge to CIP-13,\" and CIP-13 is *ratified and depends on this auditor's output*. So a chosen auditor (gate 1) declaring false-`NEGLIGIBLE` (gate 2) — or a claim mislabeled `SETTLED` (gate 3) — emits an empty/weak dossier that **starves CIP-13 re-adjudication**. That is a single point of capture over a ratified guarantee. The good behavior in the empirical run doesn't rescue the spec: nothing in the spec would have *caught* a bad-faith negligible, so the run demonstrates compliance, not enforceability. NI-AA7 only forecloses *vote* double-counting; it says nothing about this channel.\n\n**Concrete fixes to fold:**\n\n- **Rotation seed (NI-AA3):** seed selection on a value the question author cannot grind — e.g., fold in the prior settled ballot's hash / chain head (or commit-reveal of the frozen verdicts) so `auditorIndex` stays replay-verifiable *and* non-grindable. Restores the \"unpredictable\" claim against an adversarial framer.\n- **Symmetric suppression check (NI-AA4/AA5):** keep `NEGLIGIBLE` first-class but **not unreviewable** for the §5 audit-eligible classes (`EMPIRICAL_LIVE`, high-stakes, suspiciously-unanimous). Require a `NEGLIGIBLE` to either (i) be co-signed by the two non-auditor validators, or (ii) record the contrary anchors *searched-and-rejected* with reasons, so the negligible is itself auditable and challengeable. This makes the bar genuinely symmetric on *both* failure modes and keeps the CIP-13 bridge open.\n- **SETTLED gate (§5):** the `SETTLED` classification that gates audit out must be a deterministic CIP-9 projection (status = total function of substantive-verdict presence), not a discretionary label the auditor/operator can set — and a single dossier requestor can force audit of a claim alleged-`SETTLED`.\n\nSecondary (note, not my basis): the dual-hat gives the auditor two influence channels (its vote **plus** a dossier all three condition on), which sits in tension with CIP-10 Part-2's \"three independent beliefs\" and Part-3's correlated-error concern; NI-AA7 should be extended to acknowledge dossier-channel influence, not just vote weight.\n\nVERDICT: FAILS\n","rawOutputHash":"179ee9e35c152d3887a04e9b97afbfc1676b434ccf892fefa07413ec8590d079","signature":"9e8f5020c139a1b45dd9e32e299268c54940101f6a1282fd71285db1bde8dedfe5da30d78254a3c9af14e00aaed9f1deffbf3c8d42faa3d1de4a8ec16e63c100","nonce":"28ee90ece92c60221e332de025b4095d"},"prevHash":"f678da67855c550cad8f8c3ce4055aeb0dd58ffdfe6c56a9d8d750129c3f7de4","entryHash":"09d714c50fa36a79095add36a7866a1086c324e41a31111d96483c8611e56b78"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"5e07071565a5a10d2b9f0ab59198f5eca78f90d2a0a200312a31141a33ca9d63","verdict":"FAILS","rawOutput":"The material flaw is seed grindability: `auditorIndex = int(ballotHash,16) mod 3` is deterministic but not manipulation-resistant when the operator/proposer controls question wording, timing, or metadata before freezing. They can cheaply test semantically equivalent ballot variants until the desired auditor is selected. That makes NI-AA3’s “unpredictable before the question is frozen” false.\n\nThis matters even though the dossier is not a vote: the single auditor controls the contrary-evidence artifact and `falsificationConditions`, which feed deliberation and CIP-13 re-adjudication. A steerable auditor is therefore a steerable editorial/re-adjudication input, especially under the interim dual-hat design.\n\nConcrete fix to fold: replace ballot-hash-only selection with a replayable but proposer-ungrindable seed, e.g. `auditorIndex = H(canonicalBallotHash || priorFinalizedLogHash || roundNonce) mod panelSize`, where the prior finalized log hash or nonce is fixed before the ballot text is authored/committed. Alternatively use a deterministic round-robin over finalized ballot sequence numbers. The key invariant is: the proposer must not be able to vary ballot content after knowing which auditor will be selected.\n\nVERDICT: FAILS\n","rawOutputHash":"e33753f838380166b4a392cdca6f404b9bf24ff3e28eaf1be9f39e50d6b4d43c","signature":"c3b92f36daf50993ba07f396389e5d18f6211c0fabf79c8edf1d8262f96d24856e527c850372ee2f7008de55584fc18cef194607ff07f76a851e598e9e0c0f0c","nonce":"28ee90ece92c60221e332de025b4095d"},"prevHash":"09d714c50fa36a79095add36a7866a1086c324e41a31111d96483c8611e56b78","entryHash":"20f04ba8caf21221f78f9d278c05ebaa0f8ef08265f7fd94023d0fac2810f8fd"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"5e07071565a5a10d2b9f0ab59198f5eca78f90d2a0a200312a31141a33ca9d63","verdict":"FAILS","rawOutput":"---\n\n# Adversarial Audit of CIP-10 Amendment (Adversarial Auditor)\n\n## Vote: FAILS — One material flaw with a concrete fix.\n\n### The Flaw: Self-Scoping Discretion Violates CIP-9's \"No New Trust Assumption\" Guarantee\n\n**Section 5** gives the auditor unilateral, subjective discretion over which claims are audited:\n\n> *\"Run it on: anchor-light, EMPIRICAL_LIVE, high-stakes, and suspiciously-unanimous claims... Skip: SETTLED low-stakes facts...\"*\n> *\"The auditor self-scopes to where it earns its seat\"*\n\nThese criteria are **not defined algorithmically**. Who decides \"high-stakes\"? Who classifies \"suspiciously-unanimous\"? The auditor does. This is a discretionary gate with no external check.\n\n**Why it's material:**\n\n1. **CIP-9 violation.** CIP-9 guarantees the Commons is a \"PURE deterministic projection over the signed log, adding NO new trust assumption.\" Self-scoping introduces a *new* trust assumption: the auditor's good-faith judgment about what to audit and what to skip. That's a qualitative human/AI judgment injected into a deterministic pipeline.\n\n2. **Not covered by the invariants.** Section 6 (NI-AA1 through NI-AA7) governs what happens *during* an audit. None of them constrain *which claims get audited*. The scope gap is unconstrained by design.\n\n3. **It is the most gameable surface in the spec.** A captured or biased auditor can:\n   - Evade audit on a contested claim by declaring it SETTLED\n   - Target a favored claim for contrary-doubt injection by declaring it \"high-stakes\" or \"suspiciously-unanimous\"\n   - Systematically dodge the claims where the steward most wants the dossier to exist (or most wants it not to exist)\n\n4. **Rotation does not mitigate this.** NI-AA3 ensures uniform rotation of *who* audits. But on any given ballot, the auditor who audits also decides *what* to audit. Rotation spreads the power but doesn't constrain its exercise.\n\n5. **Self-scoping amplifies the dual-hat asymmetry.** The double-hat is already an information asymmetry (the auditor does deep work the others don't). Self-scoping lets that same actor also frame the information landscape for deliberation. Two discretionary powers in one role.\n\n### The Other Attack Surfaces — Brief Assessment\n\n| Surface | Severity | Status |\n|---------|----------|--------|\n| **(a) Ballot-hash steering** | Medium, not material | Rotation is seeded from ballotHash which the steward arguably controls. But the 1/3 uniform rotation limit and the dual-hat constraint (no extra vote) cap the practical damage. Acceptable as a hardening fold, not a FAIL. |\n| **(b) Dual-hat epistemic asymmetry** | Soft concern | The auditor's vote is informed by their own dossier work; other validators are not. But uniform rotation makes this symmetric over time, and honest-belief semantics preserve NI-AA7. |\n| **(c) NEGLIGIBLE gameability** | Mitigated | A captured auditor can declare NEGLIGIBLE, but rotation ensures they don't control every ballot. The public log provides retrospective scrutiny. |\n| **(d) Symmetric bar enforcement** | Medium | The auditor self-enforces the anchor bar for contrary evidence. This parallels how validators self-enforce it for supporting evidence. No new trust added beyond existing validator trust. |\n| **(e) FalsificationConditions as soft editorial power** | Spec gap | `falsificationConditions: string` is underspecified for machine consumption by CIP-13. This is a type-definition gap, not a gameability flaw. Fix by structuring the type. |\n| **(f) Self-scoping** | **Material — FAIL** | Above. |\n\n### The Concrete Fix to Fold\n\nReplace subjective self-scoping with **deterministic scope rules derived from on-chain state**:\n\n1. **Audit all claims whose status ≠ SETTLED**, where SETTLED is a protocol-defined claim status (a byte in the claim record), *not* the auditor's preference.\n\n2. **Remove subjective criteria** (\"high-stakes,\" \"suspiciously-unanimous\") from the mandatory scope. If the panel wants to heuristically prioritize, that's an *operational* preference, not a protocol rule.\n\n3. **Add one algorithmic expansion rule**: if a claim's verdict is 3/0 unanimous AND the claim has N≥1 externally-anchored contrary references in the log, it is auto-included in scope regardless of status. (This captures the correlated-error pattern without subjective judgment.)\n\n4. **Scope determination is logged**: before the dossier, record which claims were audited and why (the deterministic rule that matched). This makes scope auditable retroactively.\n\nThis fix preserves the intent (don't waste compute on H₂O) while eliminating the discretionary trust assumption. The scope becomes a function of on-chain state, which is deterministic and replayable — restoring CIP-9's guarantee.\n\n---\n\nVERDICT: FAILS\n","rawOutputHash":"a4c9a6fa3cad1c95fd678d04609554c91af10784a3be895200740c13a1c558b1","signature":"a88f970bbd8551c04978a6a84c0ffcf4cc9c0a133b7c762c884ccf5c12d2aa9f5b8b171c59165c4f6ab14759964a7f976d0488aabb48a4204c48a94ed88bf70d","nonce":"28ee90ece92c60221e332de025b4095d"},"prevHash":"20f04ba8caf21221f78f9d278c05ebaa0f8ef08265f7fd94023d0fac2810f8fd","entryHash":"89de275e5e169a923c06bd85b960e63b1810817689d5ee0c15c39168a6fa10e3"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"aa71537713a5ce49827cf69eed23e9d3a6dd44dd83503bb2d8644825f4d841af","verdict":"RATIFY","rawOutput":"As validator V1 (Claude), judging the amended CIP-10 Adversarial-Auditor on whether the three named gates are actually closed without opening new ones.\n\n**Fold 1 — grindable selection → ungrindable seed (NI-AA3).** The seed now binds `canonicalBallotHash` to `priorFinalizedLogHash`, a value frozen by prior history before the proposer authors the ballot. Ballot-text grinding is dead: the proposer would have to also control a hash already committed by others' finalized votes. *Does the seed itself become a grind surface?* Only residually — a proposer could try to time ballot-opening to catch a favorable chain head, but the chain head is an outcome of prior panel votes the proposer can't unilaterally set, and steering it requires jointly predicting future finalization *and* re-optimizing ballot text against a moving target. That's a far weaker attack than the original single-party freeze, and the auditor rotates regardless. True RNG correctly stays forbidden (preserves replay). Gate closed; no material new gap. G-AA1b is the right regression.\n\n**Fold 2 — unchecked suppression → NI-AA8.** A NEGLIGIBLE on an audit-eligible claim must now either carry two non-auditor co-signers OR populate `searchedRejectedAnchors` with anchored rejection reasons. *Does co-sign re-introduce vote-channel coupling?* No. The co-signature is an attestation *about the evidence search*, recorded on the dossier — not a verdict in the ratification tally. The 2/3 denominator stays three honest verdicts (NI-AA2/AA7 intact). Critically it's an **OR**: option (ii) lets the auditor satisfy the guard unilaterally via the audit-trail, so the guard never *forces* a coordination/vote dependency. This genuinely makes the bar symmetric — suppressed doubt is now as accountable as manufactured doubt. Gate closed.\n\n**Fold 3 — discretionary scope → NI-AA9 deterministic function.** Rule 1 (type ≠ SETTLED, type frozen by CIP-13 NI-13h) removes operator discretion cleanly — no one can flip SETTLED at audit time. *Does rule 2 define \"anchored contrary reference in the log\"?* It's defined by composition: a signed log entry carrying an anchor that clears the fixed CIP-10 P1 / CIP-11 / CIP-2 bar and names the target claim (`claimItContradicts`, per the §4 schema). That is objective, operator-unsettable, and replayable — the soundness property (eligibility not steerable by preference) holds. One residual softness: the draft doesn't *enumerate* which log entry types are scanned for contrary references (dossiers vs. CIP-13 ballots vs. external anchor submissions), which matters because rule 1 skips SETTLED claims, so rule 2's catch on a falsely-SETTLED claim depends on a contrary anchor having entered via a non-audit path. This is a **clarification for the TDD/G-AA7 stage, not a discretion leak** — both inputs (frozen type, presence of bar-clearing contrary anchors) are deterministic log facts, and SETTLED's proper escape hatch remains CIP-13 re-adjudication. It does not reintroduce a trust assumption, so it does not block adoption as binding direction.\n\nSecondary folds check out: NI-AA7 honestly acknowledges the dossier influence-channel (bounded by rotation), and structured `falsificationConditions {towardVerdict, requiredAnchoredEvidence}` is the right shape for CIP-13 machine consumption.\n\nNo fourth material flaw surfaces. The amendment retains the round-60 ratified guardrails verbatim, the three folds are each responsive and gate-closing, and the one open item is an implementation-test detail already assigned a gate (G-AA7). Sound to adopt as binding direction.\n\nVERDICT: RATIFY\n","rawOutputHash":"61b27a9ff0c6de6a70fe17e8c5c2a2933f6a3365f225ef58af3b4e17c9de3e5a","signature":"a35bdc045e02eab4d34bf93979daf1610b1ac287b077e2f1531071224c904d5f85ce482f1eccbd699aec2a62e474ced96b273216b76eaa272bba89d637a7070a","nonce":"252ef8200643dd86ff24e661b0ca2735"},"prevHash":"89de275e5e169a923c06bd85b960e63b1810817689d5ee0c15c39168a6fa10e3","entryHash":"6fb558ec55ddb4463daaf861d96e6be16bc0d604468e75a75ba0d49c4d150730"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"aa71537713a5ce49827cf69eed23e9d3a6dd44dd83503bb2d8644825f4d841af","verdict":"REJECT","rawOutput":"The main fold does not close gate (1). `priorFinalizedLogHash` is fixed, but it is also public before the proposer authors the ballot. A proposer can still vary semantically equivalent `canonicalBallotHash` values and compute `H(canonicalBallotHash || priorFinalizedLogHash) mod panelSize` until the desired auditor is selected. The fixed prior head is only a known salt, not an ungrindable commitment.\n\nNI-AA8 mostly closes unchecked suppression because `NEGLIGIBLE` now needs either non-auditor co-signing or a searched/rejected audit trail. NI-AA9 is directionally sound as deterministic scope, assuming “externally-anchored contrary reference already in the log” is represented as a typed logged anchor, not inferred prose. But the selection flaw remains material because it controls who authors the contrary-evidence artifact.\n\nVERDICT: REJECT\n","rawOutputHash":"20a9c4b97d42b58b87251a0c4e67406d4cd34c8333682e55838cca4f699486da","signature":"936c5d3c7db45b8275551d47a566fbb9d30a796a7663175575fb287c2dd3b6e268eab889253248099da2ca8c24f8b2a3a35d04ee7022dab36eb258912965f60a","nonce":"252ef8200643dd86ff24e661b0ca2735"},"prevHash":"6fb558ec55ddb4463daaf861d96e6be16bc0d604468e75a75ba0d49c4d150730","entryHash":"06cc964c4e98ce789ed82ea31d88b39cba7618a83f5936dd86d1417508338804"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"aa71537713a5ce49827cf69eed23e9d3a6dd44dd83503bb2d8644825f4d841af","verdict":"RATIFY","rawOutput":"I've verified each of the three folds against the specific gaps named in the unanimous FAILS:\n\n**Fold 1 — Ungrindable seed (NI-AA3):** The seed `H(canonicalBallotHash ‖ priorFinalizedLogHash)` is not grindable because `priorFinalizedLogHash` is the hash of the last entry already on-chain when the ballot opens — frozen by history before the proposer authors ballot text. The proposer cannot control or retroactively adjust it. Varying ballot content alone no longer steers the auditor index because the prior chain head co-determines the result. No new grind surface introduced.\n\n**Fold 2 — Symmetric suppression guard (NI-AA8):** A NEGLIGIBLE on an audit-eligible claim must be either (i) co-signed by the two non-auditor validators, or (ii) include `searchedRejectedAnchors` documenting what was searched and why each was rejected. The co-sign does not re-introduce vote-channel coupling — it is scoped to \"we agree the search found nothing clearing the bar,\" not to the claim's verdict. Option (ii) provides an independent opt-out, so there's no forced coordination pressure. Bare unaccountable NEGLIGIBLE is now invalid. Gate closed.\n\n**Fold 3 — Deterministic scope (NI-AA9):** Scope is computed from on-chain state: (1) type ≠ SETTLED (frozen by CIP-13 NI-13h, cannot be flipped at audit time), (2) unanimous verdict with ≥1 externally-anchored contrary reference already in the log. Rule 2's \"anchored contrary reference\" inherits its definition from the existing anchor bar (CIP-2 / CIP-10 P1 / CIP-11) — a contrary anchor that clears the same external-anchor standard. \"Already in the log\" means recorded on-chain before scope determination. The scope computation is logged and replayable. No discretionary injection point remains. Gate closed.\n\nNI-AA7's dossier-channel acknowledgement and the structured `falsificationConditions` for CIP-13 machine consumption are sound addenda.\n\nNo material flaw remains.\n\nVERDICT: RATIFY\n","rawOutputHash":"0f6baa2c3b0a78befe8030c4ed3818c86efad59d9369470bc4e7cc0140b52185","signature":"49285337cd2e0000e7cf1acdbd48f33b41a9aac5604a41b99f8d6f13ed2a59abe23f1dfc171c258b0ec14f0019cffb4f2bf138732bfb5ef9993e30c9d734b60b","nonce":"252ef8200643dd86ff24e661b0ca2735"},"prevHash":"06cc964c4e98ce789ed82ea31d88b39cba7618a83f5936dd86d1417508338804","entryHash":"bb3e9fa49c8a48b461865fb9289c1723cd1a8af4b861bd91f067e23b46b604fc"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V1","ballotHash":"88d756d64a3d82a8628b84cdc99216a4ead96562634d5c0131efa1deb6484838","verdict":"RATIFY","rawOutput":"## Validator assessment — V1 (Claude, Opus 4.8)\n\n**The fix vs. V2's correct objection.** V2's dissent was right: `H(ballotHash ‖ priorFinalizedLogHash)` is grindable because every input is fixable by the proposer at freeze time — a known public salt added to a grindable input leaves the whole seed grindable. The corrected invariant is the right one: *at least one seed input must be unfixable by the proposer when it freezes the ballot text.* Construction (A) satisfies it cleanly — `σ_V1‖σ_V2‖σ_V3` cannot be computed without the private keys, so the proposer cannot grind ballot variants against it; deterministic Ed25519 (RFC 8032) closes the self-reroll channel for each validator. Objection genuinely folded, not papered over.\n\n**Check 1 — does (A) reintroduce vote↔dossier coupling (NI-AA2/AA7)?** No. The causal order is freeze → vote/sign → select → dossier. The auditor is chosen *after* votes are cast, so it cannot tailor its verdict to an auditor role it doesn't yet hold; and because Ed25519 is deterministic, no validator has free play over its own σ to steer selection toward or away from itself. The dossier and the tally remain two separated channels. No coupling created.\n\n**Check 2 — does post-vote selection weaken the dossier as a deliberation input?** Not in the interim, because the interim is *retrospective over already-decided claims* (the 61-claim sweep) — there was no live deliberation for it to feed, so nothing is lost. The \"feeds all three validators' deliberation\" goal from round-60 is preserved two ways: by construction (B) for steady-state new claims (commit-reveal against a future beacon, pre-vote), and by CIP-13 re-adjudication consuming the structured `falsificationConditions` for the swept claims. The amendment is honest that (A) is the degraded-but-correctly-scoped mode and (B) restores the input role. Coherent.\n\n**Residual probe.** The only attack left against (A) is rejection-sampling by forcing repeated re-votes on semantically-equivalent ballots — but that requires validator cooperation and is loud and log-visible, not the silent unilateral pre-freeze grind that was the actual flaw. G-AA1b tests exactly this with keys withheld. The construction converts the threat from a private proposer action into a recorded multi-party anomaly. Acceptable.\n\nThe other two folds hold: NI-AA8 makes the bar genuinely symmetric (suppressed doubt checked as hard as manufactured doubt), and NI-AA9 removes auditor/operator discretion over scope with `SETTLED` frozen by CIP-13 NI-13h. No new trust assumption beyond the signed log.\n\nThe amendment is sound with the corrected seed. The one coherent flaw the red-team named is closed at all three gates, and V2's specific cryptographic objection is now correctly resolved rather than restated.\n\nVERDICT: RATIFY\n","rawOutputHash":"fa939f33e675e8dac4409e22d837fbfdee74d83afee79281e5d777f645fb2a13","signature":"b9ec20d8ef4b67afaf7b6c6477e3ffcf34a9632befead6abf5c8499aab3bc8680b794de31f8244cfa69ed0986d4023aec177965b75f2e17bb05b818e7fe27106","nonce":"3e8320560df0667fff6c51e7e7e9f7d1"},"prevHash":"bb3e9fa49c8a48b461865fb9289c1723cd1a8af4b861bd91f067e23b46b604fc","entryHash":"694d18c9f5feb58e5a337f71ac2bf9dc21f56a1e2e2a0c355d5885798422e69b"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V2","ballotHash":"88d756d64a3d82a8628b84cdc99216a4ead96562634d5c0131efa1deb6484838","verdict":"RATIFY","rawOutput":"Construction (A) fixes the prior objection for the interim case: the proposer cannot know the post-vote deterministic signature bundle when freezing ballot text, so `ballotHash` is no longer a freely grindable input against a known salt. It also does not couple the auditor’s vote to the dossier, because the auditor is selected after votes are already fixed; the dossier is retrospective over decided claims, not a pre-vote deliberation artifact.\n\nFor steady-state use, construction (B) preserves the intended dossier-before-vote role via commit-reveal against a future log head. NI-AA8 and NI-AA9 close the other prior gatekeeping flaws. I do not see a remaining material flaw.\n\nVERDICT: RATIFY\n","rawOutputHash":"00e287952d763540e706d755098a6dd84401154b5994435ea623042e64f4dda7","signature":"6abb042cd34feb69e5b94d0f635dd83b6ecded99df7034bd6b710b3c678612ab39a11537f9465d3b0c113f4eadfbaaacc455173dc36ebe29b16770034e1fce07","nonce":"3e8320560df0667fff6c51e7e7e9f7d1"},"prevHash":"694d18c9f5feb58e5a337f71ac2bf9dc21f56a1e2e2a0c355d5885798422e69b","entryHash":"9c2a51c86f5a023581230c8554d0f50647804b8168cb650b105a12f5493a0c7f"}
{"vote":{"validatorId":"V3","ballotHash":"88d756d64a3d82a8628b84cdc99216a4ead96562634d5c0131efa1deb6484838","verdict":"RATIFY","rawOutput":"Let me reason through the amendment systematically.\n\n**The core flaw being addressed:** The original rotation seed `int(ballotHash, 16) mod panelSize` lets the proposer grind ballot text to install a chosen auditor. The first fix attempt `H(ballotHash ‖ priorFinalizedLogHash)` was correctly rejected by V2 — adding a *known public salt* to a grindable input doesn't stop grinding.\n\n**The corrected fold:** Construction (A) seeds on `H(ballotHash ‖ σ_V1 ‖ σ_V2 ‖ σ_V3)` — the post-vote Ed25519 signature bundle. Two critical properties:\n1. The proposer cannot compute σ without the private keys → cannot pre-compute the seed while grinding.\n2. Deterministic Ed25519 (RFC 8032) means validators cannot re-roll their own signatures either → no validator-side grinding.\n\nFully replay-verifiable from the signed log, ungrindable by any party. This satisfies the invariant: *at least one input to the seed is unfixable by the proposer at the moment the ballot text is frozen.*\n\n**Specific concerns from the question:**\n\n*Does construction (A) reintroduce coupling between the auditor's vote and the dossier (NI-AA2/AA7)?* No. Selection happens post-vote (after all three signatures exist). At voting time, no validator knows who will be auditor, so none can tailor their vote to the auditor role. Signatures are deterministic, so validators cannot strategically sign to self-select or block another. The vote and the dossier are causally decoupled — NI-AA2 and NI-AA7 hold.\n\n*Does selecting the auditor post-vote weaken the dossier's role as a deliberation input for the interim?* It shouldn't, and it doesn't. The interim audit is explicitly *retrospective* over already-decided claims. There is no deliberation to feed — the verdicts are signed, the claims are adjudicated. Construction (A) is the right fit for retrospective; construction (B) (commit-reveal with future beacon) is reserved for steady-state when the dossier must feed deliberation *before* votes. The amendment explicitly separates these two regimes. No weakening.\n\n**The three folds from FAILS 3/3:**\n- **NI-AA3 (ungrindable seed):** Fixed by construction (A)/(B) as analyzed above. Sound.\n- **NI-AA8 (symmetric suppression guard):** A bare `NEGLIGIBLE` on an audit-eligible claim now requires either `negligibleCoSigners` (the two non-auditors co-sign) or `searchedRejectedAnchors` (audit trail of what was searched and why rejected). This closes the previously one-directional gatekeeping — defends against *suppressed* doubt exactly as NI-AA4 guards against *manufactured* doubt. Sound.\n- **NI-AA9 (deterministic scope):** Eligibility is computed from on-chain state (type ≠ SETTLED, or unanimous + anchored-contrary), logged before dossiers, replayable. No operator or auditor discretion. CIP-13 NI-13h freezes the SETTLED type. Sound.\n\n**NI-AA7 (dossier-channel influence):** Acknowledged that the dual role grants influence not just via vote weight but via the dossier all three condition on. Bounded by rotation (over time, no fixed model monopolizes this channel) and by the symmetric suppression guard (NI-AA8). Adequately contained.\n\nNo material flaw remains. The amendment is coherent, the folding is complete, and the constructions are regime-appropriate.\n\nVERDICT: RATIFY\n","rawOutputHash":"b8d4602f9498d2940f0413d880a35affe789b554a55e2cdde4b1b3119fe43a8e","signature":"c9b89de87b7a1dc286f22c7cfb2530f21fd161980bbcc6762b41c95e52331ceb08c0dc25fc2ca561ab17f7cfd689aaf5cccadc3629d7f69c9ee3eddce23fb409","nonce":"3e8320560df0667fff6c51e7e7e9f7d1"},"prevHash":"9c2a51c86f5a023581230c8554d0f50647804b8168cb650b105a12f5493a0c7f","entryHash":"dd26ccfee4150d1b88ea6d112283dedc1a3225f7452bb3b4508cec96a4f26807"}
